<HEAD>Stark Returning To Home Base Saturday</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MAYPORT NAVAL STATION, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Navy is planning a
low-key welcome for the refitted USS Stark when it returns home
Saturday, ready for duty almost 16 months after being heavily
damaged by Iraqi missiles.
   Lt. Cmdr. Tim Taylor, a Navy spokesman, said the Stark will be
greeted by family members of the crew and local Navy officials
``but there will be no formal ceremonies.''
   ``It is planned as the routine return of a ship from an overhaul
period,'' said Taylor.
   The guided-missile frigate has been in Ingalls Shipbuilding yard
in Pascagoula, Miss., for the past nine months to repair the
missile damage that left 37 crew members dead in May 1987.
   The job was completed on time and was $52 million less than the
estimate, Navy officials said.
   The government of Iraq has promised to pay the costs of
repairing the ship and to compensate the families of those killed
during the attack. It will be presented a bill for the repairs.
</TEXT>
