<FILEID>AP-NR-09-02-88 0032EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Greece-Smog     09-02 0174</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Greece-Smog,0178</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Scores Hospitalized After Second Day Of Smog</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Half the city's taxis and privately owned
cars were banned from the Athens area for a second straight day in
an effort to dispel record levels of smog.
   The government said emergency measures would be dropped today
because of a substantive drop in pollution levels.
   The state-run National Center for Emergency Aid said 92 people
with pollution-caused heart and respiratory problems sought
treatment Thursday at clinics in the Greek capital. Another 24 were
hospitalized, the center said.
   The Panhellenic Center for Ecological Studies, a private
pollution monitoring organization, said 436 people required
hospital treatment.
   ``There was a temperature inversion that got really bad
Wednesday. It was like having a lid over Athens that kept the
pollution trapped underneath,'' said Dimitris Hadjidakis of the
Government Program for Pollution Control.
   About 15,000 taxis and half the city's 730,000 private cars were
banned from a 155-square-mile area, and Athens' 120 biggest
factories were told to reduce output by 30 percent during the
emergency.
</TEXT>
