<1ST_LINE>r a PM-SlayingMovie     09-02 0314</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Slaying Movie,0322</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Parents of 15-year-old Murderer Decide Not to Assist in Film of
Slaying</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CANTON, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The parents of a high school student
convicted of murdering his classmate have decided not to take part
in a movie about the slaying, spurning a $35,000 offer that will go
to the victim's mother, a newspaper reported.
   The movie will be dedicated to the memory of Shaun Ouillette,
who was a 15-year-old freshman at Canton High School when he was
beaten to death with a baseball bat in 1986, said Dennis Bogorad of
Dave Bell Associates, a Hollywood-based production company.
   Rod Matthews, also 15, was convicted in March of second-degree
murder in the slaying of his classmate.
   ``They (Matthew's parents) have no interest in the movie,'' a
family friend, Mel Ginsberg, told The Patriot Ledger of Quincy.
``They're not going to make it. They didn't sign anything. Mr. and
Mrs. Matthews are not out to capitalize on this.''
   ``They're just an average family and they don't want any more
damage done,'' Ginsberg said.
   He said the Matthews were upset when Ouillette's mother, Jeanne
Quinn, accused them on Geraldo Rivera's national television talk
show of accepting ``blood money'' and trying to capitalize on the
crime.
   Kenneth and Janice Matthews had planned to donate a $35,000
payment from the movie production company plus a share of the
profits to a psychiatric clinic where their son was held prior to
his trial in March, the newspaper reported Thursday.
   The family decided to forego the fee when it learned that
Ouillette's estate could sue to obtain the profits within three
years.
   Quinn said she has agreed to help make the movie and will
receive the $35,000 payment. She has said she is participating to
guarantee events surrounding her son's death are accurately
portrayed.
   Matthews was sentenced to life in prison and is eligible for
parole in 2001.
</TEXT>
