<FILEID>AP-NR-09-02-88 0455EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>d a BC-Theater     09-02 0366</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Theater,0377</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Girl Quartet Sings the '50s off-Broadway</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: No PMs Planned</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARY CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Chiffons and the Orlons were female
quartets, organized in 1960 to sing pop songs. The Taffetas are
four women organized in 1988 to sing 1950s pop songs at the
off-Broadway Cherry Lane Theater.
   The Taffetas, who pretend to be sisters, remind one most closely
of the Lennon Sisters, of Lawrence Welk reknown. Bubbles even
stream up behind the Taffetas during their encore.
   It's an evening for smiling in the theater. In their
pastel-colored gowns, with matching microphone cords and shoes, the
Taffetas look like they're going to make fun of the '50s. They
don't. They don't comment on the songs or update arrangements.
They're going for nostalgia, in which the audience can look back
with gentle, bemused affection.
   Those who don't remember the '50s can view it like their
parents' antiquated photo album. Those who do can try to recall who
originally sang the songs.
   The Taffetas stress naivete, talking a lot about Mom and their
home town of Muncie, Ind. They sing like crystalized sugar, only
once digging with gusto into a lyric, ``Where the Boys Are.''
   That song was sung originally by Connie Francis. The Taffetas
also draw extensively from Patti Page and Teresa Brewer. ``Mr.
Sandman'' _ that was by the Chordettes. ``Dedicated to the One I
Love'' _ the Shirelles. They don't choose only from female soloists
and quartets. ``Cry'' was a Johnnie Ray hit and the Ames Brothers
first enlightened the world about ``Rag Mop,'' which the Taffetas
take at a stately tempo.
   The singers are Jody Abrahams, Karen Curlee, Melanie Mitchell
and Tia Speros. Pianist Rick Lewis, drummer Mike Osrowitz and
bassist Alan Rubin accompany. The show was conceived by Lewis and
staged and choreographed by Tina Paul.
   Like the mixed quartet in off-Broadway's ``Oil City Symphony,''
the Taffetas take time to talk about their hobbies. They aren't as
clever as the ``Oil City'' four and their music isn't nearly as
varied. Still, an evening with ``The Taffetas'' is a pleasant way,
as they used to say on ``Your Hit Parade,'' to stroll down memory
lane.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880902-0017 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-02-88 0014EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Colombia-Guerrillas     09-02 0389</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Colombia-Guerrillas,0404</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>President Delivers Peace Plan; Rebels Kill 12 Peasants</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM WELLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Virgilio Barco offered
Thursday to initiate peace talks with leftist guerrillas, who
launched their second big attack in a week in northern Colombia.
   Barco introduced his peace plan on national television. He said
the talks should conclude with the dissolution of guerrilla
organizations.
   Guerrillas must stop their terrorist acts, human rights
violations, kidnappings and extortions before talks begin, Barco
said. He said a peace agreement should be reached by the time of
the next presidential and parliamentary elections, in March 1990.
   Guerrillas firing automatic assault rifles, throwing hand
grenades and setting fire to houses killed 12 peasants Tuesday
night, Gov. Jose Gabriel Amin of the state of Cordoba said Thursday.
   The guerrilla attacks appear to be an effort by the rebels to
force the government to open peace talks and make concessions.
   An estimated 30 guerrillas of the People's Liberation Army set
fire to a ranch, killed 10 peasants and wounded 15 Tuesday near the
town of Canalete, Amin said.
   Canalete is about 320 miles north of the capital of Bogota.
   The insurgents then attacked the nearby village of El Tomate,
setting fire to 26 huts and killing two people, the governor said
in a broadcast interview with the Colombian radio chain RCN.
   In El Tomate, a village of 600 people, the attackers left
messages painted on walls declaring, ``Death to the toads and
paramilitaries,'' survivors said in interviews with RCN.
   Guerrillas call army informants toads.
   Peasants in Colombia have long claimed that they are caught
between the army and the guerrillas.
   In dozens of interviews with The Associated Press, peasants have
told of being forced to sell food and other necessities to
guerrillas.
   Often the army hears of this and through threats or torture,
soldiers force the peasants to tell of guerrilla movements, the
peasants say.
   The guerrillas then return and kill the peasants, accusing them
of being army informants, the peasants have said.
   The People's Liberation Army and another guerrilla group known
as the Colombian Revolutionary Armed Forces attacked the town of
Saisa in the state of Cordoba on Aug. 23 and killed 12 civilians,
10 soldiers and two policemen, the Defense Ministry said earlier.
   Twenty-two soldiers and policemen were taken prisoner, the
ministry said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
