<FILEID>AP-NR-09-02-88 0113EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ShuttleRehearsal     09-02 0425</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Shuttle Rehearsal,0436</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Computer Glitch Halts Discovery Astronauts' Simulated Flight</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SPACE CENTER, Houston (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A simulated shuttle mission
designed to test the Discovery astronauts' trouble-shooting skills
was halted just before a mock landing because of a real-life
computer crash, NASA officials said.
   The five astronauts were preparing to end their 56-hour mission
Thursday afternoon by simulating a shuttle landing with a flat tire
when the computer shutdown cut the rehearsal short.
   ``I'm sure they'll be looking at it to see why it went down, but
nobody here considers it to be a big problem that the simulation
ended early,'' said NASA Johnson Space Center spokesman James
Hartsfield.
   National Aeronautics and Space Administration officials stressed
that there was no problem with any kind of computer used in actual
flight control.
   In Huntsville, Ala., meanwhile, engineers at Marshall Space
Flight Center said Thursday's fifth and final test of seals and
joints on the space shuttle booster rocket lifted their confidence
in parts redesigned after the Challenger disaster.
   ``Based on all appearances the test was a complete success,''
said Jim Thomas, technical assistant to the manager of the solid
rocket motor project.
   The two-minute static test firing, with the booster segment
anchored in a $25 million test stand, put launch-style pressure on
the redesigned joints.
   The seals are designed to keep internal hot gases inside the
twin rockets that help kick shuttles into earth orbit. The failure
of a joint in one of Challenger's two boosters was blamed for the
January 1986 explosion that killed all seven crew members.
   Before the computer crash at Johnson Space Center, officials
said, the Discovery crew handled all the simulated problems posed
to them during a dress rehearsal for their flight, which is slated
for late September or early October.
   The 56-hour mock mission began about an hour late Tuesday
morning because of an earlier problem with the shuttle simulator.
   But other glitches faced by the Discovery crew were intentional,
as commander Rick Hauck, pilot Richard Covey and mission
specialists David Hilmers, Mike Lounge and George Nelson were
placed in situations designed to test their ability to solve a
multitude of problems that could encounter on an actual mission.
   Shortly after launch Tuesday, the astronauts were forced to
alter their course and enter a low orbit after NASA trainers staged
a main engine failure.
   On Wednesday, Nelson and Lounge had to go outside the orbiter to
fix a stuck tilt-table needed to deploy a $100 million
communications satellite. That simulation was done in a water tank,
spokeswoman Barbara Selby said.
</TEXT>
