<FILEID>AP-NR-09-02-88 0128EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Amnesty-Concert     09-02 0590</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Amnesty-Concert,0610</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Human Rights Organization Launches Global Rock Tour</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAUREEN JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Amnesty International says it hopes to raise the
conscience of youth when Bruce Springsteen, Peter Gabriel, and
other rock stars launch a worldwide concert tour dedicated to human
rights.
   The six-week tour, which opens tonight at London's Wembley
Stadium, will go to 20 cities in North America, Asia, Hungary,
Africa, and Latin America.
   The $23 million extravaganza is to mark the 40th anniversary of
the United Nations Universal Declaration on Human Rights.
Organizers expect sell-out crowds but stress that raising money is
not the sole intention.
   ``This tour is not about charity, it's about justice,'' said
Jack Healey, head of the U.S. division of the organization, which
monitors human rights abuses and won the Nobel Peace Prize in 1977.
   ``What we're talking about is human rights and the seriousness
of the issue ... there's too much torture, too many people being
killed,'' he said.
   The pop stars taking part are both realistic and romantic about
playing for human rights.
   ``When I was younger I thought maybe you could pick a guitar up
and you could change the world,'' Springsteen, 38, said at a news
conference Thursday.
   ``I don't really believe that any more. But I do believe you can
save a life,'' he added. ``Someone comes to the show, they hear the
message, they hear what we are singing about, they go home, they
write a letter and someone gets out of prison early. That's pretty
good.''
   Springsteen is sharing a bill on the 35,000-mile tour with
Gabriel and Sting, American folk singer Tracey Chapman and Sengal's
Youssou N'Dour.
   More than 1 million people are expected to see the concerts
live, with televison audiences of many more.
   Ticket prices vary from rich to poorer countries _ $37.60 in
London and $3 in Budapest, Hungary. The final concert is scheduled
in the Argentine capital, Buenos Aires, on Oct. 15.
   The U.S. sports goods manufacturer Reebok has underwritten the
cost of the tour, and organizers say they hope it will break even.
   ``This is definitely not for fund-raising,'' said Healey, who
put together a two-week American tour called ``Conspiracy of Hope''
in 1986 featuring Gabriel, Sting and an Irish group, U2.
   It convinced him that rock music works for human rights.
Amnesty's U.S. membership rose by 100,000 to 250,000 in the year
following the tour.
   The organization has a worldwide membership of 750,000.
   Every audience member will get a card with the text of the U.N.
declaration on human rights. Spectators will also be able to sign
slips of paper saying they uphold the declaration. At the end of
tour, Amnesty plans to deliver these to the governments of the
nations visited.
   Amnesty's venture is the latest using rock music to raise
consciences.
   Irish rock singer Bob Geldof's Live Aid concert in 1985 raised
millions of dollars for the starving Ethiopians, and this year
thousands turned out to mark South African black leader Nelson
Mandela's 70th birthday with a London concert.
   ``The reason we have an appeal for the young is, I believe, the
fact that they are still able to say when they hear of an
individual's plight, `But that's not fair,''' said Marie Staunton,
director of Amnesty's British section.
   Gabriel, a longtime campaigner for Amnesty, said he agreed with
critics that a song won't change the behavior of a dictator.
   ``But we hope it can affect the way his children and his
grandchildren think. ... These are our target,'' said Gabriel.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
