<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Cuba-Angola     09-02 0514</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Cuba-Angola,510</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>US Worried About Offensive Against Anti-Marxist Rebels</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cuba is undertaking a major buildup of its
forces in Angola, raising the possibility of a joint Cuban-Angolan
offensive against U.S.-backed rebels, according to American
officials.
   With Cuban troop strength possibly exceeding 60,000, the
officials said Cuba may also be contemplating a cross-border strike
into South African-controlled Namibia, Angola's southern neighbor.
   The Cuban buildup, accompanied by an estimated two dozen MiG23
fighter jets, helicopter gunships, tanks and other equipment,
worries U.S. officials who have been hoping for a negotiated
withdrawal of the Cuban forces.
   Some officials believe that the Cubans may merely be attempting
to improve their bargaining position at four-way talks aimed at
achieving both a Cuban withdrawal and Namibian independence from
South Africa.
   But one official, speaking only on condition of anonymity, said
the sheer numbers of Cubans and equipment involved in the buildup
suggest that the Cubans are thinking more of a military offensive
than a withdrawal.
   ``The numbers are frightening,'' the official said.
   The buildup began several weeks ago with about one ship a week
loaded with troops and equipment undertaking the trans-Atlantic
crossing. If the U.S. estimates are correct, Cuba has increased its
troop strength by about 25,000 since last November.
   The four-way talks involve officials from Cuba, Angola and South
Africa, with the United States serving as mediator. The next round
will take place next week in the Congolese capital of Brazzaville.
   South Africa concluded the withdrawal of its troops from Angola
earlier this week and has said it will begin a withdrawal later
this year from Namibia provided Cuba agrees to an early pullout
from Angola.
   A South African pullback would set in motion a United Nations
plan for the establishment of an independent government in the
territory.
   The officials said the South Africans decided to withdraw from
Angola after recognizing that the Cuban buildup had changed the
power balance in the southern part of the country, leaving South
African troops vulnerable.
   They said South Africans may not even be a match for Cuban
forces in Namibia, where Pretoria has been the colonial power for
73 years. One official said Cuba has 50 percent more tanks in
Angola than South Africa has in its entire inventory.
   As one official described it, Cuban President Fidel Castro ``has
his eye on the history books,'' possibly hoping to free Namibia
from South African control and to help defeat the anti-communist
insurgency that has been operating in Angola for 13 years.
   The UNITA insurgency has received U.S. military support for the
past three years and controls much of the southeastern part of the
country.
   The four-way talks were convened last May in London at the
suggestion of U.S. Assistant Secretary of State Chester Crocker. At
the time, officials said the parties appeared eager for a
negotiated settlement, realizing that a military solution was
impossible.
   But some officials now believe that Cuba has had in mind a
military solution all along, and they say that theory has been
bolstered by the Cuban buildup.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
