<1ST_LINE>r p PM-OnTheQuayleTrail     09-02 0499</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-On The Quayle Trail,500</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Snippets From The Candidate's Southern Swing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN PUTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A mild protest or two is not out of the
ordinary at Sen. Dan Quayle's campaign appearances. Allegations
that the senator pulled strings to get into the National Guard
during the Vietnam War have prompted signs like ``War Wimp'' and
``Sissy Rich Boy'' to pop up here and there.
   But reporters who follow the Republican vice presidential
nominee have noticed that his hearing and vision are selective when
it comes to such displays, as he proved Thursday at one stop in
Arkansas, home of the University of Arkansas' Razorback Hogs.
   When Quayle walked to his car for the next appearance, a voice
from the crowd loudly shouted ``Chicken Hawk!''
   Quayle, apparently not hearing the taunt correctly, smiled and
gave a thumbs-up signal.
   ``Go Hogs!'' Quayle shouted back.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Dan Quayle has taken to referring sarcastically to
reporters as ``my newfound friends in the news media.'' But after
two weeks on the campaign trail, he still had not met the reporters
who covered him.
   Then, as Quayle's campaign plane flew Wednesday to Baton Rouge,
La., a particularly noisy group of photographers in the back of the
plane started a chant, in parody of a daytime television game show
announcer: ``Sen. Quayle, come on down.''
   Moments later, apparently by coincidence, Quayle came back to
meet the press.
   The session was, of course, off the record.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   There are campaign songs and campaign songs, but the one that
was piped over the public address system on Sen. Dan Quayle's plane
recently was loudly booed by an unappreciative audience of
reporters.
   Sung by Sylvia Johns, the song, entitled ``George Bush's Song,''
had an unmemorable tune and this sampling of lyrics:
   ``From Texas to the White House
   Is where Bush is gonna be
   Loyal to his country for American unity
   We the people of the USA
   Need a strong leader in the White House today
   It's Bush, George Bush
   He's everybody's All American.''
   The song was recorded in Baton Rouge, and complimentary 45 rpm
copies were distributed to the press, courtesy of Bengal Chemical
Inc., which the record jacket notes is a manufacturer of Bengal
Roach Spray.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   It was meant as a display of Dan Quayle's youthful athleticism,
but it took several tries for things to connect.
   Quayle helped the football team at Brandon High School in
Jackson, Miss., run a few scrimmage plays Thursday, taking the role
of quarterback for himself. The first pass was badly underthrown.
The second made it to the receiver, but glanced off his fingertips.
On third down, Quayle called for a new receiver and sent him out
for a 15-yard pass. That time, the two connected.
   Quayle, whose first two weeks as the GOP vice presidential
career were about as rocky as his passing, acknowledged that his
first pass was ``lousy.''
   ``It's just like a campaign,'' he said. ``It's getting better
and better.''
</TEXT>
