<1ST_LINE>r w PM-SEC-Harassment     09-02 0280</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-SEC-Harassment,280</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>SEC Pays $145,000 in Another Sexual Harassment Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Securities and Exchange Commission paid
$145,000 to settle claims by a former employee that she had been
sexually harassed on the job, an SEC spokeswoman says.
   The payment was made late last month, with $112,500 going to the
former employee and $32,500 to her attorney, SEC spokeswoman Mary
McCue said Thursday night.
   The Washington Post in today's editions identified the woman as
Veronica Awkard.
   The payment came just months after a federal judge approved a
settlement ordering a promotion, back pay and compensation for
psychological counseling for Catherine Broderick, an SEC attorney
who the judge said had been forced to work in a ``sexually
hostile'' atmosphere at the agency's Washington regional office.
   Ms. McCue, who declined to discuss details of the most recent
case, said the two cases were unrelated.
   The Post said Awkard's allegations included reports of unwanted
physical advances and verbal invitations for sexual liaisons. It
said she left the SEC in July 1983.
   The Post said Ms. Awkard, then branch chief in the agency's
Office of Applications and Report Services, filed a sexual
harassment complaint in May 1983.
   Her complaint alleged ``the sexual harassment of me is a pattern
and practice of treatment ... resulting in females being denied or
awarded job benefits, including promotions, depending upon their
acquiescence with the supervisors' or managers' sexual approaches.''
   In June, District Judge John H. Pratt approved the settlement
worked out by attorneys for the SEC and Broderick. Pratt found that
in addition to working in a sexually hostile environment, Broderick
had been passed over for promotions and given a negative evaluation
because she complained.
</TEXT>
