<1ST_LINE>u w AM-YonkersDeseg 1stLd-Writethru a0430 09-02 0485</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Yonkers Deseg, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0430,460</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Supreme Court Stays Contempt Citations Against Four Yonkers
Officials</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: SUBS 8th graf pvs, The council, with 4 grafs to show
councilmen faced jail and UPDATE with reaction from Yonkers mayor
and Cuomo. Picks up 9th graf, Federal Judge</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court on Thursday night stayed a
lower court ruling that had upheld contempt citations against four
Yonkers, N.Y., city councilmen for fighting a federally ordered
desegregation plan, a high court spokeswoman said.
   But in a related decision, the high court refused to stay a
contempt ruling against the city.
   The court granted stays to council members Henry Spallone,
Nicholas Longo, Edward Fagan and Peter Chema, court spokeswoman
Toni House said.
   ``The court has granted the stay for the four council members''
until they have had time to ask the court formally to fully review
their cases, Ms. House said.
   ``The application so far as the city of Yonkers is concerned has
been denied,'' she added.
   She said the entire court considered the applications, and
Justices Thurgood Marshall and William Brennan filed a 12-page
dissent.
   On Friday, a federal appeals panel upheld a judge's contempt
finding but gave the councilmen and Yonkers a week to seek an
emergency stay from the Supreme Court before reinstating the
penalties.
   The council members had faced $500-a-day fines and jail, and the
city could be hit with $1 million a day in penalties.
   In Yonkers, Mayor Nicholas Wasicsko said early Friday, ``It
seems at first curious that the fines would be stayed against the
councilmen yet run against the city. It troubles me. The treasury
of the city is going to be exposed and the taxpayers of the city
are going to feel the burden.
   ``One thing it denies is the political martyrdom of the
councilmen. They were slated to go to jail on Sunday. Their
personal fines have ceased. But the city is going to plummet to
bankruptcy. So their onus is their duty to the city. Their personal
political martyrdom has been denied them.''
   In Albany, N.Y., Tom Conroy, a spokesman for Gov. Mario Cuomo,
said, ``The governor will review the decision and confer with his
council. We won't have a comment before then.''
   Federal Judge Leonard Sand had found them in contempt Aug. 2,
the day after the council first rejected the court-ordered
desegregation plan by a 4-3 vote.
   The council members have refused three times to change their
votes on a zoning amendment needed to carry out a housing plan that
the council had accepted last January.
   Sand ordered the plan to remedy what he determined in a 1985
ruling to have been 40 years of deliberate segregation in housing
and education in the city.
   The plan calls for 200 low-income public housing units to be
built in the predominantly white east side of Yonkers, with 800
moderate-income apartments to be built throughout the city.
</TEXT>
