<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Flight-BombHoax     09-02 0181</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Flight-Bomb Hoax,0186</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bomb Threat on Northwest Flight Was Hoax, Officials Say</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROMULUS, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Northwest Airlines jet that returned to
Detroit Metropolitan Airport after a bomb threat was called in was
evacuated, but no explosives were found on the plane, officials
said.
   The threat to Flight 333, bound for Los Angeles, was phoned into
the airline's reservation center here Thursday and relayed to the
control tower, said Nancy Mouradian, a spokeswoman for the Wayne
County Sheriff's Department.
   After the DC-10 landed and its 255 passengers were evacuated,
the plane was moved to an inactive runway, where explosive-sniffing
dogs and the sheriff department's bomb squad searched it. No one
was injured.
   Mouradian said she didn't know who made the threat or how much
time elapsed between the flight's takeoff and return.
   Bob Gibbons, a spokesman for the Eagan, Minn.-based airline,
said all information about the incident was being withheld.
   ``The airline has a standard reaction to bomb hoaxes. That is
not to respond to them unless they turn out to be something other
than a hoax,'' Gibbons said.
</TEXT>
