<DOCNO> AP880902-0041 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-02-88 0159EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Japan-QuakeDrills     09-02 0258</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Quake Drills,0263</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nine Million Rehearse Evacuation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nine million Japanese climbed down ladders, ran
through smoke-filled tunnels and wheeled bedridden patients to
safety as the country rehearsed for a massive earthquake that
experts say could strike at any time.
   Thursday was the 65th anniversary of the Great Kanto Earthquake,
when a temblor estimated at 7.9 on the Richter scale jolted the
crowded plain surronding Tokyo and killed 140,000 people.
   Authorities hoping to hold down casualties in the event of
another massive quake mobilized schoolchildren, civic groups and
office workers for the tenth disaster prevention drill.
   Fire departments and officials from the National Land Agency and
local governments coordinated evacuation scenarios in the aftermath
of two imaginary temblors _ a second Great Kanto Earthquake of
magnitude 7.9 and a jolt along the heavily populated, 170-mile
Tokai belt linking Tokyo and Nagoya that would measure 8.0 on the
Richter scale.
   ``The number of participants doesn't change much, but each year
we've been getting better and better at holding the drill,'' said
Takanori Kobiki, head of the National Land Agency's Disaster
Prevention Operations.
   Scientists say Japan is likely to suffer a tremendous earthquake
within the next 20 years.
   The Richter scale is a measure of ground motion as recorded on
seismographs.
   An earthquake of 3.5 on the Richter scale can cause slight
damage in the local area, 4 moderate damage, 5 considerable damage,
6 severe damage. A 7 reading is a ``major'' earthquake, capable of
widespread heavy damage; 8 is a ``great'' quake, capable of
tremendous damage.
</TEXT>
