<FILEID>AP-NR-09-02-88 0200EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-VehicleRollovers     09-02 0470</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Vehicle Rollovers,470</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Plans Research on Vehicle Rollovers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM BOVEE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The National Highway Traffic Safety
Administration says it will conduct research aimed at coming up
with rules to protect the drivers of light vehicles from
unreasonable risk of rollover.
   The NHTSA decision was announced Thursday in a case centering on
the Suzuki Samurai, under attack from consumer groups for an
alleged tendency to roll over in curves.
   The safety board rejected a petition by the Center for Auto
Safety, a consumers group that wanted a recall of the Samurai,
saying the Samurai is no more likely to roll than other comparable
vehicles. The agency, however, approved a petition from the
Consumers Union to study the light vehicle rollover problem in
general.
   Suzuki responded to the decision by saying it showed that the
allegations against the Samurai were unfounded.
   ``The federal government's action supports Suzuki's claim that
the Samurai is safe and should put to rest the inaccurate and
misleading attacks on the vehicle,'' said a statement from the
Japanese company's U.S. subsidiary, American Suzuki Motor Corp. in
Brea, Calif.
   About 169,000 Samurais have been sold in the United States,
Suzuki said.
   The Center for Auto Safety, which is often at odds with
automakers and their regulators, said the decision skirted the
issue.
   ``If this were the law, then the Justice Department would refuse
to prosecute one mass murderer because there are other mass
murderers,'' the center said, citing reports of 113 rollovers, 120
injuries and 25 deaths involving the Samurai.
   The center said it would ask NHTSA to reconsider its decision.
   NHTSA said it granted the Consumers Union petition because that
request did not specify a single cause of Samurai rollovers and
acknowledged that factors other than the stability of the vehicles
lay behind some of the accidents.
   Many of the instances of rollover involving the Samurai happened
when the driver had been drinking, was unfamiliar with the vehicle,
or was attempting a risky maneuver, NHTSA said.
   NHTSA listed 10 research projects into vehicle stability it has
completed or plans to complete, but said the research does not
guarantee that new regulations will be issued.
   In rejecting the center's request for a Samurai recall, NHTSA
said the Samurai's rollover rate, based on a study of 1986- and
1987-model vehicles, was six per 100,000 vehicles. It said the Ford
Bronco II, by comparison, had a rollover rate of about 19 per
100,000 vehicles. The General Motors S-10 Blazer and S-15 Jimmy had
rollover rates identical to the Samurai's.
   The Consumers Union in June urged a ban on the Samurai and, in
its magazine Consumer Reports, rated the vehicle ``not
acceptable,'' the first such rating given an automobile in 10 years.
   The ensuing publicity cut into Samurai sales and resulted in
several lawsuits.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
