<HEAD>Quotes From the Presidential Campaign Trail</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are some comments Thursday from the
presidential campaign trail:
   
   GEORGE BUSH, on a trip to dramatize the pollution in Boston
Harbor: ``Two hundred years ago tea was spilled in the Boston
harbor in the name of liberty. If tea were spilled in the Boston
Harbor today, it would dissolve in the residue of my opponent's
neglect and delay.''
   
   MICHAEL DUKAKIS, saying Bush had a hand in the Reagan
administration's elimination of remedial math and reading programs
for poor children: ``Where was George while all this was going on?
Where was the man who now says he wants to be the `education
president?' He was playing hooky. He was nowhere to be found.''
   
   DAN QUAYLE, touring a Timex plant in Little Rock, Ark.: ``I'm
still ticking. I'm going to continue to talk about the issues. It
is an upbeat campaign.''
   
   JESSE JACKSON, saying why he will campaign hard between now and
the Nov. 8 election: ``I would hate to wake up on the morning of
Nov. 9 and hate to think that we lost by the lack of my work.''
   
   PAUL BROUNTAS, Dukakis campaign chairman, after failing to agree
with Bush forces on a schedule for debates between the presidential
and vice presidential candidates: ``The American people ... should
not have to choose between watching the nominees debate world
events and watching the World Series.''
