<2ND_LINE>PM-Toxic Ship,0244</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>French To Refuel, Resupply Ship Carrying Toxic Waste</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHERBOURG, France (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   French authorities said a ship carrying
toxic waste and rejected by half a dozen countries will be
resupplied and refueled at sea but will not be allowed to enter a
French port.
   The cargo ship Karin B, loaded with 2,100 tons of industrial
solvents, was denied permission to enter French waters and dock at
Le Havre, at the mouth of the Seine River.
   The ship anchored off the Normandy coast, where it was being
closely watched by two French naval vessels, officials said
Thursday.
   As a storm blew in the English Channel, with winds whipping at
more than 60 mph, the Karin B took up a position 12 nautical miles
off the coast, said officials at France's Operational Search Center
for Rescue and Salvage in Jobourg.
   According to the martime affairs office in Cherbourg, ``the
commander of the ship wanted to come to Le Havre to resupply before
leaving for the sea, but the French authorities proposed
resupplying at sea in the next few hours.''
   The Karin B's wastes, originally from Italy, were dumped
secretly and illegally in Nigeria, then removed in two shiploads by
contractors for Italian authorities.
   The German-owned ship has been refused permission to unload its
cargo in Britain, Spain, West Germany and the Netherlands. The
Italian government says it does not have the technology to dispose
of the toxic solvents.
</TEXT>
