<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Mexico-PlaneCrash     09-02 0284</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Mexico-Plane Crash,0292</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bodies Recovered From Air Crash</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LAZARO CARDENAS, Mexico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Helicopters delivered the remains
of 21 people killed in a fiery commuter plane crash to friends and
relatives waiting at the airport in this Pacific port.
   About 300 people gathered Thursday night to identify the
victims, who died when the aircraft plunged into the western Sierra
Madre mountains Wednesday, said Victor a Bauza Orosco, a Red Cross
worker.
   ``It's difficult. The bodies are badly deformed, and some
arrived in pieces, only limbs. Others are thoroughly burned,'' he
said.
   Rescue workers said all 21 people aboard the twin-engine plane _
including 18 passengers and three crew members _ died when the
plane fell into the rocky, heavily forested terrain near the town
of Arteaga, about 200 miles southwest of Mexico City.
   Aviation officials said the Brazilian-made Bandeirante aircraft
of the Aerofederal line disappeared after leaving Uruapan, about
180 miles west of Mexico City, for the 100-mile flight to Lazaro
Cardenas.
   Gen. Carmelo Teran, chief of staff of the 21st Military Zone _
whose members participated in the rescue _ said the bodies and
wreckage were found within a radius of about 50 yards.
   He said the plane crashed at the juncture of two mountains. Most
of the passengers were from Uruapan.
   A helicopter of the Federal Electricity Commission spotted the
wreckage at 9 p.m. Wednesday, but rescuers could not fly into the
area until late Thursday morning, after trees were cleared in the
dense forest. Teran said rescuers climbed two or three hours
through the rugged terrain to reach the crash site, which was three
to four miles from the nearest road.
   He said they also were slowed down by rain.
</TEXT>
