<HEAD>Six Killed in Desert Military Helicopter Crash</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BARSTOW, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A California Air National Guard
helicopter on a training exercise crashed and burned on a ridge of
a Mojave Desert mountain range, killing all six crew members,
authorities said.
   The crew of the HH-3 search-and-rescue helicopter that went down
Thursday was made up of four Guardsmen and two Air Force officers
on a training mission from George Air Force Base, said Sgt. 1st
Class Carolyn Hamilton, spokeswoman at National Guard headquarters
in Sacramento.
   ``We do not know the cause of the crash. That is being
investigated,'' said Air Force Tech. Sgt. Jorge Caballero.
   The helicopter was from the 129th Air Rescue and Recovery Group
based at Moffett Naval Air Station, about 35 miles south of San
Francisco, and was participating in a training exercise at George
when it went down, Ms. Hamilton said.
   The helicopter was almost obliterated by the crash and fire,
authorities said.
   The Air Force officers were identified as 1st Lt. James R.
Dooley and 1st Lt. Patrick L. Henry, both of the 27th Tactical Air
Support Squadron, said Air Force Sgt. Sarah Hood. Hometowns and
ages were unavailable.
   Names of the other victims were withheld for notification of
relatives.
   The helicopter, a craft called a ``Jolly Green Giant'' with a
capacity of 25 passengers and 16 litters or 5,000 pounds of cargo,
picked up the Air Force crewmen at George for search and rescue
training, Caballero said.
   The crash site was about about 30 miles northeast of the base
and 18 miles southeast of Barstow in the Cinder Cone region of the
Rodman Mountains, said San Bernardino County sheriff's spokesman
Jim Bryant. Barstow is 95 miles northeast of Los Angeles.
   California Highway Patrol Flight Officer Ken Davis, who reached
the crash site in a CHP helicopter, said the National Guard craft
crashed on a ridge.
</TEXT>
