<HEAD>Navy Continues Search for Intruding Submarine</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Swedish patrol boats fired depth
charges for the second time this week in a narrow inlet where
officials believe a foreign submarine is trapped, a defense
spokesman said.
   The spokesman, H.G. Wessberg, said it was not clear if anything
was hit Thursday.
   Indications of an intruder were discovered over the weekend in
the Stig Fiord, 27 miles north of Goteborg off the western coast.
Swedish ships fired depth charges in the area Monday.
   Wessberg said it was impossible to seal off the fiord, but he
said the navy increased patrols in the outlets of the three straits
in the area in hopes of trapping any submarine that might be there.
   The navy previously has used nets to seal off waters suspected
of harboring alien submarines.
   Foreign submarines have been reported in Swedish waters
repeatedly for the last seven years. The government, citing lack of
proof, has refused to name the country it believes is violating its
territory. Experts have said tracks left on the ocean floor
indicate the vessels were Soviet.
