<HEAD>Stocks Rebound, Dollar Edges Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar edged up marginally against the Japanese
yen Friday, while share prices recovered nearly one-third of the
losses of the previous day on the Tokyo Stock Exchange.
   The dollar, which opened at 136.25 yen, finished the week's
trading at 136.75 yen, up 0.05 yen from Thursday's closing.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, the Tokyo stock
market's main barometer, closed at 27,116.50, up 182.24 points or
0.67 percent from the previous session.
   Dealers attributed the stock market's recovery to the dollar-yen
rate, which was seen as stabilizing after the dollar's steep rise
the previous day.
   ``Investors were buying a little more than yesterday, but some
investors are still cautious, waiting to see the U.S. report on the
unemployment rate,'' said a stock dealer at a major securities firm
in Tokyo, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   The Labor Department was to release national unemployment
figures for August later Friday in Washington.
   The yen's recovery was attributed to the dollar's 0.20 yen
decline overnight in the United States, but a dollar-buying drive
remained strong among investors, leading the dollar to ``rise
slowly but surely,'' according to a foreign exchange dealer at the
Bank of Tokyo.
   ``Finance Minister Miyazawa's comments on the yen-dollar rate
(Thursday and Friday) have made investors stay away from the yen,''
he said, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   Miyazawa said Thursday that the yen's downswing was nothing to
worry about, and after a news conference Friday morning said he saw
no need to change Japan's current monetary policy.
