<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Hungary     09-02 0424</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hungary,0438</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Grosz: Strikes Not The Correct Action to Express Demands</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Poland, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Premier Karoly Grosz said 300 miners
who staged a rare strike in southern Hungary had lawful demands,
but he warned against other work stoppages.
   In a speech on Miners' Day, an annual fixture in the Soviet
bloc, Grosz on Thursday shifted blame from his communist government
to the management of the Komlo mine for failing to meet miners'
grievances.
   Workers at the Komlo mine, about 100 miles south of Budapest,
went on strike Aug. 23.
   The miners complained that a personal income tax introduced in
Hungary on Jan. 1 sliced annual bonuses by 30 percent to 50
percent. The tax is part of Grosz's efforts to curb an $18 billion
foreign debt and stimulate the economy.
   Workers returned to the job after the government promised to try
to resolve the problem over the tax.
   Officials said the strike, the first worker challenge to Grosz's
stringent eoconomic policies, was ``regrettable'' but
understandable in view of economic hardships under a government
austerity program.
   ``For the non-payment of the full sum of bonuses due ... the
responsibility'' belongs not to the government but ``on the local
management which took a wrongly interpreted economic and political
decision,'' Grosz said.
   ``We are looking into this question and will try to find a
solution,'' the official MTI news agency quoted him as saying.
   Grosz, who told the meeting he was in favor of radical reforms
to heal the ailing economy, criticized company managers of not
``economizing correctly on the funds available for dsitribution''
among the miners.
   But in a clear warning and in a bid to curb other potential
strikes, Grosz said he did not believe ``threats would produce any
results.''
   ``I would contest that ... the stopping of work would provide
the correct emphasis to express political demands ... as there are
also those who believe that by using such methods they can acquire
undue advantages,'' Grosz was quoted as saying.
   The strike coincided with labor unrest in Poland. Hundreds of
Polish miners work in Hungarian shafts. But the official media did
not say if any Poles were involved in the 20-hour stoppage at the
Komlo mine.
   The mining industry in Hungary has been crippled for at least 10
years due to producion lags, financial problems and a growing labor
shortage.
   Hungary's official trade unions have been critical of recent
economic policy, emphasizing that workers, retirees and the
unemployed must be protected against inflation, already at 18
percent this year.
</TEXT>
