<HEAD>Dollar, Stocks Rise</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar inched up marginally against the
Japanese yen today, while share prices recovered nearly one-third
of the losses of the previous day on the Tokyo Stock Exchange.
   The dollar, which opened at 136.25 yen, finished the week's
trading at 136.75 yen, up 0.05 yen from Thursday's closing. The
currency ranged between 136.23 yen and 136.78, with spot volume
estimated at $4.54 billion.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, the Tokyo stock
market's main barometer, closed at 27,116.50, up 182.24 points or
0.67 percent from Thursday, when the index closed at a 431.69-point
loss.
   An exchange dealer at a major commercial bank in Tokyo said the
dollar ``was firm and edging up gradually'' in the absence of
action by Japan's monetary authorities.
   ``The market reaffirmed Japanese monetary authorities will do
nothing about the dollar's recent rise, creating for further
yen-selling drive,'' said the dealer who spoke on condition of
anonymity.
   Finance Minister Kiichi Miyazawa told a news conference today
that no change in Japan's monetary policy is necessary at the
moment, and currency yen-dollar dealings are mostly speculative and
will soon settle down.
   Seichiro Kita of Daiwa Securities Co., a major Japanese
securities brokerage, said the stock market ``regained much
confidence today after the Nikkei index recovered above the
27,000-point level, due partly to relative stability of exchange
rates.
   The Tokyo market was looking to the latest monthly statistics of
U.S. employment data, to be released later today, Kita said.
</TEXT>
