<DOCNO> AP880902-0061 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-02-88 0448EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-CDC--Measles     09-02 0529</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-CDC--Measles,0543</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Measles Going Back Down For First Time In Four Years</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BYRD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After three years on the increase, measles is on
its way down again, but health experts say it's too early to tell
if the disease might finally be on the decline for good.
   The national Centers for Disease Control said Thursday that
3,652 cases of the once-common childhood disease were reported in
1987, down 42 percent from the previous year. It's the first drop
in measles reporting since the record low of 1,497 cases in 1983.
   Measles has fallen 99 percent since the era before measles
vaccine was licensed in 1963, and the disease was thought headed
for eradication when the record low came in 1983. But the case
count then surprised researchers by going back up in 1984, '85 and
'86.
   Researchers cannot say just what the latest drop in measles
really means, said Dr. Bradley Hersh, a CDC measles specialist. The
disease could continue to show ``little peaks and valleys'' for the
next decade, he noted.
   ``We don't really know,'' he said. ``We feel now that the
vaccine is very good and very effective, but there are problems we
are having _ in the people unvaccinated in the inner cities, and
the vaccine failures in the school-age children.''
   The CDC said 1,010 of the cases, or 28 percent, were
theoretically preventable, occurring in people who should have been
vaccinated, but weren't _ mostly preschool children in urban areas.
   Nearly three-fourths of the cases _ 2,642 _ were classified as
non-preventable, occurring in patients who had been vaccinated but
got measles anyway; most of those patients were older
schoolchildren.
   ``We've got two fronts,'' Hersh said, ``the (young) kids in
those preventable cases, and the vaccine failure in older
children.''
   The Atlanta-based agency said Thursday its expert consultants
still believe the elimination of measles in the United States
``should be pursued,'' but the two lingering problems _ the
non-vaccinated and the vaccine failures _ will ``require different
solutions.''
   ``Increased efforts are needed to vaccinate preschool-aged
children,'' particularly in inner-city areas, the CDC said in its
weekly report. ``Innovative strategies are needed to increase
immunization levels in these populations.''
   Meanwhile, the CDC said, ``aggressive revaccination strategies''
may be needed during measles outbreaks to eliminate the so-called
non-preventable cases in already-vaccinated children.
   Such a revaccination would involve a rapid program of additional
shots for most children vaccinated before 1980, when new
vaccination recommendations and new vaccine techniques began to
improve the protection somewhat, Hersh said.
   Twenty-nine percent of last year's cases occurred among patients
under 5; another 29 percent occurred in the 15-19 age group.
   Researchers have reports on how two-thirds of the patients got
the measles; 53 percent of them acquired the disease in primary and
secondary schools, while others picked it up in day care,
universities, at home or in other settings.
   Three-fourths of the cases _ 2,759 _ were reported from eight
locations: New York City, 469 cases; California, 809; Texas, 452;
New Mexico, 318; Illinois, 213; Missouri, 190; New Hampshire, 162;
and Wisconsin, 146. Fewer than 9 percent of the nation's counties
reported measles cases.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
