<2ND_LINE>PM-Washington In Brief,540</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>FCC, Justice Department Begin Campaign Against Video Pirates</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Officials say the Federal Communications
Commission and the Justice Department have begun a crackdown on
manufacturers and distributors of illegal devices used with
satellite dishes to unscramble cable television and other pay TV
programming.
   The FCC said Thursday authorities have begun making arrests and
seizing equipment in their efforts against video pirates who peddle
the devices.
   FCC official Richard Smith estimated that nearly half of the one
million satellite dishes used to receive pay TV programs have
illegal devices that unscramble the picture, and let the viewer
watch for free.
   Smith said although the agenicies have targeted manufacturers
and distributors, individual home viewers using the devices are
acting illegally and are subject to criminal and civil penalties if
caught.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Bureau of Standards Becomes Technology Institute</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government agency responsible for
determing how long is a minute and how heavy is a pound has a new
name.
   The Commerce Department agency formerly known as the National
Bureau of Standards has become the National Institute of Standards
and Technology.
   Along with the new name comes some new responsibilities.
   In addition to setting standards for length, weight, measure,
time and sundry other things, the institute has been directed to
work with American industry to help improve product quality,
modernize manufacturing processes and generally better compete with
foreign companies.
   It will set up a series of regional centers to help spread
improvements in manufacturing technology, help make federal
techology more available, encourage commercialization of new
products and help state and local officials in setting technology
policy.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Interior Official Sees Oil Production Doubled by 1992</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Interior Department official says he's
confident that California offshore oil production could double by
1992.
   William Bettenberg, director of the department's Minerals
Management Service, said Thursday that permits have already been
granted for platforms off the coast of California which should
bring the total production to 200,000 barrels to 225,000 barrels a
day.
   Current California production is about 100,000 barrels a day,
nearly twice the 53,700 barrels a day in 1981 and almost quadruple
the 27,900 barrels a day in 1980.
   There are currently 16 producing platforms in federally
controlled waters, by 1992 there should be 22 in operation after
additions and retirements, officials said.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Groups Eyes Halt to Production of H-Bomb Component</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   If the United States and Soviet Union wants to
pace the cuts in their nuclear arsenals they should halt production
of a key component of nuclear weapons, according to a group of arms
control specialists.
   In an article published today in the journal Science, the group
called for stopping further production of tritium, a hydrogen
isotope that decays at a rate of 5.5 percent yearly. Tritium is a
component of the modern, compact nuclear warheads deployed by the
superpowers.
   A nuclear weapons scientist from Lawrence Livermore National
Laboratory, however, responded that the proposal poses numerous
problems and could complicate U.S.-Soviet arms talks.
   Advocating the ``Tritium Factor'' as a means of arms control
were four specialists, headed by J. Carson Mark, associated with
the Nuclear Control Institute, a Washington-based policy group.
Mark is former leader of the theoretical division at Los Alamos
National Laboratory.
