<DOCNO> AP880902-0067 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-02-88 0515EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a PM-GatorHunt Bjt   09-02 0615</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Gator Hunt, Bjt,0633</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>First Wave Of Gator Hunters Seeks Lucrative Prey</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto MH1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRIAN MURPHY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CLEWISTON, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Airboats fanned out over Lake Okeechobee
for the first statewide alligator hunt in 26 years, a 30-day
reprieve aimed at thinning out the once endangered species whose
thick hides fetch $42 a foot.
   ``We could have filled our 15-gator limit tonight,'' Warren
Schafer boasted about four hours after the hunting season opened
Thursday night. He displayed his prey: three gators ranging from
seven to 10 feet long.
   ``It wasn't as hard as other animals I've hunted,'' said
Schafer, 45, of Miami, a veteran big-game hunter.
   Across Florida starting at sundown, more than 200 hunters
selected by the state began to search for their red-eyed prey with
flashlights and head lamps.
   Harpoons, snares and bows and arrows are about the only weapons
permitted. Most alligators are taken alive, their jaws secured with
duct tape, and are delivered to processing plants still kicking.
Some are killed with a ``bang-stick,'' a device that shoots a
cartridge on impact. Guns are prohibited because the gators often
sink after being shot.
   On Lake Okeechobee, hunters, reporters and a few sightseers
departed under the din of airboats and through a mist churned up by
their large propellers. Bugs fluttered about like snowflakes in the
hunters' lights.
   Thomas Alpern, 25, a free-lance writer from New York City, said
to be the only Northerner who received a permit, was still
searching for his first alligator at midnight with the aid of a
professional trapper.
   ``Who knows?'' he said. ``Maybe I won't even be able to kill it
once we find one.''
   But Alpern, like many hunters, couldn't ignore the profitable
side of the hunt. In addition to the lucrative hides, gator meat
sells for up to $6 a pound.
   ``The money is the big factor,'' said Rodney Crawford, a
19-year-old cook from Lake Worth, who will hunt on Lake George in
Florida.
   State game officers are closely monitoring the hunt for poachers
and permit-holders using illegal weapons or taking gators below the
4-foot minimum length.
   Since federal anti-poaching methods were adopted in 1970, the
alligator population in Florida has about doubled to an estimated 1
million. Nearly 1,000 gators have been captured in experimental
hunts since 1981, and the September season will be isolated to 28
districts where the alligator population is extraordinarily high.
   Tom Stice, a biologist with the state Game and Fresh Water Fish
Commission, said a cross section of the public was sought for the
hunt to expand interest in alligators.
   The 238 hunters, selected from about 5,000 applications,
attended a six-hour, state-sponsored training session and signed
liability waivers.
   Stice estimated the hunters will capture 65 to 70 percent of the
possible maximum of 3,450.
   For state wildlife officials, the hunt follows a nearly 20-year
effort to preserve the Florida alligator, which averages about 10
feet in length.
   The last state-approved hunt for sport was in 1962, when the
American alligator was declared endangered and hunting alligators
in Florida was banned. As its numbers increased, however, officials
downgraded the alligator from endangered to threatened and the
state gradually relaxed hunting restrictions.
   ``People are getting gator phobia,'' said Lee Kramer of Delray
Beach, who captures nuisance alligators for the state. ``I got a
call the other day in Boca (Raton) and it turned out to be an
inflatable pool alligator that blew into a ditch.''
   Allan Woodward, head of alligator research for the game
commission, theorized that the alligator population was not as
decimated as previously thought during the height of poaching in
the 1960s.
   ``They've really surprised us,'' he said. ``They're a pretty
hardy animal.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880902-0068 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-02-88 0536EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Whitworth     09-02 0615</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Whitworth,0630</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Whitworth Espionage Convictions, Sentence Affirmed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB EGELKO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal appeals court upheld the
espionage convictions and 365-year prison sentence of ex-Navy
radioman Jerry Whitworth, a member of the Walker spy ring that
passed military secrets to the Soviets.
   The 9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals ruled 3-0 Thursday that
the punishment fit Whitworth's crime of selling ultra-sensitive
Navy decoding and communications information to the Soviet Union.
   The sentence imposed by U.S. District Judge John Vukasin
``viewed in the abstract ... would appear harsh,'' the court said.
``This sentence, however, is not disproportionate to Whitworth's
crimes.''
   Whitworth, 49, of Davis, Calif., a radioman with a top-secret
clearance for much of his 18-year Navy career, was convicted in
1986 of seven counts of espionage for supplying ultra-sensitive
decoding and communications information to spymaster John Walker
for nearly a decade, in exchange for $332,000.
   Vukasin called Whitworth ``one of the most spectacular spies of
the century'' and imposed the nation's harshest sentence for
espionage since Julius and Ethel Rosenberg, convicted of conspiring
to furnish atomic bomb secrets to the Soviets, were electrocuted in
1953.
   Whitworth's sentence forbids parole consideration for 60 years.
In the decision, the court rejected defense arguments that a
sentence longer than Walker's amounted to cruel and unusual
punishment.
   Military and intelligence officials testified at the trial that
the spy ring had revealed the Navy's most precious secrets and
caused damage that may be impossible to calculate.
   Walker also recruited his son and brother as members of the spy
ring. He pleaded guilty in a Baltimore federal court to spying for
the Soviets for 17 years and was sentenced to life in prison, with
parole possible in 10 years.
   The opinion by Judge Robert Boochever said the U.S. Constitution
does not require a judge in one court to compare a defendant's
relative guilt to that of a defendant in another court on separate
charges before imposing sentence.
   Even if comparison of guilt was required, Boochever said, ``the
court notes that Whitworth kept Walker's espionage operation alive
for nearly a decade and himself became a central figure because of
his access to highly classified material.''
   Whitworth's chief prosecutor, former Assistant U.S. Attorney
William Farmer, commented, ``The sentence was not harsh at all. If
this had been a case where there was a death penalty available, it
clearly would have been prosecuted as a capital case.''
   Assistant U.S. Attorney Sanford Svetcov, who represented the
prosecution on appeal, agreed that Whitworth deserved a death
sentence, which was abolished for espionage and other federal
crimes by a 1972 Supreme Court ruling.
   ``It's a sickness in our society, that we have people willing to
do harm to their own country for money,'' Svetcov said. ``These
guys were not Communists by any means. They were strictly in it for
profit.''
   Whitworth's lawyer on appeal, Alan Caplan, said he was
disappointed by the ruling and would appeal. He said he was
``astounded'' by the court's conclusion that the verdict was not
influenced when Walker was improperly allowed to speculate on the
witness stand that Whitworth must have known the secrets were being
delivered to the Soviet Union.
   Walker, also a former Navy radioman with a top-secret clearance,
testified that he had started selling secrets to a Soviet agent in
1968 and recruited Whitworth as his chief supplier of classified
materials in 1974, after Walker himself no longer had direct access
to the material.
   Whitworth was convicted of furnishing to Walker the secrets of
Navy decoding equipment, code keys and communications systems that
Whitworth gathered and photographed for nearly a decade as a highly
placed radio officer at ship and shore stations.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880902-0069 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-02-88 0540EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-YonkersDeseg 1stLd-Writethru a0478 09-02 0915</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Yonkers Deseg, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0478,0937</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Supreme Court Refuses to Stay Yonkers Fines, But Spares
Councilmen</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 6th graf pvs, `House said ...,' with 3 grafs to DELETE
incorrect reference to number of court applications and to UPDATE
with quotes from dissenting opinion. SUBS grafs 11-12 pvs, `Several
messages ...,' with 8 new grafs to UPDATE with with councilors'
reax; fixes style of byline.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARLENE AIG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>YONKERS, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. Supreme Court has refused to halt
mounting daily fines against the city for blocking a federal
housing desegregation plan, a decision the mayor says could cause
Yonkers ``to plummet to bankruptcy.''
   But in a ruling issued Thursday night, the court temporarily
spared the four city councilmen who oppose the plan from going to
jail until they have time to ask formally that their cases be fully
reviewed, U.S. Supreme Court spokeswoman Toni House said.
   The justices stayed a lower court ruling that had upheld
contempt citations against the four councilmen, who had faced a
resumption of $500-a-day fines and the start of jail terms this
weekend.
   The city's fines for failing to comply with the desegregation
order were put on hold until today, pending the Supreme Court's
ruling. The fines will now resume against the city, Yonkers Mayor
Nicholas Wasicsko said.
   The fines started Aug. 2 at $100 and doubled daily. The city had
paid $12,700 before receiving its first stay from an appeals court,
which upheld the contempt finding last Friday but granted an
additional one-week stay. It also capped the city's fines at $1
million a day.
   House said the entire court considered the applications from the
councilmen and the city, and ``the application so far as the city
of Yonkers is concerned has been denied.''
   Justices Thurgood Marshall and William Brennan filed a 12-page
dissent, arguing that all stays be denied, she said.
   ``As the city repeatedly points out in its application, `Yonkers
is relatively unique in that most of the governmental power in the
city is centralized in the legislative branch.' For this reason the
city IS the council,'' Marshall wrote.
   The ruling surprised Wasicsko, who favors compliance with the
desegregation order.
   ``It troubles me,'' he said early today. ``The treasury of the
city is going to be exposed and the taxpayers of the city are going
to feel the burden.
   ``One thing it denies is the political martyrdom of the
councilmen. They were slated to go to jail on Sunday. Their
personal fines have ceased. But the city is going to plummet to
bankruptcy.
   ``So their onus is their duty to the city,'' he added. ``Their
personal political martyrdom has been denied them.''
   Two of the four defiant councilmen _ Nicholas Longo and Vice
Mayor Henry Spallone _ said early today that the decision, for
them, was a major victory.
   ``This country went through a revolution a couple hundred years
ago to make sure that people could cast their votes independently
and without coercion,'' Longo said.
   Councilman Peter Chema, another one of the four, called the
decision ``a big personal victory, but I have serious concerns
about the city. It's kind of like being administered oxygen while
someone strangles you.''
   The fourth councilman, Edward Fagan, called the decision
``unexpected'' and declined to comment further.
   Longo said the four would ask U.S. District Judge Leonard Sand,
who initially found them in contempt, to suspend the city's fines
pending their Supreme Court hearing, which Longo said would not be
until 1989.
   ``The relief becomes moot if he decides to bankrupt the city in
the interim,'' Longo said.
   Longo and Spallone refused to say if they would allow the city
to go bankrupt rather than change their votes.
   In 1985, Sand found the city liable for 40 years of segregating
housing and schools and ordered the city to build 800 units of
moderate-income housing throughout the city.
   Sand found them in contempt Aug. 2, the day after the council
first rejected the court-ordered desegregation plan by a 4-3 vote.
They've rejected the plan by the same vote three times since.
   Bertran F. Wallace, president of the Yonkers branch of the
National Association of Colored People, one of the plaintiffs in
the original suit against the city, said this morning he was not
very familiar with the ruling.
   ``Our greatest concern is to see that the court order issued by
Judge Sand is carried out and implemented and that we build the
homes ... in a very peaceful and orderly manner,'' he said.
   The state Emergency Financial Control Board, which has taken
control of the city's spending, had said it would seek criminal
charges against the four councilmen today if the fines are
reimposed.
   Spokespeople said this morning that Gov. Mario Cuomo and
Secretary of State Gail Shaffer, who chairs the control board,
would not comment until they had seen the high court's ruling.
   The criminal charges stem from violating the control board act _
a state law _ by jeopardizing the city's finances through spending
money the city they were not authorized to spend.
   Kevin Condon, spokesman for a citizens' group called COMPLY,
which supports compliance with the desegregation order, said ``the
ruling is one final indication that the city needs to face reality
and get on with putting its life back together.''
   The city and councilmen had a tentative court appearance with
Sand set for 2 p.m. today. It was not known how the Supreme Court
ruling would affect the schedule.
</TEXT>
