<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Lites     09-02 0429</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lites,0442</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>On The Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ANCHORAGE, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Louie, an Alaskan King Crab, is just
getting a leg up in the racing game, but he'll be seasoned in a
Maryland crab derby Saturday.
   Louie, dubbed King Louis the 49th by Alaska officials, is in the
field of competitors from 31 states in the Governor's Cup race at
the 41st National Hard Crab Derby and Fair at Crisfield, Md.
   Alaska won the Governor's Cup in 1968, 1972 and 1980, but crab
handicappers have their doubts about Louie. They say he may be too
big and ungainly to cover the 16-foot course ahead of the smaller
blue and Dungeness crabs entered by other states.
   ``You're talking about an animal that is large, with a heavy
body weight,'' said Bill Nippes of the Alaska Department of Fish
and Game. ``Take it out of the water and you change the buoyancy.
Crabs are very slow on land. Dungeness crabs are a lot faster,
quicker.''
   So are Chesapeake Bay blue crabs, Nippes said. Maryland offers
those to crabless states. Those entries include the Cheese State
Streaker from Wisconsin, Colorado Super Collider, Ethan Allen's
Revenge from Vermont, Peanuts from Georgia, Crabby Curt from
Michigan and Koa o Ke Kai from Hawaii.
   ``That means `Warrior of the Sea,''' said Claude Brooks of the
Maryland Office of Tourism Development. ``I hope that's what it
means. I hope it isn't something obscene.''
   Maryland is famous for its crabs, but none of its entries has
won in the 41-year history of the derby said race coordinator Ruth
Custis.
   Maybe the Maryland blues know something about the post-race
festivities the other crabs don't.
   ``We eat them,'' Custis said, laughing. ``We put our famous
seasoning on them and have a feast.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>EDWARDSVILLE, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The motley, shaggy drill team is
whipped into line with barked commands of ``left, left, about
turn!'' They march heads high, but without pompons, drums or flags.
   ``Dogs on Parade,'' which is still being whipped into shape, is
sponsored by the Madison County Humane Society in this city nearly
15 miles northeast of St. Louis.
   ``We are all dog lovers who have taken the time to train our
animals,'' said society President Sherry Harper. ``The drill team
is a chance for other people to see what can be done.''
   ``This is fun,'' Vicky Sullivan of Edwardsville said during a
team practice last week as she urged a golden retriever named Bear
and a mutt named Sackett into action during a practice last week.
``Dogs will do anything you want them to do.''
</TEXT>
