<2ND_LINE>PM-Dollar-Gold,0302</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar In Narrow Range, Gold Prices Down</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar was little changed today, trading
within a narrow range on European markets as dealers awaited the
announcement of U.S. employment data. Gold was lower.
   Foreign exchange dealers said in early trading the dollar
recovered slightly on support from the Japanese yen which had
broken through a critical resistance point of 137.00 yen.
   But the U.S. currency remained in a narrow range before U.S.
unemployment data was published. As the first economic indicator
for August, it could be a key factor in determining the dollar's
short-term trend, dealers said.
   The market on average expected the jobless rate to be unchanged
from July's 5.4 percent.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day
begins, the dollar rose 0.05 yen to a closing 136.75 yen. Later, in
London, it was quoted at 137.00 yen.
   Other dollar rates in Europe at midmorning, compared with late
Thursday's rates:
   _1.8745 West German marks, down from 1.8795
   _1.5815 Swiss francs, down from 1.5835
   _6.3750 French francs, down from 6.3780
   _2.1182 Dutch guilders, down from 2.1205
   _1,397.50 Italian lire, down from 1,398.50
   _1.2370 Canadian dollars, unchanged.
   In London, the British pound fell to $1.6695 from $1.6730 late
Thursday.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $429.40 a troy ounce,
down 10 cents from late Thursday's bid. At mid-morning, the city's
five major bullion dealers fixed a lower recommended price of
$428.95.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $428.75, down from $430.50 bid late
Thursday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell 1.26 dollars to close at a bid
$431.35.
   Silver was quoted in London at a bid price of $6.56 a troy
ounce, down from Thursday's $6.58.
</TEXT>
