<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Ethiopia-Somalia     09-02 0196</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Ethiopia-Somalia,0201</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Prisoner Exchange 10 Years After Ethiopia-Somalia War</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nearly 3,800 captives taken in fighting between
Somalia and Ethiopia have been flown home, most of them Ethiopian
POWs from a 1977-78 conflict, the International Committee of the
Red Cross said today.
   The prisoner swap supervised by the Geneva-based humanitarian
agency followed an agreement between Ethiopia and Somalia in April.
   A total of 3,543 Ethiopian prisoners of war and civilian
prisoners and one Cuban were brought back to Ethiopia in exchange
for the return of 245 Somalian POWs in a nine-day operation
completed Thursday, a Red Cross statement said.
   A Boeing 707 chartered by the Red Cross made 20 round-trip
flights between Somalia's capital of Mogadishu and Dire Dawa in
Ethiopia to complete the exchange, the statement said.
   The original plane crash-landed at Djibouti airport Aug. 26 when
its front landing gear failed, injuring 20 of the 190 people
aboard. The flights continued with another aircraft after a day's
interrruption.
   Forces from Somalia invaded the arid Ogaden region in 1977, but
Ethiopia's Soviet-backed communist government rebuffed the Somalis
the following year. The border conflict was not formally resolved
until the April peace agreement.
</TEXT>
