<2ND_LINE>PM-Greece-Blackout,0183</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Power Restored to Most Parts of Greece</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Officials restored power to most of the
country early today after an explosion in a substation plunged
Athens and southern Greece in darkness for several hours.
   A police spokesman reported no blackout-related deaths, serious
injuries or looting but said hundreds of minor car accidents
occurred in Athens because there were no traffic lights.
   Fire officials said more than 1,000 Athenians were trapped in
elevators during the blackout, which lasted up to five hours in
parts of the city.
   A senior Public Power Corporation official said 90 percent of
power had been restored and the system would be back to normal by
the end of the day. The officials spoke on condition of anonymity.
   The blackout occurred Thursday night when an explosion in a
substation near the town of Larissa knocked out three of four power
cables serving southern Greece.
   Industry Minister Anastasis Peponis said power officials were
trying to determine the cause of the power failure, which he said
``probably wasn't caused by human error.''
</TEXT>
