<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Colombia     09-02 0356</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Colombia,0369</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>President Offers Peace Plan With Guerrillas In National Address</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM WELLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Virgilio Barco, in a national
address, offered to start peace talks with leftist guerrillas who
have attacked two northern Colombia towns within a week.
   Barco told a national television audience Thursday night that
the talks should conclude with the dissolution of guerrilla
organizations.
   Guerrillas must stop their terrorist acts, human rights
violations, kidnappings and extortions before talks begin, Barco
said. He said a peace agreement should be reached by March 1990,
when the next presidential and parliamentary elections are
scheduled.
   The offer came two days after guerrillas firing automatic
assault rifles, throwing hand grenades and setting fire to houses
killed 12 peasants, Gov. Jose Gabriel Amin of Cordoba state said.
   An estimated 30 guerrillas of the People's Liberation Army set
fire to a ranch, killed 10 peasants and wounded 15 Tuesday near the
town of Canalete, Amin said Thursday.
   Canalete is about 320 miles north of Bogota.
   The insurgents then attacked the nearby village of El Tomate,
setting fire to 26 huts and killing two people, the governor said
in a broadcast interview with the Colombian radio chain RCN.
   In El Tomate, a village of 600 people, the attackers left
messages painted on walls declaring, ``Death to the toads and
paramilitaries,'' survivors said in interviews with RCN.
   Guerrillas call army informants toads.
   Peasants in Colombia have long claimed that they are caught
between the army and the guerrillas.
   In dozens of interviews with The Associated Press, peasants have
told of being forced to sell food and other necessities to
guerrillas.
   Often soldiers force the peasants to give information about
guerrilla movements, the peasants say. The guerrillas then return
and kill the peasants, accusing them of being army informants, the
peasants have said.
   The People's Liberation Army and another guerrilla group known
as the Colombian Revolutionary Armed Forces attacked the town of
Saisa in the state of Cordoba on Aug. 23 and killed 12 civilians,
10 soldiers and two policemen, the Defense Ministry said.
   Twenty-two soldiers and policemen were taken prisoner, the
ministry said.
</TEXT>
