<1ST_LINE>r i PM-BoatPeople     09-02 0258</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Boat People,0268</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hong Kong Planning New Shelter For Boat People</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government said today it will build a new
emergency shelter for the growing number of Vietnamese refugees
arriving by boat to this British colony.
   The center, which is to open by the end of September, will be
the sixth center built to house Vietnamese boat people who landed
after mid-June. Hong Kong announced a new policy that classified
most of the boat people who arrived after June 15 as illegal
immigrants subject to repatriation.
   Vietnamese who arrived earlier are considered political refugees
eligible for resettlement.
   More than 9,000 new refugees _ including 2,375 in August _
arrived since the measure took effect, although it was designed to
stop the rising influx of boat people. The number of Vietnamese in
Hong Kong refugee camps totals 25,000, according to government
statistics.
   The new center is expected to shelter about 3,000 people in
huts, the government said.
   Some residents near the site of the future shelter said they
will oppose it unless authorities guarantee local services will not
be disrupted, government-run radio reported.
   Hanoi said it will examine on a case-by-case basis the
Vietnamese who arrived in Hong Kong after mid-June, if they
volunteer to return to their homeland, 500 miles southwest of Hong
Kong.
   However, only 1 percent of the boat people have requested
repatriation to their communist homeland, and none has returned so
far, a government spokeswoman said today.
   The United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees is processing
their applications to return.
</TEXT>
