<1ST_LINE>r a PM-StrandedVessel     09-02 0385</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Stranded Vessel,0401</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Coast Guard Sends Icebreaker to Help Cruise Ship in Beaufort Sea</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSAN GALLAGHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ANCHORAGE, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An intellectuals' cruise ship trapped
in the ice inside the Arctic Circle awaited a Coast Guard
icebreaker today. The 149 passengers and crew members were in no
danger, the cruise operator said.
   Passengers on the Society Explorer bound for the Northwest
Passage were paying an average of $400 a day as clients of a
company specializing in educational journeys to unconventional
destinations, including Antarctica.
   The Coast Guard said the 236-foot ship was caught in Beaufort
Sea ice 50 miles northeast of Point Barrow, or about 400 miles
inside the Arctic Circle. The crew notified Canadian maritime
officials on Wednesday the ship was stranded.
   The Coast Guard said Thursday that one of its icebreakers, based
in Seattle, was bound for the area on a research mission and was
diverted to help the cruise vessel. The 399-foot icebreaker was
expected to reach the ship Saturday.
   The Society Explorer set sail from Dutch Harbor on Aug. 19.
Stops have included the Pribilof Islands, Gambell and the Siberian
port of Provideniya.
   The itinerary calls for the ship to sail east along the
Northwest Passage, with the voyage scheduled to end in St. John's,
Newfoundland, on Sept. 21.
   That schedule likely will be set back several days, said Peter
Cox, planning director for Society Expedition Cruises Ltd., which
offers trips that emphasize libraries and lectures.
   The passengers, most of them Americans, found intellectual
pursuits to fill the time while awaiting the Coast Guard.
   ``Our entertainment on board is mostly intellectual
entertainment, not gambling and dancing,'' Cox said. He said the
company caters to an ``extremely well-educated and a very
naturalist-oriented passenger.''
   He said the ship is ``absolutely safe'' and well-stocked with
items on its continental menu.
   Cox likened the Beaufort Sea to ``a big jigsaw puzzle'' of ice
and water.
   A wind rearranged the ice to the ship's disadvantage, said Randy
Crosby of North Slope Borough Search and Rescue. The rescue unit
planned to fly over the ship for a look but was held back by heavy
fog Thursday, Crosby said.
   Employees of an Alaskan air-service company who flew over the
vessel on Wednesday said it was caught in seven to eight miles of
ice.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880902-0085 </DOCNO>
