<2ND_LINE>PM-Northern Ireland, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0474,0551</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>PRECEDE Belfast</HEAD>
<HEAD>Riot Police Fill Village Where Funeral Set For IRA Supporters</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New throughout to UPDATE with village in mourning for IRA
funerals, security, army withdrawal from sports charity. No pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BEN DOBBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOUGHMACRORY, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police guarded a funeral
service in this village today for two IRA guerrillas killed by
British soldiers, and rioting occurred for a second night in
Catholic west Belfast.
   Black flags were hung on telephone poles and pro-IRA slogans
were scrawled on walls in Loughmacrory, 45 miles west of Belfast.
   Brothers Gerard Harte, 29, and Martin Harte, 21, were to be
buried after a service at St. Mary's Roman Catholic Church, and
26-year-old Brian Mullin's funeral was to be held Saturday at the
nearby village of Dunmoyle.
   Police said they were shot and killed in a British army ambush
Tuesday and that the trio was plotting to kill an off-duty soldier.
   Dozens of police with riot shields and batons deployed in the
village and along the road to the Harte family home, apparently to
prevent the IRA turning the funeral into an anti-British show of
strength.
   The IRA said it honored its dead comrades with a ceremonial
volley in the Loughmacrory area Thursday night.
   In Belfast, a police spokesman who demanded anonymity said
police fired plastic bullets to disperse rioters during violence in
Roman Catholic areas of the city that flared Thursday night and
continued early today.
   Police said that in rioting earlier Thursday in a west Belfast
IRA stronghold, three people were slightly injured and taken to the
hospital when troops fired plastic bullets at a hostile crowd.
   Police said the rioting in Belfast late Thursday and early today
was not on the scale of riots that broke out Wednesday.
   In those riots, gangs of young IRA supporters set fire to a bus,
two vans and more than 35 cars, and hurled gasoline bombs and rocks
at security forces while a gunman fired on the city's New Barnsley
police station.
   Dozens of burned out vehicles still blocked some roads in the
area Thursday night as groups of youths gathered at street corners,
talking and drinking beer while police and army patrols cruised by.
   Police said the three slain IRA men were armed, masked and
driving in a stolen car when they were ambushed. They said Gerard
Harte was the commander of the IRA's Mid-Tyrone unit and that
Martin Harte was responsible for selecting IRA targets from the
ranks of the police and the Ulster Defense Regiment.
   Martin Harte was arrested during police raids following the Aug.
20 bus bombing but was released without charge, they said.
   The IRA in a statement Wednesday said the Harte brothers and
Mullin, 26, were on ``active service'' _ a guerrilla euphemism for
a bombing or shooting mission _ when they were slain.
   The mainly Catholic IRA is fighting to end British rule in
Protestant-dominated Northern Ireland and unite it with the mainly
Catholic Republic of Ireland under socialist rule.
   Organizers of Sport Aid, a worldwide charity run scheduled for
Sept. 11, announced that the army had withdrawn from participation
in an event at London's Hyde Park, citing the heightened IRA threat
to military personnel.
</TEXT>
