<DOCNO> AP880902-0086 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-02-88 0846EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-LastCall     09-02 0383</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Last Call,0397</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Stag Brewery Closes, Ending 130-Year Tradition</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELLEVILLE, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It's last call for Stag Beer.
   Terry Galati pushed the last case of beer off the Stag Brewery
production line at 1 p.m. Thursday, ending a brewing era in
Illinois.
   ``As the final case came through, a lot of memories flashed in
my mind,'' said Galati, a machine operator at Stag for 11 years.
``I felt bad. It was a depressing moment for me.''
   Stag was Illinois' last full-scale brewery, and at 130 years was
one of the oldest in the Midwest. The closing put about 200 people
out of work.
   G. Heileman Brewing Co., which owns Stag, announced June 27 its
was closing the brewery because of its age, excess capacity at
other Heileman plants and the need to spend $2.9 million for a
sewage plant for the brewery.
   The LaCrosse, Wis.-based beer company and Belleville officials
continue to search for investors willing to reopen the brewery.
   Mayor Richard Brauer said last week an unidentified investor was
considering making an offer to buy the brewery.
   But Gary Perleberg, director of planning and development for
Heileman, said Thursday, ``We have received no offers and I have no
comment further than that.''
   Heileman bought the brewery from Carling National Breweries in
1979. Last fall, Australian brewing giant Bond Corp. Holdings Ltd.
purchased Heileman for $1.22 billion. The company closed a brewery
in Evansville, Ind., earlier this year.
   Workers who trickled out of the Stag plant Thursday said they
were resigned to the closing.
   ``It was very quiet at work today,'' said Galati, 34. ``There
was a lot of hugging and hand-shaking. ... I'm going to miss the
money and working with the guys. I've been working with some of
these guys for so long, I'll miss seeing them every day.''
   About 180 employees had been laid off by Thursday. The remaining
50 will be kept on indefinitely to handle distribution of the
remaining stock, close the books and maintain equipment in hopes an
investor will save the plant.
   Greg Beaston, 27, said his grandfather, father and four brothers
have worked at the brewery. He said he hopes the brewery is
reopened soon.
   ``The shorter the time it is shut down, the quicker it can be
started back up,'' Beaston said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
