<HEAD>Forest Fires At-A-Glance</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Forest Fires Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is a brief look at forest fires today in the Western states:
</TEXT>
<HEAD>ALASKA</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   The fire season has ended with snowfalls in the interior of the
state. About 2.1 million acres were charred.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>CALIFORNIA</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Firefighters today hoped to contain five major fires in the
mountain ranges of Northern California, including a 3,000-acre fire
in remote Sierra Nevada timber country.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>IDAHO</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   More than 2,500 firefighters remained on the lines of the worst
of the 17 major fires burning more than 70,000 acres. Reduced winds
increased optimism.
   Losses, mainly in commercial timber, were estimated at some $4.5
million statewide and mounting.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>MONTANA:</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Ten major fires still burning have charred 255,000 acres. The
main activity is on two 45,000-acre fires in the Absaroka-Beartooth
Wilderness north of Yellowstone Park. Some West Yellowstone
residents fled their homes overnight as a blaze moved within 1{
miles of the tourist town. Firefighters also battled both ends of a
51,000-acre fire that stretches for 22 miles in the Scapegoat
Wilderness of west-central Montana.
   All hunting postponed until Sept. 16. The delay may affect as
many as 75,000 hunters.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>OREGON</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Total acreage burned since Aug. 23: 58,558. Twelve major fires
still burning, the largest of which has burned 37,400 acres of
grass and timber in the Hell's Canyon National Recreation Area and
Wallowa-Whitman National Forest.
   About 3,000 firefighters and support personnel working on forest
and range fires. Fire damage to natural resources since Aug. 23 is
$11.4 million, cost of firefighting $8.3 million.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>UTAH</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   A once-controlled blaze near northern Utah's Pineview Reservoir
jumped fire lines and had more than doubled to 2,000 acres,
threatening high-voltage lines that bring power to the Salt
Lake-Ogden-Provo metropolitan area.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>WASHINGTON</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Since Aug. 23, wildfires have charred more than 24,500 acres.
Fires are burning in seven areas; 2,332 firefighters are on the
line.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>WYOMING</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   The south entrance to Yellowstone National Park, closed for 12
days by forest fires, re-opened Thursday. A lack of strong wind
gave a breather to firefighters on the eight major fires in the
park, which involve about 540,000 acres and include a 231,000-acre
blaze in the park's northeastern corner.
</TEXT>
