<1ST_LINE>r a PM-RoyalShower     09-02 0301</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Royal Shower,0311</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Royal Baby Gets Shower of Gifts</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROL ZUEGNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEATRICE, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Princess Beatrice, the newest member of
Britain's royal family, got a king-sized baby shower from this
community of the same name.
   The daughter of Andrew and Sarah, the Duke and Duchess of York,
received in absentia a regal array of gifts, from a college
scholarship to a library card and a key to the city of 13,000.
Beatrice, born Aug. 8, is fifth in line to the throne.
   The party, an open house Thursday at the Chamber of Commerce
office with cake, coffee and punch, was the idea of the Gage County
Visitors Committee, said chairman Randy Baynes.
   ``We wanted to celebrate something we had in common with her,
even though the name's pronounced differently,'' Baynes said.
   The cake, festooned with pink frosting roses, spelled out the
difference. It read: ``Be-AT-trice welcomes Princess BE-a-trice.''
   Her Royal Highness will receive a bevy of bibs, some
cross-stitched with her name, others crocheted.
   There were also baby booties, baby-sized high-topped tennis
shoes, a quilt, a rattle, an American flag, an atlas with the town
of Beatrice marked, a deck of cards, a toothbrush and a miniature
pink sand castle, labeled fit for a princess.
   ``I'm not sure the gifts are the traditional kind, but it's been
fun for the community,'' Bayne said.
   Some residents dropped off cards, including one from a young
girl who wished Beatrice the best of luck and added, ``I hope you
find a handsome prince to marry.''
   The princess has been made an honorary citizen of the community
and residents said they hope she'll make it there someday. If she
does, she will be able to check out a book from the the town
library with her own library card.
</TEXT>
