<FILEID>AP-NR-09-02-88 0932EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-AirCrash     09-02 0493</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Air Crash,0513</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Air Force Says Two Americans Killed In Air Show Crash</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GIRARD C. STEICHEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RAMSTEIN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A U.S. Army private and her
9-year-old son are the only Americans identified among 49 people
killed in a fiery crash at an air show at a U.S. base, Air Force
officials said today.
   The officials also lowered their death toll from Sunday's
disaster. Earlier they said 52 people died when three Italian jet
fighters collided during the air show and one plowed into a crowd
at the Air Force base in Ramstein.
   West German officials said a badly burned male victim died
Thursday, raising the death toll to 49. U.S. and West German
officials now have the same death toll, said base spokeswoman
Monika Stuppy.
   ``There was so much confusion at the beginning. Now we are
meeting twice a day to coordinate more closely on this,'' Ms.
Stuppy told The Associated Press. The Air Force identified the two
dead Americans as Joshua Frymyer, 9, and his mother, Pfc. Genevieve
Riggs of the 110th Military Police Co. in Pirmasens, West Germany.
The child is survived by his father, Michael D. Frymyer, of
Lewistown, Penn., an Air Force statement said.
   No ages were available for the parents.
   Mrs. Riggs' husband, Army Sgt. Myron Riggs, 24, who was severely
burned in the disaster, served in the same military police unit as
his wife. He was flown Tuesday to Brooke Army Medical Center in
Texas, the unofficial U.S. military newspaper Stars and Stripes
reported.
   West German officials said 40 of the dead have been identified.
In addition to the two Americans, they are 33 West Germans, a Dutch
citizen, a French citizen, and the three Italian pilots, according
to Juergen Dietzen, spokesman for Rhineland-Palatinate state, where
Ramstein is located.
   Dietzen said 172 people remained in hospitals, including some
who had been released and returned after their condition worsened
at home.
   He said the hospitalized victims were 144 West Germans, 16
Americans, two Britons, and one each from France, Italy, Belgium,
Portugal, Africa and the Philippines. He did not name the African
country.
   Four more injured victims were not identified because they were
``unable to communicate due to the severity of their injuries,'' he
said.
   Meanwhile, a West German medical expert charged today that
rescue work after the air show disaster was seriously flawed and
that many burn victims were sent to hospitals incapable of handling
their injuries.
   ``The organizational handling of the catastrophe ... was a
scandal and an unbelievable failure of those responsible,'' said
Leo Koslowski, an expert on burns and former director of the
University Surgical Clinic in Tuebingen.
   Wolfgang Herbig, director of the nearby Kaiserslautern hospital,
where many of the injured were taken, said there were not enough
mobile medical teams available at the air base after the accident.
   But officials of Rhineland-Palatinate state strongly defended
the rescue efforts and praised the cooperation between Americans
and Germans.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
