<DOCNO> AP880902-0093 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-02-88 0949EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Britain-Kurds     09-02 0302</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Britain-Kurds,0313</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iraqi Kurds Occupy London U.N. Offices</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Iraq-Kurds</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 20 Iraqi Kurds occupied the London offices
of the United Nations today and accused Iraq of using chemical
weapons against their people, a U.N. official said.
   They demanded intervention by U.N. Secretary-General Javier
Perez de Cuellar.
   The United Nations has condemned Iraq for using chemical weapons
in its 8-year war with Iran.
   Iraq is fighting Kurdish separatists in northern Iraq who are
supported by Iran. Iraq launched an offensive to crush the Kurdish
rebellion soon after Iraq accepted a U.N.-sponsored cease-fire in
the Persian Gulf war.
   About 20 million Kurds live where the borders of Iran, Iraq and
Turkey converge. Turkish officials also have accused Iraq of using
chemical weapons against the Kurds.
   Eric Jensen, U.N. information director in London, said the group
gave him a petition for Perez de Cuellar and said they would not
leave until they got a satisfactory response to their demand.
   Perez de Cuellar left the U.N. office in Geneva on Thursday and
was traveling in Portugal today, Jensen said. The U.N. headquarters
in New York was closed when the Kurds moved into the London office
at 11 a.m. (6 a.m. EDT).
   ``Someone asked to come in. We are open to the public for many
purposes and the girl on the reception quite correctly let this
person in,'' said Jensen. ``Once the door was open a number of
others came in _ about 20.''
   A British group which supports Iraqi Kurds, the Commiteee
Against Suppression of Democratic Rights in Iraq, said the
occupying group represented seven Iraqi Kurdish parties.
   Questioned in a British Broadcasting Corp. interview on
Thursday, Iraqi Ambassador to London, Mohammed Sadiq Al-Mashat, did
not deny his country had used chemical weapons but said Iran had
``used chemical weapons first.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
