<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Iraq-Kurds     09-02 0535</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Iraq-Kurds,0554</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Kurdish Rebels Say 1,300 Civilians Slaughtered</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NEIL MacFARQUHAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A spokesman for Kurdish rebels fighting
Iraqi government troops claimed today that the Iraqi army
slaughtered about 1,300 unarmed men, women and children this week.
   The official Islamic Republic News agency quoted Kurdish
refugees as saying their houses were set on fire and they fled into
the mountains without food.
   In London, a group of 20 Kurds occupied the offices of the
United Nations, accusing Iraq of using chemical weapons against
their people and demanding that U.N. Secretary-General Javier Perez
de Cuellar intervene.
   An official of the Kurdish Democratic Party told The Associated
Press in Nicosia in a telephone interview that the 1,300 victims
were arrested Aug. 28 in the Dahok region in northwestern Iraq,
killed and buried in mass graves.
   In addition, 43,000 people trying to get out of the region are
being held back by the Iraqi military, said the spokesman.
   There was no way to independently confirm the report.
   He said the refugees were ``suffering from hunger, disease and
serious chemical injuries.'' The spokesman, based in a West
European capital, declined to give his name for ``security
reasons.''
   IRNA, monitored in Nicosia, quoted a Kurd identified as
38-year-old Hakim Refaq as saying, ``My house has been set on fire
three times and for weeks we had to live in the mountains without
food or any other facilities.''
   It quoted other men as saying numerous villages had been
destroyed by the Iraqi army and that Kurdish families were being
imprisoned in camps.
   The ferocious battles between the Kurdish rebels and the Iraqi
army are escalating, the rebel spokesman said.
   ``Fierce fighting is now taking place around our main base,''
said the spokesman. The base, called The First Branch, is in
Amadiyah.
   He said the Iraqi northern-based 1st and 5th army corps as well
as the 7th army corps based in the south and the elite Presidential
guards were all fighting the Kurds. The rebels estimated Wednesday
that 60,000 troops backed by fighter-bombers and helicopter
gunships were fighting against them.
   In addition to burning villages, he said the Iraqi army used
chemical weapons to attack three villages in the Amadiyah area
Wednesday and Thursday.
   The spokesman said thousands of Kurdish refugees were trying to
flee to Turkey, with 90,000 already resettled there.
   ``We call upon the United Nations and the international
community to intervene and stop this war of genocide against our
people,'' he said.
   The Turkish and Iranian governments have reported that thousands
of Kurdish refugees have been streaming across their borders with
Iraq.
   In Turkey, Premier Turgut Ozal said Thursday that 60,000
refugees had arrived since the country opened its borders two weeks
ago.
   Iran supported the Kurdish guerrillas fighting for autonomy in
northern Iraq during the 8-year gulf war. Iraq launched an
offensive to crush the Kurdish rebellion after Iraq accepted a
U.N.-sponsored cease-fire Aug. 20.
   There are about 20 million Kurds living in the mountains where
the borders of Turkey, Iran and Iraq meet, and Syria and the Soviet
Union have small Kurdish enclaves.
   Iraq's 3.5 million Kurds have been fighting on and off for an
autonomous homeland for 50 years.
</TEXT>
