<HEAD>West German Fighter Jet Crashes Into North Sea</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GLUECKSBURG, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A West German fighter jet
plunged into the North Sea today, leaving wreckage and empty life
rafts afloat at the scene, but no sign of the two-man crew, the
navy said.
   Navy aircraft, ships, and helicopters joined the search for the
pilot and weapons system officer of the Tornado jet, which crashed
about 10 miles miles north of the East Frisian island of Langeoog,
the navy said in a statement.
   Langeoog is six miles north of the West German coastline on the
North Sea.
   Rescue teams found two empty, inflatable life rafts and wreckage
but the crew was missing. The two men may be floating in the sea in
their life vests and the search was continuing, the statement said.
   Navy spokesmen said they did not know the cause of the crash,
which occurred during a routine training mission at about 9:00 a.m.
   The Tornado jet was assigned to Navy Flight Squadron One, which
is based near the northern West German town of Schleswig, 25 miles
north of Hamburg.
