<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Soviet-Solzhenitsyn     09-02 0470</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Solzhenitsyn,0484</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Expelled Author Invited to Join Memorial Committee for Stalin
Victims</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Alexander Solzhenitsyn, who was expelled from the
Soviet Union after he chronicled the horrors of Josef Stalin's
rule, was asked to join an officially sanctioned committee building
a monument to Stalin's victims.
   An organizer said today the move did not necessarily indicate an
easing in official attitudes toward the dissident writer, whose
works angered the Kremlin, but reflected the number of Soviet
citizens who think Solzhenitsyn is one of the best qualified people
to serve on the committee.
   Solzhenitsyn, who won the 1970 Nobel Prize in literature, wrote
``The Gulag Archipelago,'' which traces the history of political
repression in the Soviet Union, especially the purges and
repression during Stalin's 29-year reign.
   Solzhenitsyn, who himself spent eight years in labor camps under
Stalin, was expelled from the Soviet Union in 1974 following the
publication of the ``Gulag'' trilogy in the West. He now lives in
Vermont.
   Under Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev, Stalin and his legacy
have received increasingly severe criticism. In July, the ruling
Communist Party Politburo approved the building of a monument in
Moscow to Stalin's victims.
   On Aug. 25, a public council to supervise the construction and
maintenance of the monument was formed, as well as an executive
committee to submit a blueprint for the memorial's design.
   Among those selected for the public council were Solzhenitsyn,
fellow dissident and Nobel Peace laureate Andrei D. Sakharov, poet
Yevgeny Yevtushenko and Boris Yeltsin, the fiery former Moscow
party boss.
   Yuri Samadunov, a member of the executive committee, said
members of the public council had been chosen in street polls
conducted at two central Moscow locations, as well as from names
submitted by readers to Literaturnaya Gazeta, Ogonyok and other
state-run publications.
   ``We chose the first 17 people mentioned, and Solzhenitsyn was
among them,'' Samadunov said in a telephone interview.
   This week's edition of Moscow News listed Solzhenitsyn as a
member of the public council charged with building the memorial.
   However, Samadunov said the committee had not yet been able to
notify Solzhenitsyn that he had been selected for the committee, or
to determine whether he would agree to take part in its work.
   ``We sent him a telegram with news of his selection and that of
the others, and asked his agreement, but the telegram was returned
to us with a notice that it could not be delivered because the
address was not precise enough,'' said Samadunov.
   Solzhenitsyn's wife has previously denied that the writer
intends to visit the Soviet Union.
   In June, the editor of the literary monthly Novy Mir said he was
negotiating for the right to print Solzhenitsyn's novel ``Cancer
Ward,'' which would mark the first publication of the author's work
in his native land since he was expelled in 1974.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880902-0098 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-02-88 1025EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-DrugIndictments     09-02 0406</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Drug Indictments,0419</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Indictments Announced In $1.6 Billion Drug Ring</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MONTGOMERY, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A billion-dollar drug ring gunned down
the mother of a potential witness, hatched terrorist-like plots to
free their jailed kingpin and laundered profits through phony coal
companies, prosecutors allege.
   U.S. Attorney Jim Wilson on Thursday announced the indictment of
25 alleged members of the ring on conspiracy, racketeering and
obstruction charges. Eighteen were in custody Thursday; the others
remained at large.
   The ring, described as one of the biggest in the Southeast,
smuggled 33 tons of cocaine worth $1.6 billion into the United
States over five years, Wilson said.
   Jerry Allen LeQuire, the alleged ringleader, has been in prison
since before his conviction in a 1983 smuggling operation involving
about 710 pounds of high-grade Colombian cocaine.
   Bill Warner, a Drug Enforcement Administration agent, said that
case launched the probe that resulted in the indictment unsealed
this week.
   Cocaine was brought from Colombia into small or remote airports
in Alabama, Georgia and Tennessee and hauled to Florida, Kentucky
and Tennessee for sale, authorities said.
   Wilson said the ring set up several phony coal companies in
Kentucky and one in North Carolina to launder its profits, which
helped finance a lavish life of yachts and Jaguars for some members.
   Members of the ring committed crimes ranging from the
machine-gun slaying of a witness' mother to witness tampering and
attempting to record grand jury proceedings, prosecutors said.
   In one of the alleged escape plots hatched to free LeQuire from
prison, LeQuire in 1985 came up with a scheme to blow up power
lines, airports, dams and Naval vessels to convince authorities
that terrorists were active in the United States, according to the
indictment, which gave no further explanation.
   The organization had profits totaling more than $280 million in
the year beginning July 1982 alone, and the same amount of cash was
buried in vaults on a farm in Greenback, Tenn., Wilson said.
   ``This is probably one of the biggest (importation operations)
in the Southeastern United States,'' said FBI agent Gerald Shockley.
   The indictment, unsealed Tuesday in Knoxville, Tenn., and
announced here Thursday, named LeQuire as the leader of a gang that
Wilson said smuggled 33 tons of cocaine, one ton of marijuana and
1,200 methaqualone tablets into the Southeast from 1981 to 1986.
   Ira DeMent, an attorney who along with defense lawyer F. Lee
Bailey is representing LeQuire, had no comment on the indictment.
</TEXT>
