<1ST_LINE>u w PM-DrunkenDriving     09-02 0223</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Drunken Driving,220</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>MADD Focusing on Drunken Driving This Weekend</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mothers Against Drunk Driving and other
organizations will focus attention this weekend on efforts to end
drunken driving with national advertisements, local events and a
request that motorists turn on their headlights, officials
announced today.
   Representatives of MADD, federal, state and local governments
and Volkswagen United States Inc. asked Americans to promise to not
drink and drive on Saturday and to show support for the ``Drive for
Life'' program by driving with their headlights on.
   ``We're asking all Americans to make this pledge with the hope
that they will continue their commitment never to drink and
drive,'' Norma Phillips, national president of MADD, told a news
conference.
   Last year, 23,632 Americans were killed and 560,000 were injured
in accidents attributed to drunken driving, according to MADD. On
last year's Drive for Life day, the traffic fatality rate dropped
28 percent, MADD says.
   ``We must constantly remind the American people of these
statistics, and do all we can to mobilize them to stop the
carnage,'' said Transportation Secretary Jim Burnley.
   Under a congressional resolution signed by President Reagan,
this weekend has been proclaimed National Drive for Life Weekend.
Over the long Labor Day weekend, the rate of fatal accidents caused
by drunken driving usually increases by 10 percent, MADD says.
</TEXT>
