<1ST_LINE>r a PM-HumanFly     09-02 0231</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Human Fly,0237</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>`Human Fly' Burglar Eludes Police</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A burglar dubbed by authorities The Human Fly is
apparently scaling high-rise buildings and entering apartments
through open balcony doors, police said.
   The burglar has made nearly 50 nighttime hits in southeast
Denver during the last six months.
   ``He's got to be athletic _ either a mountain climber or someone
skilled,'' said Sgt. Bill Wiederspan. ``We think he's got to have
some climbing equipment.''
   Earlier this week, in one night, six apartments in a 10-story
building were burglarized, police said. The apartments were on the
third, sixth, eight, ninth and 10th floors and were entered through
balcony doors.
   Police said The Fly may want thrills as much as money. His
high-flying antics have cost his victims an average of only about
$50, and his takes have ranged from $20 to $500, police said.
   The Fly has left some clues _ an occasional shoe print on a
balcony railing or a screen door removed from its track.
   ``Originally, we hesitated to believe the victims,'' Wiederspan
said. ``We thought it might have been an internal theft. You get a
burglary on the eighth floor of a building you hesitate to believe
someone is capable of doing it.''
   But as more reports came in, police theorized he scales the
sides of buildings and may occasionally exit through a hallway
door, police said.
</TEXT>
