<DOCNO> AP880902-0102 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-02-88 1047EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Iran-Iraq     09-02 0442</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Iran-Iraq,0455</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rafsanjani: Iraq Attempting to Rekindle War</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NEIL MacFARQUHAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iran's commander in chief today said
Iraq's claim to the disputed waterway at the southern end of their
border was an attempt to rekindle the war, the official Islamic
Republic News Agency reported.
   In a prayer sermon at Tehran University, Hashemi Rafsanjani
attacked Iraq's demand that the waterway _ known as the
Shatt-al-Arab in Iraq and as the Arvand River in Iran _ be dredged
and cleared of wreckage.
   Rafsanjani, also parliament speaker, said Iraq started the war
``with the prime goal of gaining control of the Arvand River and
was trying to rekindle it by repeating its aborted claim on the
waterway,'' the IRNA report said.
   Iran wants a 1975 treaty that split the waterway down the middle
to remain in effect, but Iraq claims the agreement is void.
   In Baghdad, the government-run daily Ath-Thawra said it expected
peace negotiations to ``be difficult, exactly like the difficulty
of war.''
   The newspaper said the Iranian government had nullified the
treaty by declaring in 1980 that all agreements signed by Shah
Mohammed Reza Pahlavi were invalid. The shah was overthrown by an
Islamic revolution in 1979 .
   With regard to the negotiations, ``The most important thing is
to realize that this is our chance to get all our rights on land,
at sea and in the air,'' the newspaper said.
   In Tehran, Rafsanjani said soldiers at the front must remain
vigilant because there is a chance the war could start again.
``Even if the possibility of war becomes only 10 percent or 20
percent, we must remain attentive.''
   Rafsanjani's remarks also were broadcast by Tehran Radio. Both
reports were monitored in Nicosia.
   ``We want our armed forces to respect and obey the cease-fire,
but in case the enemy does not, they (Iran's forces) have a right
to respond,'' said Rafsanjani, echoing remarks he made in a
television interview Thursday.
   Both sides have made repeated belligerent statements over the
past few days as U.N.-sponsored peace talks in Geneva sputtered
over troop withdrawals and control of the waterway.
   The foreign ministers of Iran and Iraq have not met for a week,
although talks have continued at a lower level. Negotiations
started Aug. 25.
   In Geneva, Iranian Foreign Minister Ali Akbar Velayati charged
today that Iraq has violated the gulf war cease-fire more than 60
times since it took effect two weeks ago, and he said Iraq was
blocking progress in the peace talks by raising ``new
preconditions'' every day.
   U.N. observers have not reported any serious cease-fire
violations, only minor problems that they said were resolved.
</TEXT>
