<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880902-0103 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-02-88 1051EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-GulfTalks 2ndLd-Writethru a0542 09-02 0710</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Gulf Talks, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0542,0728</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iran Accuses Iraq Of 60 Cease-Fire Violations</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 3 grafs to UPDATE with Rafsanjani's comments.
Pickup 4th graf pvs, ``Velayati spoke...''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By VICTORIA GRAHAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iranian Foreign Minister Ali Akbar Velayati today
charged that Iraq has violated the cease-fire in the Persian Gulf
war more than 60 times since it took effect two weeks ago.
   Velayati also said Iraq was raising new conditions every day to
block progress in peace talks aimed at ending the eight-year
conflict.
   In Tehran, Iran's commander in chief accused Iraq of trying to
rekindle the war by claiming the disputed Shatt-al-Arab waterway,
the official Islamic Republic News Agency reported. The commander,
Hashemi Rafsanjani, made the remarks during a prayer sermon today
at Tehran University.
   Velayati spoke to reporters as he left the U.N. building after
meeting with Jan Eliasson, a Swedish diplomat who is the new U.N.
special representative for the talks. Shortly afterward, Iraqi
Foreign Minister Tariq Aziz also met Eliasson to brief him on
Iraq's position at the talks.
   Iraq is prepared to continue working ``sincerely and seriously''
toward full agreement on implementing the U.N. cease-fire
resolution that forms the basis of the negotiations, Aziz told
reporters.
   He did not comment on Velayati's allegations.
   Both sides have traded charges of cease-fire violations. But
U.N. observers monitoring the truce did not report any serious
violations by either side, only ``minor problems'' that were
resolved.
   ``After the establishment of the cease-fire, Iraq has had more
than 60 kinds of violations of the terms of the cease-fire,''
Velayati said. ``We have some difficulties because day-by-day they
raise some new preconditions.''
   The two 90-minute meetings were Eliasson's first talks with
Velayati and Aziz on substantial issues. Eliasson was formally
introduced to them by U.N. Secretary-General Javier Perez de
Cuellar after Eliasson's appointment Thursday.
   The two ministers have not met face-to-face since Aug. 26, when
the talks stalled. Negotiations have continued at a lower,
technical level since.
   Perez de Cuellar, who had mediated the talks since they began
Aug. 25, left Geneva on Thursday because of other commitments. He
said he was frustrated by the slow pace of the talks but that he
was trying to end the stalemate. He said he would return to Geneva
if necessary.
   The talks are stalled over follow-up procedures to the
cease-fire that went into effect Aug. 20.
   The major problem is the Shatt-al-Arab waterway, which forms the
southern border between the two nations and is Iraq's only outlet
to the sea.
   Iraq wants full control of the waterway and has repudiated a
1975 treaty that gave Iran control of half of the Shatt-al-Arab.
Iran says any peace settlement must include strict adherence to
that treaty.
   A U.N. compromise would guarantee free navigation for both
nations in the Persian Gulf, withdrawal to internationally
recognized borders and an impartial study of conflicting positions
on the Shatt-al-Arab.
   The cease-fire resolution also calls for prisoner exchange and
the work of a commission to determine which side started the war.
   On Thursday, Iran accused Iraq of taking more than 750 Iranian
troops prisoner in attacks since the cease-fire began. The Iraqi
government said Iran continued setting up observation posts and
bunkers, moving troops close to the border and launching gunboats
into the Shatt-al-Arab.
   A U.N. report Thursday said Iran brainwashed Iraqi prisoners of
war, turning many into fanatical supporters of Iran. The report
also said many POWs from both nations are afraid to return home.
   The report was compiled by Maj. Gen. Rene Bats of the Belgian
army and international law professors Wolfram Karl of the
University of Salzburg, Austria, and Torkel Opsahl of the
University of Oslo, Norway.
   POW camps in Iran were dominated by Iraqi prisoners who swore
allegiance to Iran's Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini and denounced
Iraq's President Saddam Hussein as an atheist, the report said.
   ``Cultural Committees'' in the camps provided religious and
political instruction called ``spiritual guidance,'' it said. ``To
us, it is indistinguishable from mental pressure.''
   In Iraq, the report found no mental indoctrination of Iranian
POWs but said the prisoners also were worried about going home.
   The U.N. investigators estimated that Iran may be holding up to
70,000 POWs, and Iraq may have about 35,000 prisoners.
</TEXT>
