<DOCNO> AP880902-0104 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-02-88 1053EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-TropicalWeather     09-02 0186</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Tropical Weather,0190</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New Tropical Storm Develops Off Mexico</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A weather system in the Gulf of Mexico strengthened
today into tropical storm Debby and was expected to bring up to 10
inches of rain to parts of Mexico.
   The Mexican government posted storm warnings from Santa Cruz to
Vera Cruz for Debby, which had maximum sustained wind of 40 mph,
with gusts up to 50 mph, said National Hurricane Center forecaster
Hal Gerrish.
   At 8 a.m. EDT, Debby was 180 miles southeast of Tampico, Mexico,
moving west at 8 mph.
   ``Locally heavy rains up to 10 inches can be expected over
portions of Mexico,'' Gerrish said. ``Some flash floods and mud
slides may occur in the warned area and inland today and tonight.''
   The storm, designated a tropical storm and named Debby when its
sustained wind passed the minimum 39 mph, was expected to weaken
and die out soon after hitting the coast.
   Debby is the fourth named storm of the 1988 Atlantic hurricane
season. None have reached the 74 mph wind speed at which a storm is
classified as a hurricane.
</TEXT>
