<1ST_LINE>r a PM-DeltaCrash-Abort 1stLd-Writethru a0485 09-02 0677</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Delta Crash-Abort, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0485,0691</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pilot Aborts Flight That Ended In Crash Day Before</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS two grafs after the 7th, `Delta declined ...,' to
UPDATE with today's flight.</NOTE>
<HEAD>With PM-Delta Crash, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUZANNE GAMBOA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GRAPEVINE, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An ``extremely cautious'' Delta Air
Lines pilot aborted takeoff when a panel indicator warned of
possible engine trouble on Flight 1141, on which a jet crashed and
burned a day earlier.
   Six people aboard aborted Flight 1141 Thursday were among the 95
survivors of Wednesday's crash at Dallas-Fort Worth International
Airport, which killed 13. The doomed plane also was a Boeing 727.
   ``He was only at a maximum of 20 knots (23 mph) ... which is
pretty slow for an airplane,'' said Glenda Johnson, a Delta
spokeswoman in Atlanta. ``Then he gets an indicator on the panel
that there is a momentary disruption of air flow'' in one of the
engines.
   ``The captain feels that he had what is called a compressor
stall,'' said another Delta spokesman, Bill Berry. ``There was a
crosswind blowing across the runway. That can interrupt the
smoothness of the airflow that goes into the engine, creating a
temporary loss of power.''
   Under normal circumstances, a pilot would ``simply increase
thrust to see if everything continued to perform right. But based
on the incident that happened yesterday, the captain was extremely
cautious and elected simply to come back to the gate and let
maintenance look at the engine,'' Berry said.
   On any day, Berry said, captains ``have got to go by their years
of experience'' and can abort flights ``if they don't like what
they feel, if they've just got a gut feeling.''
   Delta declined to release the pilot's name.
   Today, Delta Flight 1141 departed Dallas-Fort Worth without
incident. The flight was airborne at 8:49 a.m., a few minutes
behind schedule.
   Delta officials at the terminal declined to talk to reporters,
but several passengers who regularly take Flight 1141 said the
plane carried only about half as many passengers as usual.
   Wednesday's Flight 1141, bound for Salt Lake City, crashed and
burned shortly after takeoff. Federal investigators said the
aircraft may have experienced an engine malfunction as it left the
runway.
   Delta officials said no maintenance problems were found in the
engine of the jetliner whose takeoff was aborted. Although
officials said there never was any danger, many passengers appeared
jolted after the plane returned to the gate.
   ``We figured this would be the safest flight we could ever take
today,'' said Louise Cox of Baton Rouge, La., as she waited to
board another 727 for Salt Lake City. ``Evidently not.''
   ``It was a routine takeoff until we got almost to the end of the
runway,'' said Assistant U.S. Attorney Don Burkhalter of Jackson,
Miss., where the flight originated. ``Then we heard what sounded
like bumps and the pilot decelerated. He said there was a problem
with the `compressors,''' Burkhalter said.
   ``The captain said, and this is a quote, `It's just one of those
things.' We just laughed.''
   It was a nervous laughter, said Burkhalter, who was on his way
to Fresno, Calif., with his wife.
   Thursday's flight carried 102 passengers and a crew of seven,
said Delta spokesman Henry Conley in Dallas. Conley said that to
his knowledge, all the passengers got on a substitute plane.
   A survivor from Wednesday's crash said he had trouble working up
the courage to board Flight 1141 _ the flight that was aborted _ a
day after the accident.
   ``You've got to do it sometime,'' said Ronald Black, 30, of West
Monroe, La. ``Can't live in Dallas.''
   Burkhalter said two of the crash survivors aboard Thursday's
flight whom he talked to appeared relatively calm, although one
said ``he was a little nervous.''
   Passenger George Snelling, 30, of Dallas, said he missed
Wednesday's Flight 1141 because of a faulty alarm clock.
   Waiting to board the same flight Thursday, Snelling said, ``I'm
a little apprehensive, but when the time's up it's up and I would
have been on the plane yesterday.''
</TEXT>
