<1ST_LINE>r i PM-HotelBlast 1stLd-Writethru a0500 09-02 0446</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hotel Blast, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0500,0456</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>SWAPO Denies It Planted Bomb At Hotel</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 8 grafs to UPDATE with SWAPO denial and police
saying no one injured in railroad blast. Pickup 7th graf pvs,
``Firefighters needed...''</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   WINDHOEK, South-West Africa (AP) _ The South-West Africa
People's Organization today denied it planted a bomb at a hotel
patronized by blacks and blamed South Africa. The blast killed two
people and injured 15, police said.
   The three-story Continental Hotel was severely damaged by the
explosion Thursday evening. Witnesses said parked cars were hurled
across the street.
   About one mile away, a mine exploded 90 minutes later on a
railroad line, but no one was injured, police said. Hospital
officials earlier had said two people were hurt in the blast.
   The South-West Africa People's Organization, or SWAPO, has
fought since 1966 for independence for the South Africa-ruled
territory.
   It issued the denial from its office in Lusaka, Zambia, and
called the bombing one of ``South Africa's dirty tricks.'' The
statement said: ``It is not SWAPO's policy to attack soft targets.
This bomb attack was aimed at demoralizing white Namibians and
setting them against SWAPO.''
   The explosions occurred on the day SWAPO said it would begin a
voluntary cease-fire. The organization has fought a long guerrilla
war against South African control of South-West Africa, also known
as Namibia.
   The government-run broadcasting network said an anonymous
telephone caller claimed responsibility on behalf of the
guerrillas, and South Africa's chief representative in the
territory, Louis Pienaar, blamed the bombing on SWAPO.
   The guerrilla group normally attacks military targets or white
residential or shopping areas, but the hotel was patronized by
blacks. Pienaar did not explain why the guerrillas would bomb a
hotel patronized by blacks.
   Firefighters needed more than 90 minutes to bring the blaze
under control.
   SWAPO and other black groups have warned of a possible white
backlash in South-West Africa because of preliminary South African
proposals for independence elections that probably would result in
government by the black majority.
   SWAPO said its guerrillas would stop launching attacks in the
territory Thursday to contribute to a regional peace initiative
involving South Africa, Cuba, and Angola.
   South Africa has administered South-West Africa for 73 years,
despite repeated U.N. resolutions since 1966 calling for
independence in the territory.
   South Africa says it will begin withdrawing from South-West
Africa on Nov. 1 and allow independence elections June 1, 1989, if
Cuba pulls its 50,000 troops out of Angola by June 1.
   On Tuesday, South Africa said it has pulled all its troops out
of Angola, where it was fighting alongside rebels in their battle
against Angola's Marxist government and its Cuban allies.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
