<2ND_LINE>PM-Dukakis-Sasso, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0559,410</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis To Bring Former Aide Sasso Back Into Campaign</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS two grafs after 4th graf to include detail; picks up
5th graf pvs, bgng: Sasso, who...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis today will bring back to his
campaign John Sasso, its former manager, who resigned last year
after leaking a videotape that helped drive Delaware Sen. Joseph
Biden from the Democratic presidential race.
   Sasso, Dukakis' closest political confidant since 1982, will
rejoin the campaign as vice chairman, according to campaign sources
who spoke on the condition they not be named.
   Dukakis, the Democratic presidential nominee, will make the
announcement at news conference today in California, where his is
campaigning, the sources said.
   Sasso will appear at a separate news conference at noon in
Boston, along with his replacement as campaign manager, Susan
Estrich, and campaign chairman Paul Brountas.
   The move to rehire Sasso comes at a time when Dukakis has been
criticied for allowing his once double-digit lead in the polls to
disappear in the wake of aggressive attacks from Republican nominee
George Bush.
   Only in recent days has Dukakis begun to fire back, and sources
said Sasso was among those urging Dukakis to take a more aggressive
stance. ``He's the man the governor believes in most, will listen
to the most,'' said one of the sources.
   Sasso, who directed Dukakis' comeback as governor in 1982 and
then served as his Statehouse chief of staff, will take a leave
from his job at Hill & Holladay, an advertising firm he joined last
year after resigning the campaign job.
   Dukakis has stayed in close contact with Sasso since then mainly
by telephone, reluctant to appear together with his former top
aide. The vice chairman's job will be a paid campaign position, the
sources said.
   Sasso resigned from the campaign after telling Dukakis he was
responsible for leaking videotapes to the press showing that Biden
used words during a debate in Iowa taken almost verbatim from a
campaign speech by British Labor Party leader Neil Kinnock.
   Biden dropped out of the campaign after this and other instances
of alleged plagiarism were publicized. Another Dukakis campaign
aide, Paul Tully, also resigned because of his role in the incident.
   Dukakis, at first reluctant to accept Sasso's resignation, said
later that Sasso had used ``very poor judgment.''
   Dukakis also said Sasso ``will have no role in this campaign,''
but he refused to rule out a possible role for Sasso in a Dukakis
administration should he win in November.
</TEXT>
