<DOCNO> AP880902-0109 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-02-88 1108EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Brazil-Constitution     09-02 0514</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Brazil-Constitution,0537</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lawmakers Finish Brazil's New Constitution</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRASILIA, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Legislators today completed a l9-month
process of drafting a new constitution to replace an authoritarian
document handed down two decades ago by the military regime.
   The document shortens presidential terms to five years,
abolishes cencorship, guarantees the right of workers to strike and
rejects land reform.
   Elated lawmakers in the constituent assembly sang the national
anthem and threw confetti into the air when speaker Ulysses
Guimaraes closed the final sesion at 1:49 a.m.
   ``Brazil is a new country,'' Guimaraes said. ``This constitution
will protect the weak and punish those who abuse power.''
   The final version appeared to be a mixture of radical, even
nationalistic laws on foreign and domestic business and mainly
conservative laws on issues such as land reform.
   Since February 1987, legislators have been working on the new
charter, which replaces the 19-year-old constitution handed down by
military generals during a 1964-1985 military regime.
   The new 245-article charter is to go into effect Sept. 23. It
will be Brazil's eighth constitution in 166 years of independence.
   The 559 representatives and senators chosen in wide-ranging 1986
elections have been voting for several weeks on the more than 1,000
amendments to the 245-article final draft, which was completed in
July.
   The draft itself was the result of more than a year of voting on
an initial draft of more than 3,000 articles, derided by many
because of its length.
   Over the past 19 months, legislators engaged in heated and often
even violent debate over such controversial issues as land reform,
the system of government Brazil should adopt, the presidential term
and the right to strike.
   Some of the key decisions are:
   _President Jose Sarney and future presidents will serve for five
years, in contrast to the six-year term of former military
presidents.
   _Censorship, a remnant of military days, was abolished in films,
books and television.
   _The right to strike was guaranteed for all workers. Before,
``essential'' sectors of the labor force were not allowed to strike.
   _The assembly rejected wide-ranging land reform in a country
where four percent of the people own 50 percent of the farmable
land. This countered a government promise to distribute land to 1.4
million landless peasant farmers.
   _Decree law, a powerful tool used by the president to bypass
Congress and push through legislation, was also abolished.
   _The voting age was lowered from 18 to 16 years of age. The only
other country where 16 year olds can vote is Nicaragua.
   _Maternity leave for new mothers was extended from 90 to 120
days and the work week was cut from 48 to 44 hours.
   _A 12 percent ceiling was imposed on interest rates charged
above inflation. Interest rates have been running as high 1,000
percent yearly, while inflation this year is expected to reach 700
percent.
   _Mineral mining was nationalized and foreign companies now
involved in mining will have to leave Brazil in four years or
transfer financial control to residents of the country.
   _New oil risk contracts allowing foreign companies to drill in
oil-rich Brazil were banned.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
