<2ND_LINE>PM-Forest Fire Rdp, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0549,0586</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Some Residents Leave West Yellowstone Community As Labor Day
Weekend Opens</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with seven grafs to UPDATE with morning conditions near
West Yellowstone; CLARIFIES that residents left rather than fled;
PICKS UP 6th graf pvs, `Earlier Thursday ...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Residents of a tourist town outside Yellowstone National Park
left overnight as a ``slop-over'' wildfire moved to within 1{
miles. Elsewhere in the West, campers were barred from the woods as
the Labor Day weekend opened.
   Wildfires also burned over hundreds of thousands of acres in
California, Idaho, Oregon, Utah, Washington and Wyoming.
   In West Yellowstone, Mont., residents and tourists filled their
gas tanks as flames to the west lit up the sky with an orange glow
Thursday night.
   ``There are some pretty nervous people, no question about
that,'' said Dawn Whitman, a gas station owner.
   The threat came from a quarter- to half-acre ``slop-over'' of a
109,100-acre fire inside the park. As the flames progressed,
residents watched smoke billow high into the air. Explosions set
off by firefighters cutting fire lines periodically shook buildings.
   ``The town was pretty excited last night,'' Brian Morris, a
Forest Service spokesman in West Yellowstone, said this morning.
   ``Things have calmed down a little. No evacuation has been
ordered, but we do have an evacuation plan in case one is
necessary.''
   Earlier Thursday, Yellowstone's south gate reopened for the
first time in almost two weeks, leaving all park entrances and
roads open.
   In eastern Oregon, recreational users were banned from 3.8
million acres of state-protected land beginning today. Already
closed are 2.8 million acres in western Oregon.
   In Idaho, lighter wind allowed firefighters breathing room on
the worst of 17 blazes, but activities were restricted in several
forests over the Labor Day weekend. Tight controls also were placed
on campfires in Washington state.
   ``It's like sitting on a time bomb,'' said Scott Phillips,
recreation officer for the Sawtooth National Recreation Area in
central Idaho. ``If we can get through this weekend without a
conflagration, it will be a miracle.''
   Progress was reported on two other major series of fires in
northeast Washington, but the forecast was for hot and dry weather
over the weekend, and U.S. Forest Service spokesman Paul Hart said,
``All these fires are real worries because any one of them can blow
up.''
   Crews battling five forest fires in California's mountain ranges
hoped to contain the blazes by today, but forest fire danger will
remain high throughout the holiday weekend, they predicted.
   Despite tinder-dry conditions, this year's fires have been much
smaller than last year's because there haven't been strong winds.
   Harley Greiman of the U.S. Forest Service warned, however, that
more lightning and temperatures in the 90s in the mountains are
expected during the Labor Day weekend, adding to the danger.
   In the Absaroka-Beartooth Wilderness along the Montana-Wyoming
border, crews had to be pulled back from a fire line Thursday along
a flank of a 47,200-acre fire when the blaze flared up and
destroyed portions of the line.
   ``The fire got rolling in there and it got too hot,'' said fire
information officer Chris Comstock. ``This is the fourth day we've
built good line and had to back up and let it go.''
   In Utah, strong ridgetop winds near the Pineview Reservoir
fanned a once-controlled fire into a 2,000-acre inferno threatening
high-voltage lines that bring power to the Salt Lake-Ogden-Provo
metropolitan area.
</TEXT>
