<2ND_LINE>PM-Cheerleader Controversy,0348</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Death Of High School Cheerleader Sparks Controversy Over
Replacement</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SALYERSVILLE, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A teen-ager who was named a high school
cheerleader after a member of the squad died in an auto accident
was dropped from the squad at the request of the dead girl's mother.
   The decision to remove Nikki Cheek, 14, from the junior varsity
cheerleader squad has sparked controversy at Magoffin County High
School.
   Christy Michelle Caudill, 14, a popular cheerleader, was killed
in a car-truck collision May 27 along with her 16-year-old brother
and another girl. Nikki was named to replace Christy, but on July
8, county Schools Superintendent Carter Whitaker removed her from
the squad at the request of Christy's mother, Carrie M. Caudill.
   Mrs. Caudill said Whitaker acted out of compassion for a mother
whose only children had died. Christy's spot on the squad, she
said, should be left vacant in her memory.
   ``It was a bad situation, a no-win situation,'' Whitaker said
today. ``It's hurting both families.''
   ``I know it really put him on a spot,'' said Mrs. Caudill. ``God
knows, I don't want to hurt another kid, but I just think as hard
as my daughter worked at it, and she's gone; in memory of her, they
ought to hold it open.''
   But Nikki's mother and father, Patty and Jim Cheek, criticized
the action. In a letter to the Salyersville Independent, they
expressed ``deepest sympathy'' for Mrs. Caudill but said she and
Whitaker had decided ``to hurt another innocent child.''
   Nikki received threatening phone calls after being named to
replace Christy ``saying she shouldn't be taking the place of a
girl that was killed in the accident,'' the letter said.
   The letter also said Nikki attended six or seven practices
before she was removed.
   Mrs. Caudill said she discussed the situation with Mrs. Cheek
several weeks after Nikki was named a cheerleader.
   ``I told Mrs. Cheek that Nikki had other years she could be
cheerleader,'' Mrs. Caudill said. ``Christy could not try out
again.''
