<1ST_LINE>r a PM-DisabledCadet     09-02 0307</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Disabled Cadet,0318</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cadet, Injured In Accident, Faces Possible Dismissal From Academy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AIR FORCE ACADEMY, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Air Force cadet who lost part
of a leg in an auto accident faces dismissal from the academy
because of a rule prohibiting amputees in the service, officials
said.
   Cadet Second Class Dan Korslund, 20, of Tacoma, Wash., has asked
that he be allowed to continue his studies and graduate with the
Class of 1991 with a bachelor of science degree even though he
can't receive an Air Force commission.
   A medical review board is studying the case, and an official
recommendation has not yet been made to Air Force Secretary Edward
Aldridge, said academy spokesman Will Ketterson.
   But Air Force regulations prohibit anyone ``who has lost a limb,
including a foot, leg or thigh,'' from military service, and
therefore from academy enrollment, Ketterson said.
   ``It is very unlikely Cadet Korslund will return to the Air
Force Academy,'' Ketterson said.
   Korslund was injured in an accident June 21, and his right leg
was amputated 8 inches below the knee. He was a promising defensive
tackle on the academy's football team.
   His possible dismissal drew criticism from a handicapped rights
group, which staged a protest Thursday outside the academy's chapel.
   Members of American Disabled for Accessible Public, many in
wheelchairs, handed out leaflets protesting ``the hypocrisy of the
U.S. government and the Air Force.''
   They cited the 1973 Rehabilitation Act that prohibits any
discrimination against the disabled by any agency receiving federal
funds. They carried signs reading: ``USAF Academy Discriminates,''
``Disabled and Ready to Serve'' and ``Be All You Can _ Except
Disabled.''
   Sen. William L. Armstrong, R-Colo., also has asked the Air Force
to let Korslund stay.
   Korslund is a patient at University Hospital in Denver and is
expected to be transferred to a Veterans Administration hospital.
</TEXT>
