<1ST_LINE>u a PM-Dukakis 2ndLd-Writethru a0581 09-02 0806</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dukakis, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0581,790</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Calls Dismissed Campaign Manager Sasso Back to Help</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Top 15 grafs new with Sasso announcement; picks up pvs 4th
graf bgng, Dukakis was.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DONALD M. ROTHBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN JOSE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis, saying ``I want the
strongest team I possibly can,'' announced today that John Sasso,
who resigned under fire a year ago, was returning to the Democratic
presidential campaign as vice chairman.
   ``Almost a year ago, John Sasso made a very serious mistake,''
Dukakis told a news conference. ``He's paid the price.''
   Sasso resigned as campaign manager last Sept. 30 after it was
disclosed he was responsible for putting together and leaking a
videotape demonstrating that a rival Democratic candidate, Sen.
Joseph Biden Jr. of Delaware, was using without attribution the
campaign rhetoric of British Labor Party leader Neil Kinnock.
   The questioned passage came from a Kinnock speech in which he
described his personal background. Biden incorporated Kinnock's
words to describe his own background.
   Sasso resigned the day after Dukakis had told a news conference
that no one in his campaign was involved in leaking the videotape.
   Dukakis said he told Biden he wanted to bring Sasso back into
the campaign, and the senator ``could not have been more gracious.''
   Dukakis denied that Sasso's return was linked to his decline in
public opinion polls in his race against Republican nominee George
Bush.
   ``I want the strongest team I possibly can,'' he said, noting
that Labor Day _ next Monday _ is the traditional start of the
stretch drive of the presidential campaign.
   Dukakis described Sasso as ``a uniquely talented individual who
can provide real strength.''
   Asked if he thought Sasso's return would blunt Democratic
charges of ethical violations by members of the Reagan
administration, Dukakis replied that ``there was nothing illegal
about what John did.''
   As new vice chairman of the Dukakis campaign, Sasso will
undertake unspecified duties which the candidate said were
undetermined.
   He said Susan Estrich would remain as campaign manager, and Paul
Brountas would continue as campaign chairman.
   Dukakis' announcement came as he wound up a West Coast campaign
swing stressing his interest in education and accusing the Reagan
administration of trying to scuttle school programs.
   The Massachusetts governor's backers said the battle for
California's crucial 47 electoral votes was ``dead even.''
   Dukakis said Thursday that Bush had undergone ``an election-yar
conversion on the subject of education.''
   Dukakis was planning to continue that emphasis during
appearances today in Portland, Ore., and Spokane, Wash., as schools
open.
   Dukakis said the voters this fall would ``face a choice between
two very different ideas of prosperity and two very different
records of leadership.''
   He said it was a choice ``between those who see education as a
lifetime commitment and those who see it as an election year
strategy.''
   During the speech to teachers and school officials in Oakland,
Dukakis said the Reagan administration had eliminated remedial math
and reading programs for 500,000 poor children, had cut teacher
retraining and ``led an assault on college loans and grants.''
   By contrast, he said that in Massachusetts he had quadrupled
scholarship assistance to low- and middle-income students and
invested in Professional Development Centers to help teachers
update their skills.
   The Reagan administration unsuccessfully sought cuts in the
remedial programs in 1981. In an April 1988 report, the Education
Department said the number of children in remedial programs had
dropped from 5 million in 1979-80 to 4.5 million in the 1985-86
school year.
   ``While they've invested billions in Star Wars, we've developed
a regional network of star schools,'' Dukakis said.
   ``And where was George when all this was going on?'' Dukakis
said, echoing a theme from the Democratic convention last July.
``Where was the man who now says he wants to be the `education
president'?
   ``He was playing hooky. He was nowhere to be found.''
   Meanwhile, Anthony Podesta, who is running the Dukakis campaign
in California, said he now has 70 full-time employees, a number he
said would grow to 500 by mid-October.
   ``We're going to run a field organization beyond the
imagination,'' Podesta said. ``We'll have a precinct captain in
every precinct in the state _ 29,000 of them.''
   Podesta called the race between Dukakis and Bush ``dead even''
in California, an assessment also given by state Democratic
Assemblyman Tom Hayden.
   Hayden said California voters ``want change'' and that while
Dukakis ``promises change, he's also not a wild man.''
   ``Dukakis is the most acceptable Democratic candidate we've had
in a very long time statewide,'' he said.
   ``I don't think Bush conveys an image of change,'' Hayden said.
``He's been in office, he's the vice president, he's the
establishment.''
   At the same time, Hayden said Dukakis must reassure California
voters ``he's for stable defense spending,'' because of the large
number of defense-related companies in the state.
</TEXT>
