<1ST_LINE>u i AM-UprisingBabies Bjt   09-02 0481</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Uprising Babies, Bjt,0493</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Uprising Spawns Names of Pride for Palestinian Newborns</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HAITHAM HAMAD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BETHLEHEM, Occupied West Bank (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nearly 9-month-old
rebellion against Israel has inspired new parents among the
Palestinians to give their babies such names as Uprising,
Revolution, Victory, Struggle and Sacrifice.
   An official at Al Ittihad Hospital in Nablus, one of the West
Bank's largest hospitals, said that of 247 births in the last two
weeks in July, 20 infants were given names connected with the
uprising.
   He cited Freedom and Liberation as other new names being given
Palestinian children, noting Liberation had been used for both boys
and girls.
   But the official, who asked not to be identified, said some
parents were hestitant for fear the names would not be allowed when
they went to register births with Israeli authorities.
   Atef Hajouj, of Bani Naim in the occupied West Bank, said he ran
into trouble when he named his daughter ``Intifadeh,'' the Arabic
word for uprising. He said officials at the Interior Ministry told
him the name was illegal.
   ``They told me to change her name or I will be fined,'' Hajouj,
24, said in an interview. ```One intifadeh is enough,' they said.''
   Hajouj's wife, Yussrah, insists the name is perfect for the
child, now 5 months old. ``It's very simple. She was born in the
victorious intifadeh and she deserves to be named Intifadeh,'' Mrs.
Hajouj said.
   Interior Ministry spokeswoman Tova Elinson said Israel has no
policy of preventing Palestinians from naming their children
whatever they wish.
   ``Everyone is allowed to register newborns, no matter what his
name,'' Ms. Elinson said. ``Some names may not be recorded when
several are recorded at once, but that's only because the computer
abbreviates them.''
   Rabah Manasreh, 29, from the same village, had her first baby on
April 2 and named the girl Nidaa, the Arabic word for ``appeal,''
because an uprising leaflet titled ``Appeal No. 12'' appeared that
day.
   ``I think it was a special day so I decided to name her Appeal
in memory of the intifadeh,'' Mrs. Manasreh said.``It is the least
support that I can give to the intifadeh.''
   In Bethlehem, 4-month-old Ansar Abed is named for the prison
where her father, Yasser, was jailed when she was born.
   Her 27-year-old father remains in the Negev desert prison camp
in Ketziot, which Palestinians call Ansar III after an Israeli
detention center at Ansar in Lebanon set up during Israel's
occupation of southern Lebanon.
   ``It was her father's wish,'' said his wife, Kifayah. ``He sent
messages through prisoners leaving the prison asking me to name the
baby Thaher, the Arabic word for `revolutionary' if it was a boy,
and Ansar if it was a girl.''
   ``The reason I named her Ansar is that the girl must know that
when she was born her father was detained in Ansar,'' she said.
</TEXT>
