<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Burma-Newspaper     09-02 0434</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Burma-Newspaper,0448</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>First Privately Owned Newspaper Appears</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Burma Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SEIN WIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RANGOON, Burma (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Burma's first legal privately owned
newspaper in 26 years began publishing Friday, and it said it would
present the ``true and unbiased news.''
   In its four pages, the People's View printed photographs and
accounts of demonstrations in Rangoon against the authoritarian
government, and of student protests last month outside the Burmese
embassies in Thailand and Bangladesh.
   It also carried the full text of President Maung Maung's address
to the nation Thursday in which he rejected calls for an interim
government to lead Burma back to democracy, which ended with a
military coup in 1962.
   People's View said it would be enlarged and carry foreign news
when conditions improved, and declared in its first editorial:
   ``Under the current conditions of scarcity of newsprint, ink and
other materials, the first privately owned newspaper is published
to cater to the people with true and unbiased news of the
prevailing situation.''
   It did not editorialize about the political turmoil in Burma.
   No price was printed on the front page, but People's View was
selling for up to 34 cents, several times the cost of the generally
distrusted government newspapers.
   The new morning paper's owner and publisher is Kyaw Nyein and
the editor is Tun Tha, sports editor of the government-run
newspaper Kyemon. People's View is licensed by the government but
not controlled by it.
   Rangoon's six other dailies, two in English four in Burmese, are
owned by the government.
   Twenty-one privately owned newspapers were published in Rangoon
before the coup by Gen. Ne Win, who nationalized all newspapers,
radio stations and television stations.
   Aye Ko, vice chairman of the State Council, told the legislature
Aug. 19 the government would permit privately run newspapers,
journals and magazines so as to ``provide an opportunity to bring
out the people's wants and desires and accurate news about what's
happening at work places and in regions.''
   Maung Maung assumed power the same day as the first civilian
leader since Ne Win's military coup.
   Ne Win resigned late in July and was succeeded by Sein Lwin, a
hard-line former general, who was driven from office in 17 days by
huge protests against 26 years of isolation and economic disaster.
   Employees of the government newspapers went on strike last
month, demanding greater press freedom, and kept the newspapers off
the streets for three days. They returned to work Aug. 28, saying
they had been assured their demands would be met.
   Several unauthorized newspapers have appeared, poorly printed
but selling for up to $1.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
