<1ST_LINE>r w AM-ToyotaRepairs     09-02 0184</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Toyota Repairs,180</2ND_LINE>
<BYLINE>FTC Asked to Order Toyota Warranty Disclosure</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federal Trade Commission should order
Toyota to directly notify owners of secret warranties on cars made
by the Japanese company, the Center for Auto Safety said in a
petition filed Friday.
   ``The Toyota documents clearly show that the company has an
internal policy that systematically reimburses consumers for
failure of specific components beyond the written warranty,'' said
Sam Cole of the center, a consumers group often critical of the
automakers and their regulators.
   ``Certainly ... every Toyota owner should be made aware,'' of
the policy, he said.
   An internal Toyota document, published last month by The Detroit
News, listed 41 components for which Toyota Motor Sales USA could
be reimbursed by its Japanese parent company.
   The document said an attachment was a ``complete `Secret
Warranty' listing.''
   After the document was published, Toyota said the listing
referred to reimbusement beyond the normal warranties under the
company's customer satisfaction policy rather than to secret
warranties.
   The center a year ago asked the FTC to require all manufacturers
to disclose secret warranties.
</TEXT>
