<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Singapore-Glance     09-02 0243</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Singapore-Glance,0253</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Singapore Parliamentary Elections At A Glance</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Singapore</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SINGAPORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is a look at Saturday's parliamentary
elections:
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   CANDIDATES: 87 for 42 seats in traditional single-member
districts. Another 13 constituencies elect only three-member teams
for a total of 81 seats in the unicameral legislature. They serve
five-year terms.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   PARTIES: Only the People's Action Party, which has controlled
this island republic since 1959 and won 11 seats unopposed on
nomination day, is contesting all districts. The Workers' Party
with 32 candidates and the Singapore Democratic Party with 18 are
the major opposition groups. Others are the National Solidarity
Party with 8, the United People's Front 5, Singapore Malay National
Organization 4, Singapore Justice Party 3, and Islamic Movement 1.
There are four independents.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   FORMER PARLIAMENT: Elected in December 1984, it had 79 seats,
with the PAP winning 77, and one each going to the Workers' Party
and the Singapore Democratic Party. When it was dissolved on Aug.
17 the PAP had 76 seats, the Democratic Party one and there were
two vacancies.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   MAIN ISSUE: A plan to amend the Constitution to change the
ceremonial presidency into an elected one with veto power over
spending financial reserves and nominations to senior civil service
and judicial positions.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   COMPULSORY VOTING: 1.5 million eligible in the 70 contested
districts. Voting hours 8 a.m. to 8 p.m. at 319 polling stations,
with results from 12 counting centers expected about midnight.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
