<DOCNO> AP880902-0132 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-02-88 1319EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Quayle     09-02 0312</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Quayle,300</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Quayle Attacks Dukakis On Defense, Says Bush on Farmer's Side</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN PUTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MONTGOMERY, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Dan Quayle attacked Democratic
nominee Michael Dukakis on Friday as ``flat wrong'' on defense and
foreign policy issues, and promised that Republican candidate
George Bush will be the American farmer's friend.
   Quayle, who is Bush's vice presidential running mate told an
Alabama audience that farmers should not have to compete against
``illegal subsidies'' that lower the prices of goods produced
overseas.
   ``As long as we can get that level playing field, the American
farmer will out-produce and be more competitive than any farmers in
the world,'' Quayle said.
   If the Bush-Quayle ticket is elected in November, he said,
``we're going to put the State Department on the side of the farmer
instead being on the side of the trading partners.''
   In a blast at Dukakis, Quayle said the Republican and Democratic
candidates disagree most sharply in their approach to national
defense.
   ``We believe in a strong national defense to deter aggression
against America, and he does not,'' Quayle said.
   ``On matters of national defense and foreign policy, believe me,
our opponent is not even half right. He's just flat wrong,'' Quayle
said.
   He said Dukakis needed ``some education about the defense of
America'' because of his opposition to the Star Wars space-based
missile defense system, the MX missile and other deterrent weapons
systems backed by the Reagan administration.
   ``Michael Dukakis needs an education _ that's for sure. But the
people ... are not about to let him get his on-the-job training in
the Oval Office at the expense of our security,'' Quayle said.
   Quayle's schedule called for a visit to Orlando, Fla., for a
student rally at the University of Central Florida, a GOP
fund-raising event and a tour of a laser research facility.
</TEXT>
