<1ST_LINE>r a PM-PowerOutage     09-02 0392</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Power Outage,0408</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Downtown Seattle Power Outage Extended to Saturday</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Seattle's worst-ever power outage will keep many
downtown businesses and apartment houses in the dark into the Labor
Day weekend, officials said.
   Utility officials Thursday said replacement of thousands of feet
of fire-damaged cable was taking more time than expected.
   Julia Greenlee, a City Light spokeswoman, said the expected time
for restoring electricity to the 40-block area had been pushed back
from tonight or Saturday morning to Saturday afternoon or evening.
   ``Maybe we were being too optimistic in our original estimate,''
Ms. Greenlee said.
   A smoky fire of undetermined origin wrecked an underground vault
containing two transformers and switching equipment Wednesday,
cutting electricity to much of the city's retail, financial and
hotel core and closing numerous businesses.
   Many restaurants that tried to stay open with limited service
were closed by health inspectors concerned about food spoilage and
potential sanitation problems.
   ``I probably closed 15 to 20 places myself,'' said Janet
Anderberg, senior environmental health specialist with the
Seattle-King County Health Department. ``We had places that were
cooking with candles and washing their hands without hot water.''
   No serious injuries have been reported, nor were there any
reports of looting as police increased patrols in the area.
   At Stewart House, residents pooled the contents of defrosting
refrigerators and held a barbecue in the courtyard for low-income
elderly and disabled residents.
   Generators were provided by City Light for five hotels with a
large share of elderly residents.
   About 70 City Light workers labored through the night Thursday,
Ms. Greenlee said.
   Authorities have refused to estimate the number of affected
businesses, workers and residents, dozens of whom have been
relocated until power is restored.
   Isabel Boldrin, 87, said she walked down 23 flights from her
place in a 26-story condominium to wash at a department store just
outside the outage area.
   The power failure left her without elevator service, and
residents of the upper 22 floors also were without water, she said.
   The almost complete blackout of banks in the area could leave
many residents who rely on government checks short of cash over the
Labor Day weekend.
   ``I talked to a lot of people today who were down to counting
their dimes and quarters,'' said the Rev. Carol Ludden, ``and you
can't go out to eat on dimes and quarters.''
</TEXT>
