<2ND_LINE>PM-Greece-Derailment, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0506,0281</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Six Killed in Train Derailment in Greece</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with police revising death toll to
six, more details. No pickup. Adds byline.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By HELENA SMITH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KINETTA, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A passenger train carrying more than 150
people derailed today, and three of its cars tumbled down a steep
embankment, killing six people, police said.
   A police spokesman said 29 people were injured, including two
Americans and at least 13 other foreign tourists.
   Earlier, police reported seven people were killed.
   The police spokesman, who spoke on condition of anonymity in
accordance with Greek practice, said the train was on its way from
Athens to Patras in western Greece.
   The six-car train derailed along a rocky coastline near this
resort area 35 miles west of Athens.
   ``We were going along and suddenly the train started falling. I
fell through the window and broke my arm, that's all I can
remember,'' a 23-year-old Czech passenger said from his hosptial
bed.
   The six victims and many of the injured had been sitting in the
two end cars, a medic at the scene told The Associated Press.
   ``Many of the passengers were crushed to death after they were
flung out of the windows. There were dismembered pieces of bodies
all over the place,'' said the medic, who declined to give his name.
   Several of the injured were reported to be suffering from shock.
   The police spokesman said the injured foreigners included seven
Britons, two Czechs, two Spaniards, an Argentine and a Finn. None
were in serious condition except for the Finnish woman, who
suffered a broken back.
</TEXT>
