<2ND_LINE>AM-Quayle-Health,270</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Quayle's Health Excellent, Doctor's Report Says</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dan Quayle's health is excellent and the
Republican vice presidential candidate suffers only from slightly
high cholesterol levels and minor skin and nasal problems, a
doctor's report released Quayle's office said Friday.
   Based on an Aug. 1 examination and a study of the Indiana
senator's medical and family history, Dr. Robert Krasner, senior
assistant attending physician at the U.S. Capitol, pronounced
Quayle healthy.
   ``In summary, you are a 41-year-old white male in excellent
health without any active problems,'' Krasner wrote in a letter to
Quayle dated Aug. 29.
   Quayle's cholesterol level of 228 is ``marginally elevated'' and
can be reduced by proper diet and exercise, Krasner wrote. The
senator rides a stationary bicycle one to three times weekly and
does not smoke, the report said.
   The doctor said Quayle suffers from a minor nosebleeding problem
and an unspecified seasonal allergy that causes nasal swelling, for
which he uses a nasal spray.
   The senator also has a slight skin condition on his face caused
by exposure to the sun. He treats the skin condition, called
actinic keratosis, with liquid nitrogen. The doctor recommended
that Quayle have the condition examined periodically and that he
use a sun screen.
   The candidate had a small rectal tear in the past, but the
August examination found no evidence of the problem persisting.
Krasner suggested an anal examination within the next year.
   Quayle is 5 feet 10 inches tall, weighs 176{ pounds, has 20-20
vision and had a precisely normal temperature reading of 98.6
degrees, the report said.
   The senator's office released Krasner's letter and summaries of
the doctor's findings and the laboratory results.
</TEXT>
