<1ST_LINE>r i PM-SouthAfrica 3rdLd-Writethru a0615 09-02 0619</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-South Africa, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0615,0632</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Political Leader's Home, Two Other Sites Bombed</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 12 grafs to UPDATE with black woman injured in
explosion in Durban clothing store. Pickup 11th graf pvs, ``The
anti...''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID CRARY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An explosion rocked downtown
Durban just after the evening rush hour today, extensively damaging
a clothing store and slightly injuring a black woman, police said.
   In other cities, a hand grenade was tossed at the home of South
Africa's leading mixed-race politician, and a bomb exploded in a
post office, but no injuries were reported in those attacks.
   Glass and concrete littered one of Durban's main streets
following the 5:45 p.m. blast, witnesses said. The explosion
occurred inside a street-level clothing store, causing major damage
to the shop and two adjacent stores, witnesses said.
   The street was largely deserted at the time of the explosion,
but had been full of traffic less than an hour earlier. Police
initially said no one was hurt, but later said a black woman
suffered minor injuries.
   The grenade attack in the Cape Province town of Uitenhage
damaged a parked car but did not hit the house of Rev. Allan
Hendrickse. The mine exploded inside a package at the post office
in Stranderton, southeast of Johannesburg.
   No group immediately claimed responsibility for any of the
attacks.
   More than 100 bombings have been reported in South Africa under
the 26-month state of emergency. Police have blamed virtually all
of the attacks on the outlawed African National Congress, the main
black group fighting to overthrow the white-dominated government.
   On Wednesday, a bombing destroyed a Johannesburg office building
used by anti-apartheid groups and explosions Thursday in Windhoek,
the capital of South-West Africa.
   Two people were killed and 15 injured Thursday when a bomb went
off at a hotel in Windhoek, the capital of South-West Africa, and a
mine exploded later alongside a railroad track near the city in the
South African-ruled territory. No injuries were reported in the
railroad bombing. Officials earlier had said two people were
injured.
   South Africa's chief representative in the territory, Louis
Pienaar, blamed the hotel bombing on pro-independence guerrillas of
the South-West African People's Organization. But SWAPO, which
began observing a voluntary cease-fire Thursday, denied the
allegation and blamed it on ``South Africa's dirty tactics.''
   Political and community leaders have expressed fears that the
attacks signal an escalation of retaliatory attacks by
anti-apartheid militants and by right-wing extremists.
   Hendrickse, leader of the Labor Party that controls the
mixed-race chamber of Parliament, was not at his home when the
grenade exploded about 1:05 a.m., but two of his children were in
the house.
   
   Anti-apartheid activists have criticized Hendrickse for agreeing
to mixed-race participation in the white-dominated Parliament, even
though the black majority remains excluded. Hendrickse this year
also defied President P.W. Botha several times by pressing for the
abolition of legally-enforced residential segregation.
   In what one newspaper called ``a humiliating defeat,'' Botha's
National Party on Thursday withdrew proposed bills that would have
given authorities greater powers to confiscate property and evict
and prosecute people living in areas not designated for their race.
   On Aug. 24, a Wimpy hamburger restaurant in Standerton also was
damaged by a limpet mine blast. Police blamed that attack on the
African National Congress.
   Under apartheid, South Africa's 5 million whites control the
economy and maintain separate districts, schools and health
services, giving the 26 million blacks no voice in national affairs.
   State-of-emergency regulations in effect since 1986 restrict
reporting about unrest, security force actions, treatment of
detainees, some forms of protest, and a broad range of statements
the government considers subversive. Enforcement of the regulations
has not been comprehensive.
</TEXT>
