<FILEID>AP-NR-09-02-88 1356EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Mandela     09-02 0458</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mandela,0472</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>White Anti-Apartheid Leader Visits Mandela in Clinic</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAPE TOWN, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A leading anti-apartheid member
of Parliament brought books, chocolates and fruit on Friday to
jailed black leader Nelson Mandela at the clinic where he is
recovering from tuberculosis.
   The activist lawmaker, Helen Suzman, has met with the African
National Congress leader several times during his 26 years in
prison. After the visit, she described Mandela as ``very
optimistic, very moderate and easy-going.''
   ``We did not talk in depth on politics and we did not discuss
his possible release,'' she said.
   She added, however: ``I remain, as over many years, convinced
that Mr. Mandela is a reasonable man and that he will play a
valuable part in any negotiation proceedings.''
   Mandela, 70, was transferred Wednesday from a state hospital to
the Constantiaberg Clinic, a new and relatively luxurious private
hospital in a Cape Town suburb. Mandela was moved Aug. 12 from
Pollsmoor Prison to Tygerberg, where doctors said he made a good
recovery following drainage of fluid from his lungs.
   Mandela, the country's best-known black leader, is serving a
life sentence for sabotage and plotting to overthrow the white-led
government.
   Mrs. Suzman met with Mandela for about an hour. She took him
fruit, chocolates and a book by the late South African writer Alan
Paton. During the visit she made a quick trip to a shop to buy
candied fruit that Mandela requested.
   She said the visit was her first with Mandela in more than two
years and came about because of persistent requests to Justice
Minister Kobie Coetsee following Mandela's hospitalization.
   Coetsee met with Mandela on Thursday and said the prisoner's
health had improved considerably.
   A pro-government newspaper, The Citizen, Friday quoted
unidentified government sources as saying the move to the clinic
was a ``goodwill gesture'' which officials hoped would prompt a
conciliatory response from Mandela and make his release possible.
   Mandela's lawyer, Ismail Ayob, has said he does not view the
transfer as an indication the government has decided to free
Mandela.
   Government officials had suggested previously that Mandela would
be moved to a clinic, and possibly allowed an increased flow of
visitors, before a final decision was made whether to release him
outright. Thus far, prison officials have not eased Mandela's
visiting priveliges.
   Mandela's full recuperation is likely to take a few months.
After that period, the government could choose whether to send him
back to prison or grant him freedom.
   President P.W. Botha said two weeks ago he was seriously
considering releasing Mandela but indicated he wanted Mandela to
renounce violence.
   Mrs. Suzman, 71, entered Parliament in 1953 and is its
longest-serving member. Between 1961 and 1974, she was the only
Parliament member for the anti-apartheid Progressive Federal Party.
 
</TEXT>
