<FILEID>AP-NR-09-02-88 1454EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-TeacherStricken     09-02 0285</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Teacher Stricken,0293</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Teacher Stricken By Heart Attack During Performance With Students</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Young performers fought back tears after a
popular music teacher suffered a heart attack during a concert, but
they went on with the show.
   E. O'Hara Spearman, supervisor of the elite honors music program
for the St. Louis school district, had finished his saxophone solo
with the honors stage band when he collapsed Thursday during a
welcoming ceremony put on by the St. Louis public schools for their
staff.
   ``I saw him backing up at the end of the number,'' said Larry
Wilson, band director at Woerner School, who was in the audience.
``At first I thought he was just adjusting the sound. But then I
thought something was wrong.''
   Spearman, 60, was listed in critical but stable condition Friday
at St. Louis University Hospital, a hospital spokesman said.
   After Spearman collapsed, the curtain was closed and William A.
Pearson, associate superintendent, suggested continuation of the
show because Spearman ``would want it that way.''
   While Spearman was being treated behind the curtain, dance
students from Marquette Visual and Performing Arts Middle School
did a jazz tap dance out front. Then ballet students from the
Visual and Performing Arts High School took front stage.
   But backstage, faces were tear-stained.
   Superintendent Jerome Jones then stopped the program before he
was scheduled to give the traditional welcoming speech, saying it
seemed inappropriate for the show to continue.
   The program is an annual tradition on the teachers' first day
back. Classes begin Tuesday.
   Spearman is credited with rejuvenating the district's honors
music program. About 150 high school students from all over the
city are accepted by audition into the program each year.
</TEXT>
