<DOCNO> AP880902-0146 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-02-88 1458EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BloodBank     09-02 0363</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Blood Bank,0372</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Blood Center Chastised Over AIDS Tests</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A blood center has been criticized by federal
officials for distributing 22 units of blood before completely
ensuring that they were not infected by the virus that causes AIDS,
the center's director says.
   Federal Drug Administration officials inspected the Belle
Bonfils Memorial Blood Center in July and said the center failed to
follow standard procedures by releasing blood that initially tested
positive for AIDS and hepatitis, said center director Dr. Robert
Chapman. Bonfils supplies blood to regional hospitals.
   The blood, which went to about 45 people, later tested negative
when new chemicals were used in followup tests, said Chapman.
   Blood center officials also retested all but two of the donors
of the blood, and all had negative test results for AIDS and
hepatitis, said Chapman.
   He said transfusion recipients were not contacted, because
officials are confident they were not infected.
   Chapman said the 22 blood units tested positive for the usually
fatal AIDS virus and hepatitis during one week in June.
``Ordinarily, we see maybe three to five test positive,'' he said.
   When any unit of blood tests positive, the center performs two
additional tests, said Chapman. If both followup tests are
negative, the blood is released. If one is positive, additional
tests are done and the blood may be discarded, said Chapman.
   The 22 units of blood in question did not pass both tests the
day after the initial tests read positive for AIDS and hepatitis.
But Chapman said laboratory technicians believed the tests were
defective and they released the blood.
   ``This was a really unusual number, and the lab felt something
was wrong with the test chemicals,'' the doctor said. ``New
chemicals were used the following week, and on retesting all those
units were negative'' for the diseases.
   ``Clearly this shows the tests were faulty,'' said Chapman.
``But ordinarily we would not use a unit when there is any
question. ... It's not the safest thing to do.''
   The center has instituted a policy requiring supervisors to
approve all units of blood that test positive for AIDS, said
Chapman. He said lab technicians had made those decisions
previously.
</TEXT>
