<2ND_LINE>PM-Bank Hostages, 4th Ld - Writethru, a0626,0266</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Employees Freed In Nashville Bank; Gunmen Apparently Escape</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with gunmen apparently escaped, other
detail. No pickup.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NS1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOE EDWARDS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police fired tear gas into a bank and
rushed the building in search of two holdup men who locked four
employees in an office as they arrived for work, but the gunmen had
apparently fled hours earlier.
   ``It's ironic the way it worked out,'' said Officer Douglas R.
Anderson. ``We were here to play it out until the end. We don't
feel silly.''
   The two men, armed with a sawed-off shotgun and a knife, had
broken in through a back window of the Third National Bank branch
and were waiting inside when it opened about 8 a.m., the spokesman
said.
   They locked four employees in an office; a fifth worker about to
enter the building saw one of the men and summoned police, Anderson
said.
   The employees, three women and a man, ran outside about 11 a.m.,
three hours after the ordeal began. One of the women appeared to be
crying.
   Police then fired tear gas into building and searched it for two
men but concluded they fled before the building was surrounded,
Anderson said.
   It was not immediately known if the gunmen stole anything.
   Anderson said he didn't know how the people escaped from the
office or whether they realized at that point that the gunmen had
apparently gone.
   The hostages were taken to a police station for further
interviews, police said.
</TEXT>
