<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Israel 1stLd-Writethru a0632 09-02 0753</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0632,0772</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>West Bank Commander Says Jewish Settlers Too Quick To Use Weapons</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: SUBS 2nd graf to CORRECT that Palestinians were wounded, sted
killed; UPDATES total to 10 wounded. Pick up 3rd pvs, `Brig.
Gen....' SUBS 11th pvs, `Two Palestinians...' with 5 grafs to
UPDATE with clashes. Pick up 12th pvs, `Ghasan Mustafa...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARY SEDOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The West Bank's top army commander chastised
Jewish settlers Friday for being too quick to use their weapons
after one settler accidentally wounded two soldiers.
   Palestinians and soldiers fought in the occupied West Bank and
Gaza Strip, and hospital officials said 10 Palestinians were
injured.
   Brig. Gen. Amram Mitzna warned the settlers in a 90-minute
closed-door meeting to obey army regulations on the firing of
weapons, Israel radio reported.
   Settler leaders contended Gedalia Becker was obeying army policy
when he opened fire Wednesday after a Palestinian demonstrator
threw a firebomb at his car on a West Bank road south of Bethlehem.
   Defense Minister Yitzhak Rabin recently gave Israeli soldiers
and civilians permission to shoot at firebomb throwers. But Mitzna
told the settlers they could open fire only to extricate themselves
from immediate danger, the Itim news agency said.
   Becker, a U.S. immigrant, was quoted as saying he acted on
instinct honed during service with the American army in Vietnam as
a combat helicopter pilot.
   ``In Vietnam I walked around with two pistols and a carbine.
Whoever thought twice in Vietnam died instantly. Whoever fired
survived,'' the Israeli Davar daily quoted him as saying.
   Police released Becker on bail Thursday after he was questioned
about the shooting.
   The gasoline bottle missed Becker's car and exploded on the road
behind it. Becker ran out of the car and opened fire at two figures
he spotted nearby, accidentally wounding two soldiers who were
chasing the assailant.
   Since Palestinians began an uprising against Israeli rule in the
West Bank and Gaza Strip on Dec. 8, 258 Palestinians have been
killed, most by Israeli gunfire. Four Israelis also have died.
Israel captured the territories in the 1967 Middle East war.
   Palestinians fought soldiers in three towns and refugee camps in
the occupied lands.
   Two Palestinians aged 17 and 18 were wounded by gunfire in a
Gaza Strip refugee camp after troops opened fire on stone-throwing
protesters, said an official at Shifa Hospital in Gaza City.
   Five other Palestinians, including two pregnant women and an
18-month-old child, were treated for tear gas inhalation after the
clash, said officials in Ahli Hospital in Gaza.
   A sixth victim was treated for a two-inch cut in his forehead
caused by the impact of a tear gas canister, the official said.
   The army confirmed one Palestinian was hit by a plastic bullet
in the camp after troops fired weapons in response to stonings by
protesters. The military had no other reports of injuries.
   Two other Palestinians were wounded in clashes in and near the
West Bank's largest city, Nablus.
   Ghasan Mustafa Ahmad Abed, 16, of Azzun village near Nablus,
suffered a gunshot wound in the right buttock, said an official at
Al Ittihad Hospital.
   Jihad Hamdam Badawi El Zara, 27, was hit by four bullet
fragments in the right leg during a separate clash, the official
said on condition of anonymity.
   Also Friday, the Supreme Court rejected an appeal by a sentry
who was sentenced to 18 months in jail for failing to prevent an
attack by a Palestinian guerrilla who rode a hang glider into
Israel and killed six soldiers in November.
   The Ministry of Education announced that Arabic would be a
compulsory subject for all Israeli junior high and high school
students this year.
   The Itim news agency said the requirement would fulfill the
army's need for Arabic speakers in the occupied territories.
   A Tel Aviv district court convicted two Israelis of plotting to
murder Arab workers in the nearby suburb of Or Yehuda, Israel radio
said.
   Benjamin Saada, 31, and Yaacov Batash, 21, were charged with
making firebombs out of beer bottles and planning to throw them at
a shack where Arab workers were sleeping on Aug 21. But they
panicked and hurled them into an Israeli backyard instead, the
radio said.
   Earlier in August, three Arabs were killed in an arson attack on
a shack where they were sleeping in Or Yehuda. The attack on the
Israeli backyard had been blamed on Arabs seeking revenge for the
burning deaths.
   Two other Israelis have been arrested in the Or Yehuda deaths.
</TEXT>
