<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Irish Bjt   09-02 0634</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Irish, Bjt,0653</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>IRA Brothers Buried; Riots in Belfast</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto staffing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BEN DOBBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOUGHMACRORY, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two brothers in the Irish
Republican Army, killed with a third man in a British army ambush,
were buried at their home village Friday in a peaceful ceremony
watched by 500 riot police.
   Before dawn, police in Belfast fired plastic bullets to disperse
rioters during a third night of violence in Roman Catholic areas.
No injuries were reported.
   The Rev. Peter Taggart, the Roman Catholic priest who conducted
the funeral Mass, spoke of ``disturbing questions'' about British
tactics in killing Gerard and Martin Harte, aged 29 and 21, and
Brian Mullin, 26.
   Police with riot shields and clubs swamped the tiny village 45
miles west of Belfast and flanked the cortege route, making the
country lane so narrow some mourners could barely squeeze through.
   Police said the Hartes and Mullin were well-known IRA men who
were armed and dressed for a violent mission when bullets riddled
their car Tuesday. Press reports said they were on their way to
kill an off-duty soldier.
   Mullin, who was Martin Harte's brother-in-law, will be buried
Saturday in nearby Dunmoyle.
   IRA supporters say the men could have been given a chance to
surrender. The government of the Irish Republic, although it also
has outlawed the IRA, expressed concern and the killings were
discussed at a Cabinet meeting Friday.
   Taggart told the congregation in St. Mary's Church the sanctity
of human life ``is binding on everyone, not just an ordinary
citizen but also on the government and those charged with the
administration of the law.''
   ``Some disturbing questions have been raised about the
circumstances in which these young men died,'' he said. ``It is
necessary to point out that the law of the land must obey the moral
law.''
   Authorities in the Protestant-dominated province appeared
determined to prevent the IRA from making the funeral a show of
anti-British strength. No incidents were reported and no guerrilla
paraphernalia was evident, apart from a beret and pair of gloves on
each coffin.
   An IRA statement distributed to news media said it had honored
the slain comrades Thursday night by firing a volley in the
Loughmacrory area.
   Black flags flew from all the telephone poles in the village and
``IRA the voice of an oppressed people'' was daubed on a wall.
   A military helicopter hovered low as the coffins, draped in
Irish flags, reached the graveyard. Its clatter nearly drowned the
eulogy delivered by Gerry Adams, president of the IRA's legal
political wing, Sinn Fein.
   Police say Gerard Harte commanded the mid-Tyrone IRA unit and
Martin Harte was responsible for choosing targets among police and
members of the locally recruited Ulster Defense Regiment.
   The IRA is fighting to drive the British from Northern Ireland
and unite it with the Irish Republic, which is 95 percent Catholic.
   It acknowledged the three men as members and said they died ``on
active service,'' by which it means during an operation, but has
given no details of the mission.
   So far this year, the IRA has lost 11 members and has killed 27
British soldiers, including eight with a bomb that blew up their
bus Aug. 20 not far from Loughmacrory.
   Britain responded to the increased attacks by saying new
measures would be taken, and the ambush was seen as the beginning
of a crackdown.
   Military officials also have adopted tighter security.
   Organizers of Sport Aid, a worldwide charity run scheduled for
Sept. 11, said the army withdrawn from an event in London's Hyde
Park, and the Defense Ministry explained: ``In the current security
climate, regretfully the army cannot participate.''
   Six British soldiers were killed June 15 by a bomb planted in
their van while they participated in a charity run in Northern
Ireland.
</TEXT>
