<FILEID>AP-NR-09-02-88 1638EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-AirShow     09-02 0609</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Air Show,0628</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Servicewoman, Son Identified Among 49 Air Show Victims</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GIRARD C. STEICHEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RAMSTEIN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A U.S. Army private and her
9-year-old son are the only Americans identified among the 49
killed when a jet crashed into the crowd at a U.S. base air show,
officials said Friday.
   More than 600 people attended three private memorial services
for the victims, who died after the jet collided with two other
fighter jets of the Italian air force precision flying team,
crashed and exploded.
   Two of the 49 killed Sunday at Ramstein Air Base remained
unidentified, according to police in nearby Kaiserslautern.
Fourteen children are among the 172 people still hospitalized,
officials said.
   But base spokeswoman Maj. Kathy White said three people remain
unidentified. There was no immediate explanation for the
discrepancy.
   She said the identified dead are 39 West Germans, the three
Italian pilots, the two Americans and one each from France and the
Netherlands.
   ``No more Americans have died that we know of,'' she said.
Earlier, officials said they believed six Americans were killed.
   Kaiserslautern police said 40 West Germans were among the dead.
One of the dead was a pregnant woman, said a police official who
spoke on condition of anonymity.
   Air Force officials identified the two Americans as Joshua
Frymyer and his mother, 36-year-old Army Pfc. Genevieve Riggs, who
was stationed in West Germany.
   Mrs. Riggs' husband, Army Sgt. Myron Riggs, was among seven
people evacuated to the United States this week for treatment of
burn injuries.
   Ms. White said the bodies of the mother and son were flown back
to the United States, but she did not know where they were being
taken.
   Juergen Dietzen, spokesman for Rhineland-Palatinate state where
Ramstein is located, said 14 children under age 14 are among the
172 people still hospitalized.
   He also said that 10 to 12 of the hospitalized victims were in
``life-threatening condition,'' but did not say if children were
among them.
   The unofficial U.S. Armed Forces newspaper Stars and Stripes
told of anguish and grieving as more than 600 people attended three
private memorial services Thursday night at Ramstein and in
Kaiserslautern.
   ``As a call went out for a moment of silent prayer heads bowed,
some shook as if in disbelief, some quivered from crying,'' the
newspaper said of one of the services.
   West Germans and Americans, including U.S. Air Force Europe
Commander Gen. William Kirk, attended the services, the paper said.
   It quoted Chaplain Col. Larry Kelly as saying at one service:
``We must rid ourselves of feeling guilty that we live while they
died. To survive such ... spiritual pain, we must cry, whether
privately or publicly, and vent our anger that our loved ones have
been taken from ourselves forever.''
   A public memorial service is set for Saturday at a church in
Ramstein. Top West German leaders and U.S. Ambassador Richard Burt
are scheduled to attend.
   In other developments:
   _ The Defense Ministry in Bonn said that on the same day as
Sunday's tragedy, West German air force officers went ahead with a
party after an air exhibition at another site in West Germany even
though they had been informed of what happened at Ramstein. Defense
Ministry spokesman Winfried Dunkel said the officers could face
disciplinary action.
   _ Werver Overbeck, chief surgeon at Kaiserslautern hospital,
angrily rejected allegations that victims with serious burns were
not taken to special treatment centers. ``Injured patients that
weren't treated in special burn centers had other kinds of injuries
such as broken bones, or they had burns that did not need to be
treated in special clinics,'' Overbeck said.
</TEXT>
