<1ST_LINE>u a PM-PolygamistSentencing 2ndLd-Writethru a0620 09-02 0406</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Polygamist Sentencing, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0620,0412</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Polygamist Clan Leader Sentenced For Church Bombing, Police
Standoff</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with background of case, comment from
prosecutor. No pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LAURIE SULLIVAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The leader of a polygamist clan was
sentenced to 15 years in prison today for bombing a Mormon chapel
and firing at federal agents during a 13-day standoff that ended
with the slaying of a corrections officer.
   Addam Swapp, 27, the first of four clan members to be sentenced
today by U.S. District Judge Bruce Jenkins, could have received 75
years in prison but instead was given the minimum allowed by law,
said his lawyer, John Bucher.
   Swapp's mother-in-law, clan matriarch Vickie Singer, 45, was
sentenced to five years in prison, also the minimum, for her role
in the bombing and standoff. She could have received up to 50 years.
   Swapp; Mrs. Singer; her son, John Timothy Singer; and Swapp's
brother, Jonathan, were convicted in May in the Jan. 16 bombing and
the subsequent standoff with 100 federal and state law officers.
   The stalemate at the clan's Marion farm ended in a shootout that
killed state Corrections Lt. Fred House. Assistant Attorney General
Creighton Horton said murder charges in House's death probably will
be filed Tuesday.
   Swapp admitted at trial that he bombed the Kamas Stake Center,
saying it was ordered by God as a sign of the impending collapse of
church, state and nation.
   He said the bombing also was intended to draw attention to the
1979 slaying of polygamist John Singer, Mrs. Singer's husband and
father of Swapp's wives.
   The family contends Singer was murdered in a ``church-state
conspiracy'' that began with his refusal to send his children to
public schools.
   Jenkins today told Swapp he was being sent to prison ``not for
what you say, not for what you believe _ for what you did.''
   ``There's no case I know of that more clearly shows the wisdom
of Congress in imposing minimum sentences than this one,'' said
U.S. Attorney Brent Ward, who said the government may file an
appeal for harsher penalties.
   The Swapp brothers and John Timothy Singer were found guilty of
attempted murder of FBI agents, resisting and assaulting agents and
firearms counts. Addam Swapp also was found guilty of explosives
offenses and damaging the church.
   Mrs. Singer was convicted of weapons and explosives charges and
assaulting and resisting agents.
</TEXT>
