<FILEID>AP-NR-09-02-88 1639EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-WasteShip     09-02 0311</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Waste Ship,0319</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Toxic Waste Ship to Return to Italy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A West German freighter carrying 2,100 tons of toxic
wastes will unload its cargo in Italy, government officials said
Friday.
   The ship, the Karin B, was denied permission to dock in Spain,
Britain, France, West Germany, the Netherlands and Belgium. The
wastes originally were shipped from Italy and dumped illegally in
Nigeria.
   Environment Minister Giorgio Ruffolo and Civil Defense Minister
Vito Lattanzio said after a Cabinet meeting that the wastes
probably will be unloaded at an unspecified Italian military port.
The ship is anchored in international waters off the coast of
France.
   The wastes may have come from as many as 10 European countries,
but they were shipped from Italy. Nigeria's military government
seized an Italian ship, the Piave, last July to bolster its demand
that Italy remove the wastes.
   The Karin B was the first of two ships sent to pick up the
wastes. It sailed from Nigeria on July 30. The second ship, The
Deep Sea Carrier, sailed from Nigeria on Aug. 15 and reportedly is
steaming off the coast of Portugal.
   The Cabinet announcement did not mention the second ship.
   Officials have said they don't know the precise chemical content
of the cargo. But on Wednesday, Robert Smeraldi, a spokesman for
the environmental group Friends of the Earth, said its lab
technicians in Nigeria found the drums contained PCBs and were
highly flammable.
   PCBs, or polycholorinated biphenyls, can cause cancer and burns
on contact.
   The plight of the Karin B is similar to that of the Zanoobia,
the Syrian freighter that was Italy's first so-called ship of
poison.
   It wandered the Mediterranean for four months with a cargo that
had once been dumped illegally in Venezuela. That ship was finally
given permission in June to unload its 12,000 drums of industrial
waste in Genoa.
</TEXT>
