<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Emperor     09-02 0190</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Emperor,0196</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Emperor Says He's in Good Health Despite Fever</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Emperor Hirohito took the unusual step Friday of
assuring reporters that he was in good health following a fever
earlier in the week that kept him in bed for two days.
   But Japanese reporters who attended the five-minute meeting with
the world's longest reigning monarch said he looked frail and his
cheeks were hollow.
   Hirohito, 87, underwent an intestinal bypass operation a year
ago, and since then has limited his official duties.
   ``I'm completely recovered, so please don't worry,'' the
newspaper Asahi Shimbun quoted him as telling reporters at the
imperial villa in Nasu, northeast of Tokyo, where he has been
vacationing with Empress Nagako.
   The emperor remained in bed Monday and Tuesday with a cold and
fever of about 99.5 degrees, an Imperial Household Agency official
said.
   ``He seems to be in good condition now,'' the official said,
speaking on condition of anonymity.
   In a rare negative description of the emperor's health by the
Japanese mass media, Kyodo News Service said he looked frail, his
shoulders were sloping and he spoke in a weak voice.
</TEXT>
