<FILEID>AP-NR-09-02-88 1504EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Dukakis-Sasso Bjt   09-02 0829</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dukakis-Sasso, Bjt,840</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Brings Back Former Aide, Who Promises Close Scrutiny Of
Bush</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis welcomed former top aide John
Sasso back to his presidential campaign Friday, nearly a year after
Dukakis declared that Sasso ``will not be back'' because of his
role in torpedoing Sen. Joseph Biden's bid for the Democratic
nomination.
   The return of Sasso as campaign vice chairman, announced jointly
by Dukakis in California and his senior advisers in Boston, was
widely seen as another signal that the Democratic nominee has
decided to mount a more aggressive campaign at a time when
Republican George Bush has pulled even in most polls.
   ``Almost a year ago, John Sasso made a very serious mistake,''
Dukakis reporters. ``He's paid the price.''
   Dukakis said he was rehiring his longtime political alter-ego
because he wanted to assemble ``the strongest team I possibly can''
for the final two months of the campaign.
   Dukakis said Sasso's return had nothing to do with his recent
decline in the polls.
   ``It's simply the fact we're looking at a little more than two
months of what is going to be a very tough, very competitive
campaign,'' Dukakis said. ``It's going to be a battle royal for the
presidency of the United States.''
   Bush chief of staff Craig Fuller said the rehiring of Sasso
``speaks for itself.'' GOP vice presidential nominee Dan Quayle,
campaigning in Alabama, said it was ``another sign that the Dukakis
campaign is in serious trouble.''
   Dukakis said Sasso's involvement in the Biden incident ``should
not obscure a long and well-deserved reputation for character and
for integrity.''
   In Boston, Sasso received a thunderous ovation from Dukakis
campaign and state government loyalists when he walked into a news
conference with campaign chairman Paul Brountas and Sasso's
replacement as campaign manager, Susan Estrich.
   Sasso directed Dukakis' gubernatorial comeback in 1982, served
as statehouse chief of staff and was architect of the nominee's
presidential campaign. He resigned in September 1987 admitting that
he circulated a videotape showing Biden using a British
politician's rhetoric without attribution.
   News accounts about that incident and charges of plagiarism
forced Biden to withdraw from the Democratic presidential contest.
   At first, Dukakis denied that his campaign staff was responsible
for the videotapes, but he later acknowledged that Sasso was behind
them. Sasso and political director Paul Tully, who helped Sasso
prepare the tapes, then resigned.
   ``What I did back on September was an error in judgment and I am
sorry that it hurt Sen. Biden and his family,'' Sasso said Friday.
   Sasso and Dukakis both spoke to Biden earlier Friday before his
return to the campaign was announced, aides said. Dukakis said
Biden ``could not have been more gracious.''
   Sasso dismissed suggestions that his return would give the Bush
campaign an excuse to accuse Dukakis of planning a ``sleaze''
campaign. That would be ``outrageous'' of the Bush people, he said.
``They certainly have a problem along those lines.''
   Although he apologized to Biden, Sasso said there was nothing
``unethical or illegal'' about distributing accurate videotapes
showing the similarity of speeches by Biden and British Labor Party
leader Neil Kinnock.
   Biden issued a statement saying he was glad Sasso had agreed
that the Delaware senator ``never meant to mislead anyone.'' Biden
said he still supports Dukakis for president.
   ``There are contrasts and weaknesses that are issues in this
campaign,'' said Sasso, who will take a leave of absence from his
job with an advertising firm. ``I will not shy away from pointing
those contrasts out.''
   That promise drew applause from campaign workers who have
complained that Dukakis and his top aides had not counter-attacked
vigorously enough when Bush misprepresented Dukakis' record.
   If nothing else, Sasso's return energized a campaign staff that
has been sobered in recent weeks by Bush's surge in the polls. Many
believe that Dukakis' failure to respond to the Republican
nominee's salvos has cost the Massachusetts governor the momentum _
and the lead in the polls _ that he took from the Democratic
National Convention.
   Sasso said spoke to Dukakis on Tuesday and was asked if he would
return. ``I said if he thought I could help, of course I'd do it,''
Sasso said.
   ``Now we've got all of our best players on the field,'' said
Dukakis issues adviser Thomas Herman.
   Brountas said he, Estrich and Sasso would report directly to
Dukakis and that other campaign staff would continue to report to
Estrich.
   Campaign aides insisted that the decision to rehire Sasso was
not a sign of dissatisfaction with Estrich's performance, although
several said her role in campaign strategy likely would be reduced
somewhat.
   She put the best light on the announcement.
   ``Today, a family is reunited,'' she said, introducing Sasso to
reporters. ``There's nothing more special, nothing more satisfying,
than reaching out to family. And to me, John Sasso is family.''
   Brountas said Sasso would bring ``additional strength, important
political insight and wisdom to a very strong campaign team.''
</TEXT>
