<1ST_LINE>r a AM-DanceBan     09-02 0324</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dance Ban,0332</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>`Dance Ban' Attorney Seeks Clarification</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA BRYSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SPRINGFIELD, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   School officials in a small southwestern
Missouri town need more guidance before they can respond to a
federal order striking down their ban on school-sponsored dancing,
according to their attorney.
   U.S. District Judge Russell Clark ruled last month that the ban
on dancing at Purdy High School was unconstitutional because it
promoted the values of those who oppose dancing for religious
reasons.
   The judge said it was not his role to order the district to hold
dances, but he said the district could not enforce a no-dance rule
that some believe to be a century old.
   ``Defendants respectfully submit that they do not understand
what the court is ordering them to do or refrain from doing,''
wrote school district attorney Ransom Ellis III in a brief filed
Thursday.
   But lawyer William Fleischaker, representing the 21 young people
and parents who challenged the ban, said ``there's no question in
my mind'' about the order.
   ``Any efforts by the school district to unreasonably prevent the
students from having a dance would be in contempt of that order,''
Fleischaker said.
   Fleischaker said Ellis' request for a clarification was
``typical of what's gone on all along here _ the school district
has abandoned responsibility. They said, `We can't allow dancing
because of the rule.' Now they're saying, `We don't know what we
have to do. Judge, you tell us what we have to do.' They've run for
school board, let them use some responsibility.''
   The Purdy school system, centered in a town of about 900 people
50 miles southwest of Springfield, has about 520 pupils.
   Clark did not address Ellis' arguments at a hearing Friday,
during which the judge considered the amount of attorney fees to be
awarded the pro-dance lawyers. The judge said he would make his
final ruling in the case by the end of next week.
</TEXT>
