<DOCNO> AP880902-0161 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-02-88 1734EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Boisjoly-Thiokol     09-02 0543</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Boisjoly-Thiokol,0559</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Dismisses Engineer's Suits Against Morton Thiokol</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT MIMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former engineer's $3 billion lawsuits
against rocket-maker Morton Thiokol, stemming from his warnings
against launching the ill-fated Challenger space shuttle mission,
were dismissed Friday by a judge.
   U.S. District Judge David K. Winder's decision came after more
than six months of deliberations on Morton Thiokol's motions to
dismiss the suits filed by Roger Boisjoly.
   Telephone calls to Boisjoly's Willard residence were answered by
a recording. He did not return messages.
   His attorney, Robert Levin, said from his office in Washington,
D.C., that a decision had not been made on whether to appeal
Winder's ruling to the 10th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in Denver.
   ``I obviously wish it was better news than we got,'' Levin said.
``(But) I haven't seen it yet, and I obviously can't comment on a
ruling I haven't seen.''
   Morton Thiokol officials were elated, said company spokesman Ed
Snow.
   ``The dismissal of these two suits completely vindicates Morton
Thiokol. We are very happy to have this situation behind us,'' he
said.
   In one of his suits, Boisjoly sought $1 billion for the deaths
of the seven astronauts killed when Challenger exploded on Jan. 28,
1986, and $1 million in compensatory damages for Boisjoly's own
health and career.
   Boisjoly _ who left Morton Thiokol in July 1986 citing physical
ailments and alleged mental torment _ claimed the aerospace company
impugned his professional reputation after he and other engineers
told a presidential commission investigating the disaster that they
had warned against the launch.
   The Rogers Commission found that a faulty seal in a joint in a
solid fuel booster rocket made by Morton Thiokol was to blame for
the explosion.
   Boisjoly and several other Morton Thiokol engineers had argued
the night before the launch that temperatures of 53 degrees below
Fahrenheit or less could result in failure of the seal.
   His other lawsuit, filed under the False Claims Act on behalf of
U.S. taxpayers, sought $2.075 billion and alleged that Morton
Thiokol knowingly provided NASA with defective rocket motors.
   But Winder ruled that ``the `conspiracy' alleged in the
complaint is not of a nature to support an action for damages on
the part of Boisjoly .... neither the conspiracy itself nor the
overt acts allegedly done in furtherance of it were directed toward
Boisjoly.''
   Boisjoly also alleged that Morton Thiokol's setting aside of his
recommendation against launching Challenger _ and, after the
accident, alleged attempts by the company to discredit him,
threaten his employment and its action removing him from the
disaster investigation _ left him ``severely injured in his
emotional and mental health.''
   Company lawyers argued that Boisjoly, who this year won the
Scientific Freedom and Responsibility Award from the American
Association for Advancement of Science, had based his contention
that he was defamed on office chatter.
   But Levin accused company officials of launching a deliberate
campaign to defame Boisjoly through pamphlets and interviews, ``not
coffee-shop stuff.''
   Winder dismissed most counts in Boisjoly's suits with prejudice,
meaning they cannot be refiled. However, he said he dismissed two
counts of Boisjoly's first civil suit, which deal with allegations
of defamation and conspiracy, without prejudice ``by agreement of
the parties.''
</TEXT>
