<1ST_LINE>r i AM-GulfTalks     09-02 0518</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gulf Talks,0533</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iran, Iraq Accuse Each Other of 74 Cease-fire Violations</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRENDA WATSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iran and Iraq accused each other Friday of
violating a two-week cease-fire more than 70 times, and a new U.N.
mediator sought ways to break a deadlock in talks aimed at ending
their eight-year war.
   The foreign ministers of Iran and Iraq met separately Friday
with Swedish diplomat Jan Eliasson. U.N. spokeswoman Therese
Gastaut said the talks were ``intensive'' but declined to provide
further details.
   U.N. Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar appointed
Eliasson mediator on Thursday.
   The foreign ministers, Ali Akbar Velayati of Iran and Tariq Aziz
of Iraq, have not met since Aug. 26, the second day of the talks.
Since then, the talks have continued at a lower, technical level.
They are to continue on Saturday.
   The talks have bogged down over follow-up procedures to the
cease-fire, which took effect Aug. 20. The problems involve the
withdrawal of troops and freedom of navigation in the Persian Gulf.
   After meeting with Eliasson, Velayati told reporters that
``after the establishment of the cease-fire, Iraq has had more than
60 kinds of violations of the terms of the cease-fire.''
   The Iranian diplomatic mission later released a list of what it
said were 74 violations of the cease-fire by Iraq as of Aug. 31,
which it said were reported to the U.N. secretary general.
   The list included alleged violations on every day of the
cease-fire except Aug. 28 and Aug. 31. It said there were nine
violations on the first day.
   The last entry said that on Aug. 30, Iraqi forces fired an
artillery shell in the Mehran area, about 100 miles east of
Baghdad, in the central front, killing four people.
   The official Iraqi News Agency also said it counted 74 reports
of cease-fire violations by Iran since the cease-fire.
   It said the Iranians aimed, ``through these violations, to
reorganize some of their military units, establishing observation
posts, firing flares and moving personnel-laden vehicles.''
   It repeated previous claims that Iranian gunfire was aimed at
Iraqi positions and that an Iraqi soldier was killed.
   In addition, Iranian forces ``attempted to approach the border
in various sectors, and reinforced their units in forward
positions, and redeployed in new areas,'' the agency said.
   Iran's commander and chief and Parliament speaker, Hashemi
Rafsanjani, said Iraq is trying to ``rekindle the flames of war''
by claiming sovereignty over the disputed Shatt-al-Arab waterway, a
major sticking point in the negotiations.
   A 1975 treaty split the waterway down the middle, but Iraq
claims the pact is void and has made ownership of the entire
waterway along the southern border a key issue at the peace talks.
   Tehran radio and the official Islamic Republic News Agency,
monitored in Cyprus, said Rafsanjani spoke at a prayer sermon at
Tehran University.
   ``We call on the armed forces to observe the cease-fire fully,
but if the enemy commits an offense, then it is only just that we
should answer him,'' he said. ``We should preserve our full
preparedness at the fronts until we arrive at a lasting peace.''
</TEXT>
