<1ST_LINE>u a BC-TropicalWeather     09-02 0263</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Tropical Weather,0270</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Hurricane Debby Forms</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD COLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Gulf weather system exploded Friday into
Hurricane Debby, the first hurricane of the season, and was bearing
down on the east coast of Mexico, National Hurricane Center
forecasters said.
   The Mexican government posted hurricane warnings from Punta
Jerez to Vera Cruz for Debby, which had winds of 75 mph, making it
a minimal hurricane, said forecaster Hal Gerrish.
   ``All precautions should be rushed to completion in what little
time remains before the center crosses the coast near Tuxpan in the
next several hours,'' Gerrish warned Friday afternoon.
   Heavy rains accumulating up to 10 inches can be expected over
parts of Mexico, and flash floods and mud slides may occur in the
area of the warning and inland Friday and Friday night, he said.
   Debby surprised forecasters, rapidly developing into a tropical
storm early Fridday and then into a hurricane by the afternoon,
Gerrish said. On Friday morning, forecasters had expected the storm
to fizzle out when it hit Mexico's coast.
   But an Air Force reconnaissance plane found that Debby was
gaining strength as it approached the coast.
   ``This is a small system and sometimes small systems can
strengthen rapidly in this area without much warning,'' Gerrish
explained.
   At 2:30 p.m. EDT, Debby was located 30 miles east of Tuxpan,
Mexico, moving west at 7 mph. The center was located at 20.8
degrees north latitude and 97.0 degrees west longitude.
   Debby was the fourth named storm of the 1988 Atlantic hurricane
season, and the first hurricane.
</TEXT>
