<1ST_LINE>r a AM-DroughtHay     09-02 0531</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Drought Hay,0549</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iowans Back Home After Making Hay In Idaho</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM SEERY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WINTERSET, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 60 Iowans returned home Friday
after 10 days in Idaho harvesting surplus hay to replace forage the
drought has cost them, and they were greeted by friends, relatives
and Gov. Terry Branstad.
   ``I just want you to know the people of Iowa appreciate what
you've done,'' Branstad told the workers. ``As you know, 1988 has
been a rough year, and we are proud of the way our farmers have
handled it. Sometimes the worst of times bring out the best in
people.''
   Residents brought out coffee and donuts to greet the 64 workers
when the buses rolled in at 7:20 a.m.
   The workers, all volunteers and including both farmers and
non-farmers, said they were tired but enjoyed the experience.
   ``There were long days and a lot of hard work but a lot of fun
to go with it,'' said Lane Schuldt, a livestock farmer from near
Van Wert.
   The buses also made other stops Friday morning in Bevington,
Osceola, Chariton and Albia.
   The Iowans boarded buses in those communities Aug. 21 and joined
volunteers from other Midwest states in harvesting more than 10,000
bales of hay. The hay came from set-aside land that was opened for
emergency harvesting by the U.S. Department of Agriculture in
response to the drought that stunted grass in Midwest fields.
   The hay will be distributed first to farmers who made the trip
or sent workers on the trip, said Bill Belden, Farm Bureau regional
manager in Monroe County, noting that some farmers could not leave
but instead hired workers to go to Idaho.
   Others high on the list for the hay are needy farmers who could
not make the trip because of age or health.
   ``Many Iowa livestock producers were faced with potential
liquidation of their herds. This hay will maybe held tide them
over,'' Branstad said.
   ``I need some hay,'' said Schuldt, who isn't sure how much he
will receive.
   Some of the workers are not farmers but took the trip anyway.
   ``I just wanted to help out,'' said Dave Pomeroy, who lives in
Pomeroy and holds a non-farm job in Webster City.
   ``It's been a lot of fun,'' he said. ``It was very nice. I'd
never been out there.''
   The project was coordinated by Farm Bureau officials in Iowa and
Idaho. They arranged free transportation by Greyhound buses and
free rail shipment of the hay by Burlington Northern. Food, lodging
and haying equipment in Idaho were donated by local businesses and
farmers.
   ``It's beautiful country out there, and I couldn't believe the
way the people treated us,'' said Schuldt.
   ``They were excellent people,'' Pomeroy said. ``We ate well all
the way.''
   The hay is not due to arrive for several days, so arrangements
must still be made to unload it from the train and haul it to
farms, and Belden said more volunteers are being sought for that
job.
   The governor said he called Idaho Gov. Cecil Andrus on Thursday
to express his thanks.
   ``Maybe the time will come when they'll need our help, and we
can reciprocate,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
