<FILEID>AP-NR-09-02-88 1819EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Solzhenitsyn     09-02 0510</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Solzhenitsyn,0523</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Expelled Author Invited to Join Memorial Committee for Stalin
Victims</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Alexander Solzhenitsyn, expelled in 1974 for
writing about the horrors of Josef Stalin's rule, was invited to
join an official committee building a monument to the dictator's
victims, an organizer said Friday.
   The move does not necessarily mean an easing in official
attitudes toward the dissident writer, but it is due to the number
of Soviet citizens who think Solzhenitsyn is one of the best
qualified people to serve on the committee, said organizer Yuri
Samadunov.
   The 1970 Nobel laureate's masterwork, ``The Gulag Archipelago,''
traces the history of political repression in the Soviet Union and
dwells at length on the purges and widespread repression that
marred the 29-year reign of Stalin.
   Solzhenitsyn, who spent eight years in labor camps under Stalin,
was expelled from the Soviet Union after the publication of the
``Gulag'' trilogy in the West. He now lives in Cavendish, Vt.
   Under Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev, Stalin and his legacy
have come in for increasingly severe criticism. In July, the ruling
Communist Party Politburo approved the building of a monument in
Moscow to Stalin victims.
   On Aug. 25, a public council to supervise the construction and
maintenance of the monument was formed, as well as an executive
committee to submit a blueprint for the memorial's design.
   Among those selected for the public council were Solzhenitsyn,
fellow dissident and Nobel Peace Prize laureate Andrei D. Sakharov,
poet Yevgeny Yevtushenko and Boris Yeltsin, the fiery former Moscow
party boss.
   Samadunov, a member of the executive committee, said the members
of the public council were chosen in street polls conducted at two
central Moscow locations, as well as from names submitted by
readers to Literaturnaya Gazeta, Ogonyok and other state-run
publications.
   ``We chose the first 17 people mentioned, and Solzhenitsyn was
among them,'' said Samadunov in a telephone interview. This week's
edition of Moscow News listed Solzhenitsyn as a member of the
public council charged with building the memorial.
   But Samadunov said the committee had not yet been able to notify
Solzhenitsyn that he had been selected for the committee, or to
determine whether he would agree to take part in its work.
   ``We sent him a telegram with news of his selection and that of
the others, and asked his agreement, but the telegram was returned
to us with a notice that it could not be delivered because the
address was not precise enough,'' said Samadunov.
   Solzhenitsyn's wife, Natalya, said through a family spokesman
that ``no telegram has been received,'' and that they will issue a
public statement if they get it. She declined to say whether
Solzhenitsyn would accept an invitation to serve on the committee.
   She previously has said the writer has no plans to visit the
Soviet Union. In June, the editor of the literary monthly Novy Mir
said he was negotiating for the right to print Solzhenitsyn's novel
``Cancer Ward,'' which would mark the first publication of a work
by Solzhenitsyn in his native land since he was expelled.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880902-0172 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-02-88 1539EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Bush     09-02 0646</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush,650</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Continues Fiery Attack On Dukakis Over Environment</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BELMAR, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican George Bush kept up his attack on
Democrat Michael Dukakis' environmental record, accusing the
Massachusetts governor of seeking to pollute the waters of New
Jersey where sewage has closed beaches.
   In fiery remarks, Bush stood on a sunny New Jersey beach and
told supporters he has one question for his Democratic opponent:
   ``Why did you pledge a clean ocean to the people of New Jersey
when your own state applied to pollute it?''
   Displaying the feisty campaign style he has recently adopted,
Bush shouted with disdain as he referred to a 1985 application from
Dukakis' as governor of Massachusetts to dump his state's waste in
an ocean dump site 106 miles off New Jersey.
   ``For almost two years, he fought to allow Boston's sludge to be
dumped off New Jersey's shore _ the very shore on which he had the
nerve to stand and promise clean water. Nice guy _ yeah,'' Bush
said sarcastically.
   He told the beach-clad crowd of supporters that if Dukakis comes
to their shores on another campaign trip, ``Be sure to ask him,
'Why did you want to dump Boston sludge off our coast in New
Jersey?'''
   A compromise allowed Massachusetts to dump further out beyond
the continental shelf.
   Bush was heckled by Dukakis supporters who chanted ``Where was
George?'' and carried signs ridiculing the Reagan adminisration's
Environmental Protection Agency as being weak.
   But the few hundred Bush supporters who had tickets to enter the
roped off beach section where he spoke, drowned out the protesters
with chants of ``We want George.''
   At one point a plane flew over pulling a banner with the words,
``Where was Teddy Kennedy?'' It was the Massachusetts senator one
who made the ``Where was George?'' line a Democratic rallying cry
in his speech at the party's convention this summer.
   Bush laughed when he saw the plane, saying, ``Where did that guy
come from?''
   Then he said, ``So I was home with Barbara. What's wrong with
that?''
   The remark appeared to be an oblique version to a quip making
the rounds of Republican circles that Bush was home, dry and in bed
with his wife, a pointed reference to the time Kennedy drove his
car off a bridge at Chappaquidick after a party and a young woman
passenger drowned.
   Bush told the crowd that ``nobody fools nature over the long
run.'' He said he would fight ``to ban ocean dumping forever,'' and
would ``make the enforcement of Superfund, the prosecution of
polluters, and the cleanup of toxic waste a top priority.''
   Bush was introduced by New Jersey Gov. Thomas Kean, and later
was met on a Delaware stop by Gov. Michael Castle and former Gov.
Pete du Pont, who sought the GOP presidential nomination earlier
this year.
   Bush wen to historical New Castle, Del., for another
environmental speech and a crabbling demonstration.
   In an interview with a group of outdoor reporters and editors
Bush, who has been saying, ``I am an environmentalist'' at every
campaign stop in recent days, said he was also a sportsman who has
fished and hunted for years.
   ``Anybody who loves these outdoor sports as much as I do has to
be concerned with clean water,'' he said.
   Bush avoided reporters' questions about Dukakis' decision to
re-hire John Sasso, a former campaign manager who quit last year
because he distributed a videotape that helped drive Delaware Sen.
Joseph Biden out of the Democratic presidential race.
   ``I haven't thought about it,'' Bush said at one point.
   But later, while bobbing around in boats in the Delaware River
for a crabbing demonstration, reporters shouted questions about
Sasso across the water.
   The vice president at first shook his head and then held up one
of the crabs in the boat, saying, ``Speaking of crabs.''
</TEXT>
