<2ND_LINE>AM-Flue-Cured Tobacco,130</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tobacco Crop Sales Exceed Expectations</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cigarette manufacturers collectively bought
377.2 million pounds of flue-cured tobacco last season, about 6
percent more than the companies had indicated they would purchase,
the Agriculture Department said Friday.
   Vern Neppl, acting administrator of the department's
Agricultural Stabilization and Conservation Service, said the
purchases covered the period from July 1, 1987, through June 30,
1988.
   Neppl said the companies had stated they planned to buy 355
million pounds during the marketing year. By law, companies are
penalized if they fail to purchase at least 90 percent of the
quantity they state as their intentions.
   Because crop marketings were below the 1987 effective quota for
flue-cured tobacco, the manufacturers needed to purchase only 83.1
percent of their intended quantity, Neppl said.
</TEXT>
