<1ST_LINE>r a AM-MissingInitial     09-02 0283</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Missing Initial,0292</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Kentucky Replaces Road Signs Missing Governor's Middle Initial</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COVINGTON, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Kentucky wants signs welcoming travelers
at all highway points of entry to be letter perfect.
   So it is replacing some that dropped the middle initial ``G''
from Gov. Wallace Wilkinson's name.
   Transportation Secretary Milo D. Bryant said failing to use the
``G'' _ for Glenn _ in the governor's name amounts to misspelling
the name.
   ``Obviously, it's not correct. That's not his name that he was
sworn in as governor,'' Bryant said.
   The error occurred earlier this year, Bryant said. He said an
alert supervisor noticed that workers were leaving out the ``G.''
The signs the department has made since the discovery bear the
initial.
   Bryant estimated only 10-12 signs are being changed, at a cost
of perhaps $44 for each. He was unsure of labor costs and other
expenses in the replacement project, but said it might be in the
$200 to $300 range.
   ``It was not a big deal,'' Bryant said.
   Richard Jones, who recently saw a crew of three men and two
trucks working to remove one of the signs on the Suspension Bridge
between Covington and Cincinnati, said he thought the action ``was
a waste of money.''
   ``I figure the money they used on that could have gone out here
to help the poor people on the street,'' said Jones, a 43-year-old
retiree from the Navy who rarely uses his middle initial _ ``H''
for Henry.
   Who ordered the change is unclear. Bryant said he wasn't sure.
He said he did not receive instructions from the governor or his
staff to change them.
   ``I doubt the governor even knows about it,'' he said.
</TEXT>
