<1ST_LINE>r w AM-BRF--SwineVaccine     09-02 0159</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Swine Vaccine,150</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Test of New Swine Vaccine Slated</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Kansas City, Mo., firm has been approved to
conduct a field test this fall of a genetically altered vaccine
designed to protect swine against pseudorabies, a contagious
disease that can be deadly to newborn pigs, the Agriculture
Department said Friday.
   The vaccine will be tested by Fermenta Animal Health Co., after
Oct. 1 on hog farms in Illinois, Iowa, Indiana, Minnesota and
Nebraska.
   James W. Glosser, administrator of the department's Animal and
Plant Health Inspection Service, said three previous pseudorabies
vaccines have been field tested and licensed for manufacture.
   As with the earlier tests, the Fermenta vaccine and testing
program has been reviewed and ``will pose no significant risks to
the environment,'' he said.
   Pseudorabies, also known as Aujesky's disease or mad itch, does
not affect humans, Glosser said.
   The National Pork Producers Council estimates that the disease
caused $36 million in losses last year.
