<1ST_LINE>r a AM-SchoolFood     09-02 0343</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-School Food,0351</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>School Lunch Director Charged With Stealing Food</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VERA HALLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The director of the school lunch program in
Hempstead allegedly stole hundreds of pounds of cheese and other
food donated by the federal government and used it at his cafe,
authorities said Friday.
   Samuel V. Eveleno, 56, of Greenlawn, was arrested on a federal
complaint following an investigation begun in April after an
inspector on a routine sanitation inspection is said to have
discovered 320 pounds of Agriculture Department food at Eveleno's
Long Island restaurant.
   The food included large commercial packages of American and
mozzarella cheese, raisins, vegetables, butter, honey, instant
mashed potatoes and refried beans.
   Eveleno, who was employed by a private food service company
under contract to the Hempstead School District to run its
cafeterias, owns the Backstage Cafe, a food concession at the East
Side Comedy Club in Huntington, according to the complaint.
   His duties as school lunch director included inventory and use
of food donated to the schools by the Agriculture Department under
its school lunch program, said U.S. Attorney Andrew Maloney of
Brooklyn, whose office is handling the case.
   While the complaint alleged wrongdoing only from April to
August, one of his cafe employees told investigators that Eveleno
had used 50 to 60 cases of USDA foodstuffs since August 1987 and
that he usually brought the commodities in every other week, the
complaint said.
   Some of the food at the Backstage Cafe still carried a label
that read, ``Donated by the United States Department of
Agriculture, For Food Help Programs, Not To Be Sold or Exchanged,''
Maloney said.
   A call to James Galloway, assistant school superintendent in
Hempstead, on Long Island, was not immediately returned.
   Eveleno is charged with theft of federally donated foods, which
carries a maximum sentence upon conviction of five years in prison
and a $250,000 fine.
   He was released on his own recognizance at his arraignment
before U.S. Magistrate Carol Amon. Neither Eveleno or his attorney,
Stephen Worth, would comment on the charges.
</TEXT>
