<1ST_LINE>r a AM-LifeBoats     09-02 0375</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Life Boats,0386</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>More MK-6 Rafts Fail Tests, Report Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Navy has found more MK-6 inflatable life
boats that failed to operate properly as the Pentagon continues to
investigate a West Virginia company that produced the rafts,
according to a published report.
   A Navy official who spoke on condition he not be identified
confirmed Friday that a small number of the 25-man rafts were
tested and that some had safety defects, which he did not identify.
   The spokesman, however, said he could not confirm a report in
The Pittsburgh Press that each life boat failed the testing.
   ``Indeed we have started testing the MK-6,'' he said. ``Some of
the safety problems ... have been found in the small number that
have been tested. I can't say each one'' had safety defects.
   The Navy is informing its fleet and is organizing an effort to
deal with the problems, the spokesman said.
   ``Our inspector general has been seriously involved with
concerns over the safety of the MK-6 and definitely is soliciting
inputs from all the involved agencies in the Navy,'' he said.
   The spokesman said each of those tested was produced by Rubber
Crafters Inc. of Grantsville, W.Va.
   The company's offices and factory were raided Aug. 8 by agents
of the Defense Criminal Investigative Service, the Federal Bureau
of Investigation and the Naval Investigative Service. The newspaper
reported at the time that the agents seized records but made no
arrests.
   Company officials declined comment.
   An affidavit filed in connection with a search warrant obtained
by the investigators claimed that Rubber Crafters supplied 63
defective MK-6 rafts to the Navy in 1986. The document claimed that
Rubber Crafters used inferior materials, falsified test results and
altered boat serial numbers in an effort to hide the defects.
   The investigators found four suspect rafts in Norfolk, Va., and
a small number of others were found during within the last two days
at Philadelphia and Mare Island, Calif., The Pittsburgh Press said.
   Rubber Crafters was paid more than $17 million and made nearly
2,150 MK-6 boats since 1984, when it won the supply contract from
B.F. Goodrich.
   The Navy has about 12,500 of the boats, which are stocked with
water, medical gear and other survival supplies.
</TEXT>
