<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Bush-Greeks     09-02 0525</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush-Greeks,500</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Campaign Tried to Recruit Greek Translator From Voice of
America</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUTH SINAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The George Bush campaign tried to hire an
employee of the Voice of America to translate statements by the
Republican nominee into Greek for Michael Dukakis' natural
constituency of Greek-American voters, according to agency
documents and personnel.
   The overture to an editor at the federally financed overseas
radio network prompted the VOA's general counsel to issue a
memorandum warning eployees against violating the 1939 Hatch Act,
which bars federal workers from taking part in partisan political
activities.
   VOA spokeswoman Judy Jamison said the agency's chief lawyer
``was prepared to recommend against'' accepting the Bush campaign's
job offer, but never did because the editor said he wasn't
interested in taking it.
   The employee, George Bistis, said in a memo that he received a
call Aug. 23 offering him an eight-week assignment translating
several texts of news about Bush or statements by him that were
intended for Greek-Americans.
   In the memo, a copy of which was obtained by The Associated
Press, Bistis said he told the caller, Eva Neterowicz, that
believed such an assignment would violate the Hatch Act.
   ``She answered that in her opinion there is no conflict because
the job offered involved translating services rather than engaging
in political activity,'' Bistis said.
   ``After all, she remarked, other people at VOA are working for
us and they don't seem to think that there is any conflict with the
Hatch Act,'' Bistis quoted her as saying.
   Ms. Neterowicz, chief of the nationalities department of the
Bush campaign, confirmed in an interview that she had tried to hire
VOA employees for part-time jobs providing translations for 26
ethnic groups, including Greek-Americans, at $50 per text.
   She said that ``we were told there was no problem'' with hiring
VOA personnel. But she said all her translators currently are from
private business and none is from the VOA.
   Bistis' supervisor, Andreas Antypas, deputy chief of VOA's
European division, wrote the congressional General Accounting
Office giving details of the incident and mentioning the case of
another employee from the VOA's Hungarian service who had performed
translations for the Bush campaign.
   ``I find it highly objectionable that any political organization
should feel free to fish around in the VOA for translators of
partisan political material,'' Antypas wrote.
   GAO official Paul Atkins said he relayed the Antypas memo to the
general counsel of the congressional watchdog agency.
   VOA spokeswoman Jamison said the agency receives dozens of
requests for translators because many of its employees are
multilingual. ``In this case, of course, it was different because
we're talking about a political campaign,'' she said.
   She said she did not know of any other agency employees who were
approached by the Bush campaign, but said a VOA engineer had asked
for a three-month leave to work for the Dukakis campaign.
   The VOA general counsel's memo said there may be ``very limited
and specific'' cases in which outside jobs associated with partisan
politics are permissible. But he said employees must receive his
written approval in advance before accepting them.
</TEXT>
