<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Labor-McLaughlin     09-02 0501</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Labor-McLaughlin,0516</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Labor Secretary: Economy Good Despite Unemployment Rise</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Unemployment Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK PERKISS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The American work force is in its best shape
ever, despite a drop in manufacturing jobs and a dramatic slowdown
in service industry hiring, Labor Secretary Ann McLaughlin said
Friday.
   ``Employment is still at record levels and that's good,'' Ms.
McLaughlin said in the second State of the Workforce address,
delivered before the Chicago Federation of Labor. Her predecessor,
William Brock, gave the first such address in Philadelphia last
year.
   ``The state of the work force in 1988 is good and getting better
_ the best it has ever been. But it isn't as good as it can be,''
she said.
   ``If workers, managers, government and unions can cooperate ...
we can offer a job to everyone in this country who wants one _
provided they're educated, skilled and prepared for the
workplace,'' Ms. McLaughlin said.
   The key labor issue is no longer unemployment, it's the
unemployable, she said. ``In the future, more than ever before, the
unemployed will be the underskilled,'' she said.
   Ms. McLaughlin's speech followed the Labor Department's release
Friday of unemployment figures for August, which showed the
nation's jobless rate rose to 5.6 percent last month.
   It was the second straight monthly increase. The July rate of
5.4 percent was 0.1 higher than June's 5.3 percent, a 14-year low.
   Ms. McLaughlin said the jobless rate had been fluctuating
between 5.3 percent and 5.6 percent since March.
   She praised the Reagan administration for creating 17 million
new jobs in the past five years and called for efforts to educate
and train workers with and without jobs.
   ``The day must never come when we have a worker deficit in this
country because we've failed as a nation to provide opportunities
for excellence and relevance in education, training and
retraining,'' she said.
   Ms. McLaughlin left out attacks on the Democratic Party in a
departure from her prepared text, which contained a reference to
Democrats in Congress who in 1982 tried to pass what she called ``a
costly public jobs program'' with a $3.5 million price tag.
   She also did not mention Democratic presidential candidate
Michael Dukakis by name, referring to him only as ``the other
candidate'' in acknowledging his endorsement last week by the
AFL-CIO, an endorsement supported by the Chicago federation.
   But Ms. McLaughlin criticized the Massachusetts governor as
``not terribly economically astute and literate'' at a news
conference after her speech.
   In 1983, she said Massachusetts lost 45,000 manufacturing jobs
while 1 million jobs were created nationwide.
   The Labor Department reported the goods-producing side of the
economy lost jobs in August for the first time since last January.
Employment in manufacturing was down by 5,000 after a 70,000 jump
in July.
   Susan Estrich, Dukakis's campaign manager, said from Boston that
the loss of those jobs was a ``blow to hopes for prosperity in the
nation's heartland (and) to hopes of easing the squeeze on working
Americans.''
</TEXT>
