<1ST_LINE>r a AM-WritersGuild-NLRB     09-02 0292</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Writers Guild-NLRB,0298</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>NLRB Files Complaint Against Writers Guild</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The National Labor Relations Board has filed
a complaint seeking to invalidate Writers Guild of America rules
that limit members' ability to quit the union during a strike.
   ``It's like an indictment. We are a prosecutor alleging a
violation of the law,'' said Sidney Rosen, a regional NLRB officer.
   The unfair labor practices complaint, filed Thursday, supports
an action filed by 21 dissident members of the WGA during the
guild's 154-day strike against movie and television producers. The
strike, one of the longest in entertainment industry history, ended
last month.
   The dissidents and the NLRB argue that the guild's constitution
illegally allows the union to fine writers for working during a
strike even if the writers resign from the union before going back
to work.
   The complaint called for a Nov. 3 hearing before an
administrative law judge in Los Angeles, and could eventually lead
to a hearing before the labor board in Washington.
   WGA officers said they hadn't been served with the complaint. In
a statement, however, the guild said it expects to prevail in the
lawsuit before the NLRB ``or on appeal to the federal courts, if
necessary.'' The guild also argued that the issue is moot now that
the strike is over.
   Lionel Chetwynd, one of the 21 writers who signed the original
complaint, said a guild official recently urged the dissidents to
drop their complaint. But he disputed the notion that the complaint
is hurting the guild.
   ``Clearly, there are deep problems with the guild. You could
look at this as a first step in clearing away the debris, and
getting our constitution in line with the law of the land,''
Chetwynd said Thursday.
</TEXT>
