<1ST_LINE>r a AM-FakeMemo     09-02 0306</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Fake Memo,0313</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fake California Trooper Memo Alarms Police In Miami</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A California Highway Patrol make-believe training
memo about Sandinista terrorists waging war on law enforcement
officers made it into the hands of Metro-Dade police, who took it
very seriously.
   So seriously that Metro-Dade's intelligence unit issued a memo
of their own, in which they warned officers to be wary of a feared
Nicaraguan gang, suspected in the March shooting death of Miami
police Officer Victor Estefan.
   ``The attached memorandum from the California Highway Patrol
infers that members fo the Sandinista National Liberation Front ...
will utilize deadly force against law enforcement officers who come
in contact with them,'' the Aug. 11 Metro-Dade memo said.
   ``Due to the large population of Nicaraguans in Dade County, the
probability of contact with these subjects is great,'' said the
memo, which was read to all members of the force at roll call.
   Oops, California Highway Patrol Sgt. Joe Farrow said Thursday
when told the creative training memo made it to Miami.
   ``This was not intended to go nationwide and scare people over
the Sandinistas,'' Farrow said. ``It's a training bulletin for our
guys. That's all it is.''
   Farrow didn't know how it ended up at Metro-Dade police or why
they were taking it seriously. He called the Miami version of the
memo, 11 paragraphs, a ``cut-and-paste job.'' Someone deleted the
cover page _ which was plainly marked _ ``Training Bulletin.''
   The bulletin mentioned the death Estefan on March 30 after a
traffic stop in Little Havana, a Cuban neighborhood in Miami.
California troopers arrested two Nicaraguan brothers during an
April 27 shoot-out near San Luis Obispo. The brothers, from Miami,
are suspects in Estefan's slaying, though they have not been
charged.
   Police do not believe the suspects to be involved in any
organized terrorist group.
  
</TEXT>
