<FILEID>AP-NR-09-02-88 1812EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Corn-Soviets     09-02 0361</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Corn-Soviets,360</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>800,000-Ton Corn Sale Reported</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union has bought an additional
800,000 metric tons of U.S. corn for delivery during the 1988-89
marketing year that began Thursday, the Agriculture Department said
Friday.
   Sale of 100,000 tons of corn was announced a day earlier, also
for delivery in 1988-89.
   A metric ton is about 2,205 pounds and is equal to 39.4 bushels
of corn or 36.7 bushels of wheat or soybeans. The 900,000 tons of
corn would be about 35.5 million bushels.
   Corn prices have been averaging about $2.49 per bushel at the
farm level, meaning that the two sales could have a farm value of
around $88.4 million.
   There was no indication whether the new sales of corn would
count under the current long-term grain supply agreement between
the two countries or be carried forward separately in case a new
pact is forthcoming.
   The current five-year pact is set to expire Sept. 30 and
negotiators are currently trying to work out a new one, or at least
an extension of the current agreement, to take effect Oct. 1.
   Arthur K. Homann of the department's Foreign Agricultural
Service said it would be determined later how to count the latest
corn sales, depending on the actual shipping dates and whether
there is a new agreement.
   Regardless, the Soviet Union has already lived up to terms of
the final year of the agreement, which calls for the annual
purchase of at least 9 million tons of U.S. grain.
   According to the agreement, the annual purchases are supposed to
include a minimum of 4 million tons each of wheat and corn. The
Soviets have the option of buying the remaining 1 million tons as
wheat, corn or soybeans, with every ton of beans counting as two
tons of grain _ up to a maximum of 1 million tons of grain
equivalent.
   Prior to this week's sales, the Soviet Union had purchased 9.05
million tons of wheat and 5.17 million tons of corn for delivery in
the fifth year of the agreement, plus 830,000 tons of soybeans and
1.3 million tons of soybean meal.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
