<HEAD>Contras Agree to Continue Truce</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Contras released a letter to the Sandinistas on
Friday agreeing to continue the Nicaraguan truce past its formal
Aug. 31 expiration date.
   The Sandinistas had previously announced they would not initiate
any action against the Contra rebels, although both sides have
accused each other of violating the truce.
   Only four of the Contras' seven directors signed their letter,
dated Thursday and addressed to Victor Tinoco, deputy secretary of
the Sandinista foreign ministry.
   Contra spokesman Jorge Rosales said the other three directors _
including hard-line military leader Enrique Bermudez _ were out of
town.
   The truce was originally declared earlier this year to permit
peace talks between the two sides. But the Contras have refused
further meetings inside Nicaragua, as the Sandinistas wanted, and
the talks are at a standstill.
