<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Spain-Drugs 1stLd-Writethru a0595 09-02 0239</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Spain-Drugs, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0595,0240</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Seize Seven Tons of Hashish; Arrest 14</HEAD>
<HEAD>Updates with nationalities, but not names, of suspects given and
other details, changes throughout</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BENIDORM, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police seized seven tons of hashish in
the Barcelona port Friday and broke an international smuggling ring
by arresting 14 people, including an American, at Beniform down the
Mediterranean coast, police said.
   It was Spain's second-largest hashish seizure, according to
police and the civil governors of Alicante and Barcelona.
   Police said authorities in Barcelona removed the hashish from a
ship container, then put the container under surveillance and
police followed two men who took it south to Benidorm by truck.
   Virginio Fuentes, provincial governor of Alicante, said 12
Britons, an American and a Norwegian were arrested but he did not
give their names.
   Ferran Cardenal, civil governor of Barcelona, said the drugs
arrived Aug. 18 from Pakistan and the ring intended to distribute
most of it in Britain. He said the hashish was from Afghanistan.
   Cardenal said the ringleader was believed to be Louis King, a
34-year-old Briton, but police had not finished determining the
identities of those arrested.
   The largest hashish seizure in Spain occurred July 24 when
police uncovered 17 tons in a specially built vault on a cove near
Lloret del Mar, north of Barcelona. Six people were arrested.
   Spain has become a major entry point to Western Europe for
hashish traffickers.
</TEXT>
