<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Airplane-Deer     09-02 0183</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Airplane-Deer,0191</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Plane Hits, Kills Two Deer While Taxiing For Takeoff</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TRENTON, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Eastern Express plane had to abort its
takeoff when it hit and killed two deer that bounded out of the
woods adjacent to a runway, an official said Friday.
   Neither the pilot nor the co-pilot of the twin-engine Beechcraft
turboprop was injured in Thursday night's incident at the Hancock
County Regional Airport, said airline spokesman Steve Mason.
   No passengers were aboard the 19-seat plane, which was bound for
its home base in Portland.
   As the plane went down the runway, one deer hit the plane's
propeller and a second hit the nose of the plane, Mason said.
   ``The deer just came so quickly and they (bounded) out of
nowhere,'' he said.
   The impact disabled the plane, which slid along its nose for
``some distance'' before coming to a stop, Mason said.
   Damage to the landing gear, propellers and front end was
``substantial,'' he said, adding that the plane was undergoing
repairs Friday.
   Mason said a deer was killed in a similar fashion a few years
ago.
</TEXT>
