<FILEID>AP-NR-09-02-88 2239EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Pope-Women     09-02 0327</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pope-Women,0336</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pope Tells U.S. Bishops Church Committed To Helping Women</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VATICAN CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pope John Paul II told a group of U.S.
bishops Friday that the Roman Catholic church is determined to help
fight discrimination against women and his own document on women's
dignity will be released soon.
   Receiving 22 bishops from the West and Southwest, the pope noted
the American bishops have prepared a draft of a pastoral letter on
women and he praised them for ``rightly striving to help eliminate
discrimination based on sex.''
   ``Throughout the whole church a great prayerful reflection still
remains to be made on the teaching of the church about women and
about their dignity and vocation,'' the pope said.
   John Paul's document is expected to be released after he returns
from a trip to Africa later this month.
   ``The church is determined to place her full teaching, with all
the power with which divine truth is invested, at the service of
the cause of women in the modern world _ to help clarify their
correlative rights and duties, while defending their feminine
dignity and vocation,'' the pontiff said.
   ``The importance of true Christian feminism is so great that
every effort must be made to present the principles on which this
cause is based, and according to which it can be effectively
defended and promoted for the good of all humanity.''
   The draft of the U.S. pastoral letter, titled ``Partners in the
Mystery of Redemption, A Pastoral Response to Women's Concerns For
Church and Society,'' was issued in April.
   A final draft is expected to be presented to the full body of
U.S. bishops in November 1989 and, if approved, would become part
of their teachings.
   The pope also urged the bishops, at the Vatican for a periodic
visit, to defend the family, in particular from drug trafficking
and pornography.
   ``Both of these plague society, debase human life and human love
and violate human rights,'' John Paul said.
</TEXT>
