<FILEID>AP-NR-09-02-88 2150EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Indians-Hostages     09-02 0434</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Indians-Hostages,0444</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mother Begs For Safe Return of Suspect in Newspaper Hostage-Taking</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MEG REYNOLDS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DURHAM, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A sobbing mother warned U.S. marshals Friday
not to harm her son, who remained a fugitive three days after a
federal court ordered him returned to jail on hostage-taking
charges.
   Eddie Hatcher, 30, an American Indian, is accused with Timothy
Jacobs, 20, of taking up to 20 people hostage Feb. 1 at the offices
of The Robesonian newspaper in Lumberton, in what they said was a
protest of alleged corruption and discrimination against minorities
by Robeson County law enforcement officials.
   The siege ended after 10 hours when Gov. Jim Martin agreed to
form a state task force to investigate their allegations.
   Hatcher failed to surrender at the U.S. Marshal's office in
Raleigh when his bond was revoked Wednesday, and a federal arrest
warrant was issued Thursday, said Chief Deputy Dwight Rich. Jacobs
surrendered Wednesday.
   ``If anything happens to my son, I will hold the federal
government responsible,'' Hatcher's mother, Thelma Clark, said at a
news conference outside a hospital where she underwent back surgery
this week.
   Mrs. Clark said her son had followed the terms of his $100,000
bond before it was revoked. ``He kept all the rules they gave
him,'' she said. ``He is not a criminal.''
   Hatcher and Jacobs spent five months in jail before a
three-judge panel of the 4th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals ruled in
June they had not been given a bond hearing soon enough after their
arrest.
   Hatcher and Jacobs were denied bond twice by a U.S. magistrate
and once by a U.S. District Court judge. They were ordered back
into custody when the entire appeals court agreed to reconsider the
case at the request of Assistant U.S. Attorney John Bruce, who
challenged the terms of their release.
   A lawyer representing Hatcher said Friday he has asked to have
the federal warrant revoked because it was issued without a hearing
and prosecutors had not demonstrated that Hatcher posed a danger to
the community while free on bond.
   ``He lived where he was supposed to, honored his curfew and
travel restrictions, reported religiously to the probation office
(and) submitted to urinalysis,'' attorney Barry Nakell said at a
news conference in Carrboro, near Chapel Hill.
   Nakell refused to comment on whether he had spoken with Hatcher
since the arrest warrant was issued or knew of his whereabouts.
   But he said he was confident Hatcher would show up for his
scheduled Sept. 19 trial ``if he is alive and well. He was very
anxious for this trial.''
</TEXT>
