<FILEID>AP-NR-09-02-88 1845EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Haiti-Rights     09-02 0423</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Haiti-Rights,0436</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Human Rights Group Ends Visit; Report Says Arrested Man Slain By
Soldiers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL NORTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   PORT-AU-PRINCE, Haiti (AP) _ A radio station on Friday said
soldiers fatally beat an employee of state-run television while he
was being held at an army compound because of a debt to an officer.
   Also on Friday an independent team probing allegations of human
rights abuses in Haiti concluded its visit.
   Radio Soleil said Schubert Baptiste, 30, a messenger employed by
Televison Nationale, was beaten to death during his detention at
the Dessalines Barracks. That is the headquarters of Haiti's most
feared army unit.
   Radio Soleil, a station operated by the Roman Catholic church,
quoted Baptiste's wife as saying Baptiste was arrested Aug. 20 for
failing to repay a $1,000 debt to an army officer that the report
identified only as Lt. Metellus.
   The station did not say when Baptiste died. The Press Federation
on Friday protested the death.
   Meanwhile, a five-member team from the Organization of American
States Commission on Human Rights ended a five-day trip after
visiting six detention centers, including the Dessalines Barracks.
   The group also gathered information on the slaying of human
rights activist Lafontant Joseph who was found stabbed to death in
his car on July 11.
   Haiti has been under the military rule of Lt. Gen. Henri Namphy
since June 19 after he ousted civilian President Leslie Manigat.
   ``We were disappointed not to have met with Lt. Gen. Namphy,''
team member Christina Serna told The Associated Press. ``After all,
he has proclaimed himself the champion of human rights.''
   The delegation visited several other towns ``to gather
information on human rights violations in those regions,''
according to an OAS communique that said the group met with several
ministers of Namphy's all-military cabinet.
   Members of the team arrived Sunday night and are to report to
the next session of the OAS General Assembly on Nov. 14.
   It was the first mission by an OAS team to Haiti since January
1987, when Namphy led a provisional government set up after
President Jean-Claude Duvalier fled to France on Feb. 7, 1986,
ending a 29-year family dictatorship.
   Namphy relinquished power on the second anniversary of
Duvalier's flight, but returned in a bloodless coup that ousted
Manigat. More than a dozen Manigat followers were held for several
weeks without charges.
   A day after seizing power, Namphy declared himself president and
abolished the legislature. A month later he suspended the
constitution, which 99 percent of Haitian voters approved in a
March 1987 referendum.
</TEXT>
