<FILEID>AP-NR-09-02-88 2054EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Yugoslavia-Strike     09-02 0161</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Yugoslavia-Strike,0164</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Miners Strike for Higher Pay in Yugoslavia</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 1,200 miners went on strike
higher pay and the dismissal of the mine manager, whom they accused
of corruption, the official news agency Tanjug said Friday.
   It said the strike at the Krupanj antimony mine, 90 miles
southwest of Belgrade, began Thursday after workers asked for their
July pay, which had been withheld for lack of funds.
   Tanjug said average monthly pay at the mine is $80 but did not
say how much more the men were demanding. It gave no details of the
accusations against the manager.
   Striking miners sent a 140-member delegation to the headquarters
of state-run unions in Belgrade to press their case, the agency
said.
   Labor unrest has grown in Yugoslavia in recent years because of
a decline in living standards resulting from austerity measures
imposed in an attempt to revive the faltering economy and deal with
a $21 billion foreign debt.
</TEXT>
