<1ST_LINE>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     09-02 0409</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0419</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Texas Coast Drenched As Hurricane Debby Moves Toward Mexico</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Showers and thunderstorms pelted the coast of Texas on Friday as
Hurricane Debby moved across the Gulf of Mexico toward the east
coast of Mexico.
   Over 3 inches of rain fell in Galveston, Texas, on Friday
morning.
   Showers and thunderstorms also continued from southwest Kansas
through western Oklahoma into west-central Texas.
   A fire station in Odessa, Texas, measured over 6} inches of rain
since Thursday evening. More than 3} inches of rain fell at Big
Spring, Texas.
   Other showers and thunderstorms were scattered from southern
lower Michigan and northwest Ohio through central Indiana and
southern Illinois into northwest Arkansas. Showers and
thunderstorms also spread from the southern Atlantic coast to the
Gulf coast.
   Rainfall during the six hours ending at 2 p.m. EDT included over
1{ inches at Cape Girardeau, Mo.; nearly 1\ inches at Apalachicola,
Fla.; and over an inch at the Naval Air Station at New Orleans.
   Temperatures Friday afternoon were in the 70s or 80s across much
of the nation. Readings were in the 60s as cooler air came in
behind a front in the northern Plains. Temperatures were also in
the 60s because of clouds and rain from the southern Rockies into
southwest Kansas and the Texas Panhandle.
   Temperatures were in the mid-90s over the northern valleys of
California. Temperatures ranged from the mid-90s to 105 degrees in
the desert Southwest.
   The nation's low Friday was 33 degrees at Lake Yellowstone, Wyo.
Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 55 degrees
at Crescent City, Calif., to 105 degrees at Palm Springs, Calif.
   The forecast for Saturday called for showers and thunderstorms
along a cold front from the eastern Great Lakes through the Ohio
Valley into Arkansas and northeast Texas. Showers and thunderstorms
were expected from the southern Atlantic states through the Gulf
coast region and much of Texas.
   Near record heat was expected once again over inland areas of
the Pacific Northwest with high temperatures from the mid-90s to
105 degrees. High temperatures were expected in the 80s or 90s
across much of the nation, but in the 70s from the northern third
of the Mississippi Valley through the Great Lakes and the Ohio
Valley and in the upper 60s over northeast Minnesota, northwest
Wisconsin and western Upper Michigan. Highs were forecast between
100 and 110 degrees from the California valleys into the desert
Southwest.
</TEXT>
