<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Brazil 1stLd-Writethru a0611 09-02 0574</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brazil, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0611,0592</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New Brazilian Constitution A Mixture of Nationalism And Liberalism</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Inserts 1 graf after 4th pvs: The lawmakers completed... with
no further action needed for adoption.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SUSANA HAYWARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRASILIA, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lawmakers early Friday finished work on
a new constitution that replaces the authoritarian charter drawn up
two decades ago by military generals.
   The new constitution failed to make major social or economic
changes, such as land reform and curbing the role of the military,
but it legalizes strikes, abolishes censorship, strengthens
Indians' rights and environmental laws, and lowers the voting age.
   ``Brazil is a new country. This constitution will protect the
weak and punish those who abuse power,'' the constituent assembly's
speaker Ulysses Guimaraes said.
   The lawmakers completed the document shortly before 2 a.m. They
had begun work in February 1987, two years after civilian rule
returned to Brazil after 23 years under the military.
   No further action is required for adoption of the constitution.
The document has been sent to proofreaders and it will become
effective Sept. 23.
   The 245-article constitution covers nearly every aspect of daily
life: interest rates, education, health, divorce, Indians' rights,
strikes and minimum wages.
   A first draft had reduced the military's role to basic keepers
of the peace, but rumblings from the still-powerful,
behind-the-scenes generals promoted the armed forces to
``defenders'' against foreign or national threats. The nationwide
Democratic Ruralist Union lobbied hard against land reform. Its
leader, powerful landowner and chiropractor Ronaldo Caiado,
convinced thousands of farmers and rural workers that the
constitution would expropriate ``productive land.''
   Bowing to pressure, legislators excluded productive land from
land reform, unless it produces marijuana.
   In a country where farms are the size of nations and 4 percent
of the 143 million people own more than half the fertile land, very
little land is expected to go to Brazil's 12 million landless
peasants under the constitution.
   President Jose Sarney, who came to power in 1985 in an indirect
electoral college election, ardently fought against a parliamentary
system of government and won a five-year term in office instead of
four. Brazilians haven't voted for president since 1960 and most
polls showed they wanted Sarney, a provincial politician closely
linked to the military, out of office this year.
   Brazilians will vote for a new leader in November 1989.
   New envirnonmental laws are aimed at protecting Brazil's Amazon
rainforest, randomly burned by the landless and speculators.
Indians also gained new rights, including ``exclusive'' use of
their land and resources.
   The constitution also:
   _ Lowers the voting age from 18 to 16 years of age. The only
other country where 16 year olds can vote is Nicaragua.
   _ Legalizes strikes for all workers. Before, ``essential''
sectors of the labor force were not allowed to strike.
   _ Nationalizes mineral mining and gives foreign companies four
years to hand over control to a Brazilian resident.
   _ Bans new oil risk contracts.
   _ Abolishes censorship of films, books and television.
   _ Abolishes the decree law, a powerful tool used by the
president to bypass Congress and push through legislation.
   _ Gives women 120-day maternity leaves and men five-day
paternity leaves.
   The question Brazilians now must wrestle with is how to
implement the constitution in a country with rampant corruption,
runaway inflation and vast economic and social inequality.
   In 1993, Brazilians will vote on whether they prefer a monarch,
prime minister or president to run the country.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880902-0214 </DOCNO>
