<1ST_LINE>u a AM-PolygamistSentencings 1stLd-Writethru a0721 09-02 0767</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Polygamist Sentencings, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0721,0782</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge's Sentences of Polygamist Clan Members Draw Prosecutor Ire</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 10 grafs to UPDATE with final sentencings,
prosecutor comments, picking up 9th graf pvs, `State murder ....'</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto SK1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURIE SULLIVAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge Friday sentenced four polygamist
clan members to minimum prison terms, enraging prosecutors who said
the penalties for a church bombing and fatal police standoff were
too lenient and possibly illegal.
   Chief U.S. District Judge Bruce Jenkins, amid repeated
criticisms of federal mandatory sentencing standards governing
bombings and firearms, said he had no choice but to order prison
terms of 15 years for clan ringleader Addam Swapp and five years
for his mother-in-law, Vickie Singer.
   ``The sentence imposed is not for what you say, not for what you
believe, but for what you did,'' Jenkins told Swapp, who was
seriously wounded in the Jan. 28 shootout with FBI agents that
ended one of Utah's most bizarre church-state confrontations. A
state corrections officer was killed.
   Swapp's brother, Jonathan Swapp, and Mrs. Singer's son, John
Timothy Singer, both 21, each received mandatory 10-year sentences
for a pair of firearms charges and five years' probation for two
other counts. Prosecutors said the maximum penalty for the four
counts was 45 years.
   They said Addam Swapp could have been imprisoned for 75 years
and Mrs. Singer for 50 years for their parts in the Jan. 16 bombing
of a Mormon chapel in Marion and a 13-day siege of their rural
stronghold by 100 officers.
   ``I think once again that everyone involved in this whole
process continues to wonder why it ever occurred,'' Jenkins told
Mrs. Singer, 45, who tearfully implored the judge to free her.
   Jenkins said mandatory sentencing laws imposed by Congress
``illustrate a crisis of the whole sentencing process ... whether
we judge without knowing anything about the case as a matter of
social policy.''
   The sentences and Jenkins' criticisms of Congress infuriated
U.S. Attorney Brent Ward. He said prosecutors planned to appeal the
sentences as illegal since Jenkins simply declined to impose
penalties on some counts and rendered less-than-minimum terms on
others.
   ``I've heard stronger sentencing comments in a drunk-driving
case,'' Ward said, adding he had never been involved in a case
where the sentence was ``given with apologies to the defendant and
criticism of the Congress.''
   ``There's no case I know of that more clearly shows the wisdom
of Congress in imposing minimum sentences,'' Ward said.
   State murder charges in the shooting death of state Corrections
Lt. Fred House, killed in the shootout, were expected to be filed
Tuesday against an unspecified number of the 15-member clan that
included nine children under age 18.
   Swapp said the bombing was ordered by God as a sign of the
impending collapse of the Mormon Church and all government, and
that it would trigger the return of family patriarch John Singer,
slain by police nine years before for resisting arrest. The clan
maintained Singer was killed in a church-state conspiracy and that
the family had been harassed for years by police and neighbors.
   ``I have to call the state of Utah and the United States to
repentance. If they do not repent, they will be destroyed,'' Addam
Swapp, 27, said in court Friday.
   He and the judge discussed the Constitution, the defendant
likening the bombing to the Boston Tea Party. Jenkins ended the
exchange by noting Swapp's intelligence and devotion to his two
wives, Mrs. Singer's daughters, and their six children.
   Jenkins said the case had troubled him. ``It always seemed to me
that this whole episode was an unnecessary episode. If one had
sought redress in appropriate, peaceful ways, there would have been
a forum,'' he said.
   Mrs. Singer, 45, made a plea for mercy saying she didn't want to
be separated from her children.
   The judge said he could not overlook her culpability. ``Mrs.
Singer has to look within herself and recognize that these are
consequences of her own doing, no one else's,'' he said.
   The four clan members were convicted by a federal jury in May of
20 of 23 counts following 13 days of testimony by some 67 witnesses.
   On the eve of his sentencing, Addam Swapp said in a telephone
interview with the Associated Press that God would intervene.
   ``We're going to be delivered. We have received the promise that
we aren't going to prison. To actually say that I will not go into
prison, I really don't know. I do know whatever time they give me,
I'm not going to serve it,'' Swapp said.
</TEXT>
