<FILEID>AP-NR-09-02-88 2019EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-YonkersDeseg 3rdLd-Writethru a0747 09-02 0919</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Yonkers Deseg, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0747,0943</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Heavy Fines Reimposed on Yonkers; $192,000 Due Tuesday</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 12th graf, `Possible action ...,' with 1 graf to UPDATE
with Cuomo saying he will direct control board to order service
reductions; INSERTS 2 grafs after 14th graf, `Cuomo said ...,' with
governor saying he won't immediately begin proceedings to remove
councilmen.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARLENE AIG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge Friday reimposed potentially
bankrupting fines against Yonkers for defying a court-ordered
housing desegregation plan, then unsuccessfully tried to reach a
settlement in informal discussions.
   U.S. District Judge Leonard Sand, who found the city guilty of
racially segregating housing for 40 years, reinstated the fines
which were upheld by the U.S. Supreme Court on Thursday night.
   Sand said the Supreme Court decision ``does not alleviate in any
way, indeed one might agree it intensifies, the fiscal crisis that
confronts the city of Yonkers.''
   He added that although the nation's highest court blocked fines
and jail terms for four defiant city councilmen ``they (the
councilmen) still have a responsibility to the citizens they
represent who will bear the brunt of these fines.''
   Because Monday, Labor Day, is a court holiday, Sand ordered the
city to pay $192,000 on Tuesday. As previously promised by Sand,
more than $85,000 of the money due will be earmarked for Yonkers
public schools and to guarantee the payment of interest on city
bonds. The balance of the $192,000 will go to the U.S. Treasury and
is non-refundable.
   Sand then called on lawyers for all parties to immediately meet
with him privately ``to explore informally some ideas we have for a
possible solution of this crisis.'' The talks ended after about an
hour.
   ``It was not successful,'' Mayor Nicholas Wasicsko told
reporters.
   Michael Sussman, attorney for the National Association for the
Advancement of Colored People, said there was no progress and
called it a ``hostile discussion.''
   ``I haven't changed my position. I will do what I have to do,''
said Henry Spallone, one of the councilman opposed to the
desegregation plan.
   On Aug. 1, the council voted 4-3 against incentives to build 800
units of middle-income housing throughout the city as part of the
desegregation plan ordered by Sand.
   The fine had started at $100 on Aug. 2 and doubled daily until
it was stopped after a week pending appeals. The city has paid
$12,700 and was to resume paying at $12,800 on Friday until the
fine reaches $1 million a day and stays there, growing in
million-dollar jumps.
   Gov. Mario Cuomo said he would direct the city's Emergency
Financial Control Board on Tuesday to begin making the substantial
reductions in city spending and services that will be required by
Sand's order.
   The control board, which assumed management of Yonkers' finances
Aug. 9, passed a resolution the same day saying it would seek the
criminal charges against the four councilmen if the fines were
reinstated. The charges stem from violating the control board act _
a state law _ by jeopardizing the city's fiscal condition.
   Cuomo said last week he would initiate removal proceedings
against the four councilmen if the fines were reimposed.
   However, Cuomo spokesman Gary Fryer said Friday that for the
time being, the governor would not attempt to oust the recalcitrant
councilmen.
   The high court's ruling was ``raising more questions about
removal than already existed and there were already many
questions,'' Fryer said.
   The Supreme Court ruled late Thursday night to stay a lower
court ruling that upheld contempt citations against the four
councilmen, who had been paying $500-a-day fines and would have
been subject to imprisonment this weekend.
   The court ``has granted the stay for the four council members''
until they have had time to ask the court formally to fully review
their cases, U.S. Supreme Court spokeswoman Toni House said
Thursday night.
   ``The application so far as the city of Yonkers is concerned has
been denied,'' she said.
   Even with the $1 million daily fine cap, Yonkers, the state's
fourth-largest city with a population of 200,000 people just north
of New York City, would be bankrupt by November, officials said.
   House said the entire court considered the applications, and
Justices Thurgood Marshall and William Brennan filed a 12-page
dissent.
   ``As the city repeatedly points out in its application, `Yonkers
is relatively unique in that most of the governmental power in the
city is centralized in the legislative branch.' For this reason the
city IS the council,'' Marshall wrote in arguing that all the stays
be denied.
   Wasicsko, who favors complying with Sand's housing desegregation
order, said the decision troubled him.
   ``The treasury of the city is going to be exposed and the
taxpayers of the city are going to feel the burden,'' he said.
``One thing it denies is the political martyrdom of the councilmen.
They were slated to go to jail on Sunday. Their personal fines have
ceased. But the city is going to plummet to bankruptcy. So their
onus is their duty to the city.''
   Two of the four, Nicholas Longo and Vice Mayor Henry Spallone,
called the decision a ``great victory.''
   But Councilman Peter Chema, another of the four, called the
decision ``a big personal victory, but I have serious concerns
about the city.''
   ``It's kind of like being administered oxygen while someone
strangles you,'' said Chema.
   ``The relief becomes moot if he decides to bankrupt the city in
the interim,'' Longo said.
   The fourth councilman, Edward Fagan, called the decision
``unexpected'' and declined to comment further.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
