<1ST_LINE>r i AM-US-Paraguay     09-02 0376</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Paraguay,0385</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Human Rights Advocate Finishes Term as US Ambassdaor</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PEDRO SERVIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ASUNCION, Paraguay (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Ambassador Clyde Taylor on Friday
finished his three-year assignment here during which he was accused
of meddling in Paragay's internal affairs and was once tear-gassed
at a garden party.
   Before boarding the plane, Taylor acknowleged having contacts
with people and organizations Gen. Alfredo Stroessner's government
considers subversive, but added: ``We never aligned ourselves with
any group.''
   He said the goal of U.S. policy is ``that Paraguay continue
being a stable country. ... Thinking of the future, five or 20
years after Stroessner, is to think of a transition with someone
who knows how to promote development and democracy and justice,
without violence.''
   Stroessner, 75, seized power in 1954 and has ruled this
landlocked South American nation since with the support of the army
and the Colorado party.
   Taylor's replacement, Timothy Towell, is to arrive next week in
Asuncion.
   The departing ambassador told foreign reporters: ``When I got
here, it was taboo to talk of anyone replacing the president. Now,
everything has changed. President Stroessner, like all of us, is a
little older and I see it as a good step that he himself talks
about his succession.''
   Relations between Taylor and the general's authoritarian
government became uneasy soon after the ambassador arrived in
November 1985. The 50-year-old career diplomat, whose parents were
Calvinist missionaries, traveled through the country advocating
human rights and meeting with opposition groups.
   He pressed for the reopening of ABC Color, Paraguay's biggest
newspaper, which was closed in 1984 for printing articles the
government considered subversive.
   Taylor also had asked the government to track down the source of
a signal that jammed broadcasts by Radio Nanduti, the country's
most popular station before it was forced off the air.
   Allegations about his conduct ranged from interfering in
domestic politics to conspiracy and subversion. Interior Minister
Sabino Montanaro said last year Taylor was close to being declared
``persona non grata.''
   Police fired tear gas at a garden party given in his honor in
February 1987, but Taylor continued to press for human rights and
speak his mind _ including a hint in February 1988 that government
officials might be involved in drug trafficking.
</TEXT>
