<1ST_LINE>u a AM-BirthControlSentence     09-02 0381</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Birth Control Sentence,0388</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Lifts Probation Term Requiring Birth Control</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BURT GOODMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge Friday reversed her order that a teen-age
mother who left her two sons alone in a sweltering apartment for
three days, practice birth control throughout her child-bearing
years, saying it was unenforceable.
   Maricopa County Superior Court Judge Lindsay Budzyn had
sentenced Debra Ann Forster on May 24 to lifetime probation with
the birth-control stipulation.
   At a hearing earlier in the week, Ms. Budzyn refused to revoke
the probation even though she learned that Mrs. Forster, 18, is
pregnant with her fourth child. She said Mrs. Forster's pregnancy
didn't mean that the court's orders had been ignored, since no
method of birth control is foolproof.
   Mrs. Forster pleaded guilty in April to two counts of attempted
child abuse stemming from a May 1987 incident in which she left her
two sons, William, 1{, and Scott, 6 months, alone in a Mesa
apartment for three days. Authorities said the apartment had no air
conditioning, and both babies were dehydrated and near death when
found.
   The judge said at Forster's sentencing that the birth control
stipulation was the only way to make sure Mrs. Forster did not have
other children to abuse.
   Ms. Budzyn's ruling Friday came on motions filed by defense
attorney Garrett Simpson, Mrs. Forster's public defender, and
attorney Colin F. Campbell, representing the Arizona Civil
Liberties Union, to modify the terms of probation by deleting the
birth-control requirement.
   Campbell argued that the order was invasive, amounted to cruel
and unusual punishment and violated freedom of religion for Mrs.
Forster, a Roman Catholic.
   In her ruling Friday, Ms. Budzyn wrote the birth-control
requirement was being lifted because of ``its inability to be
enforced.''
   Instead, the judge ordered that Mrs. Forster undergo urinalysis
testing for drugs every two weeks; enroll in a comprehensive
counseling program including individual counseling and classes in
parenting skills, prenatal care and birth control; receive marriage
counseling; and have a complete assessment of her medical condition
at the time of the delivery of her child.
   While awaiting trial this year, Mrs. Forster gave up the rights
to her sons and a daughter who was born in jail. According to court
records, all three have been adopted.
</TEXT>
