<1ST_LINE>u a AM-GatorHunt 1stLd-Writethru a0637 09-02 0611</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gator Hunt, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0637,0629</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>First Day of Hunt Provides Victories, Defeats</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 1 graf after 2nd graf, `The first ...,' with number
of alligators taken the first night.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos MH1, MH3</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRIAN MURPHY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CLEWISTON, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Most alligator hunters were disappointed
after the first day of Florida's month-long gator season, but by
Friday morning some lucky ones bagged animals as long as nine feet.
   Thursday at sunset marked the beginning of the first legal
alligator hunt in 26 years for the lucky _ or not-so-lucky _ 230
people granted permits to catch the reptiles with harpoons, nooses,
crossbows and almost anything but a gun.
   The first night of the 30-day hunt netted about 130 alligators
in 28 designated hunting areas across the state, according to the
Florida Game and Fresh Water Fish Commission. Thirty-eight were
bagged in the Everglades, while 36 were taken in the Lake
Okeechobee area, a spokesman said.
   Two novice hunters, David and Jerry Navin, snaked through a Dade
County canal in the darkness looking for the red-reflecting eyes
that give away the swimming reptiles, but the gators refused to
cooperate.
   ``There's a few here, but they're not really doing what they're
supposed to,'' chuckled David Navin. ``They're a little tougher
than we thought.''
   His brother Jerry called their experience ``on-the-job
training.''
   To the north on Lake Okeechobee, one of the designated hunting
areas, some gator pursuers reported better luck.
   Thomas Alpern, 25, of Brooklyn, N.Y., the only northerner
receiving a permit, bagged a nine-footer despite worrying
beforehand that he might be unable to kill the animal even when he
captured it.
   With gator hides selling for $42 a foot and meat running up to
$6 a pound, Alpern and others persevered, though few expected to
bag their 15-gator limit the first night.
   Hide and meat sales from a single alligator can total $300 to
$500.
   ``We're having fun,'' said Bud Wolfe, an alligator hunter from
Oakland Park. ``Where else but in Africa can you go after a
500-pound animal that can kill you?''
   Early success came to Carlos Donate of Miami and his guide, Jay
Medore of Clewiston. They snagged a 8-foot-3-inch animal only 80
minutes after they started hunting on Lake Okeechobee.
   Once they got the gator reeled up to the side of the boat, they
shot it with a ``bang stick,'' a firearm-like gadget that is
allowed under the game commission rules.
   ``We blew one hell of a hole in his head,'' Donate said. ``It
was exciting.''
   He then taped the gator's mouth shut.
   ``It's scary putting that tape on his mouth, even with a hole in
his head,'' he said.
   Doug Mackie and Steve Prater, who work for the city of Pembroke
Pines' utilities department, bagged a 6-foot alligator and another
that was 8 feet or longer.
   Prater showed how he hooked one just beside the alligator's left
rear leg with a large hook on a heavy-duty saltwater fishing rod.
He said fighting the gator when it was hooked was very difficult,
and he snapped the heavy fiberglass rod.
   ``It was a deep-sea rod and it just plain snapped in two,'' he
marveled.
   Alligator hunting was outlawed in Florida in 1962 because
wildlife biologists feared overhunting of the ancient reptiles
might threaten the survival of the alligator.
   A small alligator industry has built up in recent years because
alligators have increasingly become problems by turning up in urban
areas and pestering and occasionally killing humans or their pets.
   Estimates place the current number of alligators living in
Florida at 1 million, and game commission officials said they are
now far from an ``endangered'' species.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880902-0223 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-02-88 2130EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Iraq-Kurds 1stLd-Writethru   09-02 0701</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Iraq-Kurds, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0667,0722</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Kurdish Rebels Say 1,300 Civilians Slaughtered</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 4 grafs to UPDATE with new Amnesty International
report; picks up 3rd graf pvs: `The reports...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By NEIL MacFARQUHAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A spokesman for Kurdish rebels fighting
Iraqi government troops said Friday the Iraqi army slaughtered
about 1,300 unarmed men, women and children this week.
   Kurdish refugees in a camp in Turkey said they fled on foot from
Iraqi chemical bomb attacks that killed about 500 people in their
group.
   In London, the human rights group Amnesty International said
Friday that Iraq had used chemical weapons in a military campaign
against Kurdish villages that has left hundreds of civilians dead.
   The London-based group accused Iraq of a ``systematic and
deliberate policy'' of killing Kurds.
   The reports were among many recent accusations of Iraqi
atrocities against Kurds, who are fighting for an independent
homeland in northern Iraq.
   The Iraqi News Agency quoted an ``official source'' as denying
chemical weapons were used in northern Iraq. The source identified
the Kurds who are fleeing into Turkey and Iran as ``traitors'' who
collaborated with the Iranian ``invaders'' during the eight-year
Persian Gulf war.
   Iraq launched a major offensive against the rebels after
accepting a U.N.-sponsored cease-fire in the war last month.
   Both the Turkish and Iranian governments have reported the
arrival of thousands of Kurds. In Turkey, Premier Turgut Ozal said
Thursday that 60,000 refugees had arrived since the country opened
its borders two weeks ago.
   The official of the Kurdish Democratic Party told The Associated
Press in a telephone interview that soldiers arrested the victims
in the Dahuk region in northwestern Iraq, killed them, then buried
them in mass graves Sunday.
   He also said the Iraqi military was holding back 43,000 people
trying to flee the region.
   The report could not be independently confirmed. The spokesman,
based in a West European capital, has given information to the AP
on several other occasions. He declined to give his name for
security reasons.
   Iraq's 3.5 million Kurds have been waging their separatist
struggle on and off for 50 years.
   Iran has supported the Kurdish rebels in their fight against
Iraq. The rebels estimated Wednesday that 60,000 troops backed by
fighter-bombers and helicopter gunships were fighting them.
   One of the refugees in Turkey, 64-year-old Salih Zaid, said
three bombs fell near his group them as they prepared to leave
their village.
   ``I fainted, and when I came to I saw that my daughter and two
sons were dead,'' he said.
   Zaid said he was partially blinded by gas with a garlic-like
smell that he claimed was mustard gas. The United Nations has said
that Iraq has in the past used mustard gas, which is
distinguishable by its garlic-like smell.
   The refugees, most of them from Zakho and Duhok townships in
northern Iraq, said they walked north for three days to reach the
Turkish border after the Iraqi army launched an offensive, heavily
bombing their settlements in the last week of August.
   ``We were under constant bombardment all during our trek. About
500 people from our original group of 10,000 died before reaching
the Turkish border,'' said Aziz Taha, 25, a university student who
was in his hometown, Duhok, when the Iraqi assault started.
   In other reports, the Iranian government-run Islamic Republic
News Agency quoted Kurdish refugees in Iran as saying their
villages were destroyed by Iraqi forces.
   ``My house has been set on fire three times ...,'' IRNA quoted
Iraqi villager Hakim Refaq, 42, as saying.
   The party spokesman said fighting between the Kurdish rebels and
the Iraqi army was escalating. The army used chemical weapons to
attack three villages in the Amadiyah area Wednesday and Thursday,
he said.
   ``We call upon the United Nations and the international
community to intervene and stop this war of genocide against our
people,'' he said.
   On Friday, U.N. spokeswoman Nadia Younes said in New York that
Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar had received cables from
Kurdish groups and that U.N. officials were studying them.
   About 20 million Kurds live in the mountains where the borders
of Turkey, Iran and Iraq meet. Syria and the Soviet Union also have
small Kurdish enclaves.
</TEXT>
