<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Dukakis 1stLd-Writethru a0709 09-02 0631</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dukakis, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0709,600</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Jibes at Bush on Education, Quayle on Drug War</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: To update with continuing attacks on Quayle, inserts graf 11,
bgng ``In Spokane,'' also 2 new grafs at end with more on Spokane
visit and new quote on Sasso</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DONALD M. ROTHBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic nominee Michael Dukakis jibed
at both men on the Republican ticket Friday, labeling George Bush a
dropout on education and ridiculing the idea of Dan Quayle leading
the war against drugs.
   Speaking to an enthusiastic, flag-waving crowd, Dukakis asked,
``Is there anybody here today, is there any citizen in the United
States of America, who thinks that Dan Quayle is qualified to be
the nation's drug czar?''
   The crowd of 2,000 to 3,000 people in a public park erupted in
hoots and cheers.
   Dressed in shirtsleeves on a bright, sunny day in which the
temperature headed toward 100 degrees, the Massachusetts governor
noted that Bush had said he was going to put his vice president in
charge of the war against drugs.
   ``Ronald Reagan tried that and it failed,'' Dukakis said.
   He also stressed the schools issue, a recurring theme of his
speeches during a pre-Labor Day campaign swing up the West Coast.
   ``The future will depend, above all, on the quality of education
we provide,'' Dukakis said.
   He accused the Reagan administration of seeking to cut funds for
remedial programs and teacher training while he had worked to
bolster such programs in Massachusetts.
   Then he asked what Bush, who says he wants to be known as the
``education president,'' was doing at the time.
   ``I guess he just dropped out,'' Dukakis said.
   In Spokane, Wash., Dukakis kept up his attack on Quayle, saying
at a rally at a steelworkers' union hall: ``Isn't it nice to have a
Democratic nominee for vice president whose qualifications have
never been questioned by anybody?''
   The Portland crowd, which included some anti-abortion
demonstrators, was one of the most enthusiastic to greet Dukakis
during the campaign, and he had little trouble drawing partisan
responses to his punch lines.
   Several times the crowd picked up the chant, first heard at the
Democratic convention in Atlanta, of ``Where was George?'' _ a
reference to Democratic claims that Bush tried to dissociate
himself from such controversial Reagan administration activities as
arms sales to Iran.
   The crowd also loudly booed a reference to President Reagan's
Star Wars plan for a space-based missile defense system.
   In another cut at Quayle, Dukakis said that in a Democratic
administration, ``we're going to have a vice president who's been a
leader in the United States Senate.''
   In contrast to Quayle, a 41-year-old senator from Indiana,
Dukakis' running mate, Lloyd Bentsen of Texas, is one of the
Senate's senior members.
   Dukakis appeared in Portland only hours after announcing that
John Sasso, forced to resign a year ago as campaign manager, would
return with the title of vice chairman.
   Sasso left the campaign on Sept. 30 because of his involvement
in distribution of a videotape demonstrating that Sen. Joseph Biden
of Delaware, a Dukakis rival for the Democratic nomination, had
incorporated language by a British politician in his own speeches
without giving credit.
   Dukakis was introduced at the rally by Oregon Gov. Neil
Goldschmidt, who said Dukakis ``has set the standard for every
governor in the country.''
   As for the Republican nominee, Goldschmidt said, ``With George
Bush, what you see is all that you get.''
   In Spokane, Dukakis toured a Kaiser Aluminium Co. plant and gave
his standard ``good-jobs-at-good-wages'' stump speech at the union
hall.
   Later, at the airport, asked again about Sasso's return, Dukakis
replied: ``He is a very talented person. ... John didn't do
anything that was illegal or dishonest. It was a mistake in
judgment.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
