<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BRF--HolidayTraffic     09-02 0104</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Holiday Traffic,0106</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Safety Council: At Least 420 Traffic Deaths Estimated</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The three-day Labor Day weekend that began Friday
could result in 420 to 520 deaths on the nation's roadways, the
National Safety Council said.
   Last year, 441 people died during the Labor Day weekend. The
highest toll for the holiday was recorded in 1968, when 688 people
were killed.
   Safety Council statisticians said 410 traffic deaths could be
expected during a non-holiday three-day weekend at this time of the
year.
   For counting purposes, the holiday began at 6 p.m. local time
Friday and ends at midnight local time Monday.
</TEXT>
