<1ST_LINE>r a AM-NavyDeath 1stLd-Writethru a0670 09-02 0629</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Navy Death, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0670,0641</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mirecki Family: Trial Proved Recruit's Rights Denied</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 14th graf, `A motion ...,' with 1 graf to UPDATE with
motion to dismiss denied and panel seated.
^By BILL KACZOR</NOTE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PENSACOLA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Navy officer's court-martial in the
drowning of a rescue-swimmer recruit proved that the recruit's
rights were violated, regardless of the innocent verdict, the
victim's family said Friday.
   A panel of four officers late Thursday found Lt. Thomas A.
Torchia, former officer in charge of the Navy Rescue Swimmer
School, innocent on two dereliction-of-duty charges after a
seven-day trial.
   Torchia was in charge of the school at Pensacola Naval Air
station on March 2 when Airman Recruit Lee Mirecki, 19, of
Appleton, Wis., died in a training pool after suffering a
fear-induced heart attack.
   Witnesses testified that instructors threw Mirecki into the pool
and that one held his head under water after the panic-stricken
recruit climbed out and shouted that he wanted to ``D-O-R,'' or
drop on request, Navy jargon for quitting the voluntary training.
   ``My brother's rights to DOR were totally violated without a
doubt,'' said his sister, Lynn Johansen, of Appleton. ``The law was
broken according to the Uniform Code of Military Justice. That
comes out loud and clear.''
   Mrs. Johansen and her husband, Larry, sat through most of the
trial. Mirecki's mother, Elaine Kitowski, of Manitowish Waters,
Wis., and her husband, Mel Kitowski, also attended.
   ``It is a very stressful thing for our family to be here,'' Mrs.
Johansen said. ``The verdict is not the most important thing for
us.''
   Most important, she said, is finding out how her brother died.
Family members declined to express an opinion on the verdict, but
said they were satisfied with the prosecution of the case, led by
Lt. Cmdr. Larry Wynne.
   Mrs. Kitowski said she believed the court-martial panel thought
the defendant's ignorance of what the instructors were doing to her
son was insufficent reason ``to make him a criminal.''
   Torchia testified he was on the telephone in his office
overlooking the pool but neither heard nor saw anything to indicate
something was wrong. If present, he said, he would have stopped the
instructors.
   Torchia, 32, of Princeton, Ill., said he intended to continue
his Navy career as an aviation maintenance officer.
   Mirecki's family is staying in Pensacola for the court-martial
of a second defendant, Petty Officer 2nd Class Michael W. Combe,
28, of Tempe, Ariz.
   Combe, an instructor, is charged with involuntary manslaughter,
battery and conspiracy to commit battery charges. He is accused of
holding Mirecki's head under water.
   A five-member panel of officers was seated Friday night to hear
the case, beginning Tuesday. Also, a motion to dismiss the charges
was denied by the military judge who has handled both trials. Cmdr.
Newell D. Krogmann made a similar ruling in the Torchia case.
   Defense lawyer W.H.F. Wiltshire of Pensacola argued that Vice
Adm. N.R. Thunman, chief of naval education and training, was
unqualified to convene the court-martial because there was an
appearance he had a personal interest in the outcome of the case.
   He contended Thunman's interest stemmed from the adverse
attention his command has received as a result of the death.
   Wynne argued against the motion, saying that extending
Wiltshire's theory up the chain of command would prohibit anyone,
including the chief of naval operations, from convening a
court-martial in such a high-visibility case.
   Thunman testified Wednesday that he had wanted to correct what
he said were erroneous press reports that the Navy failed to begin
investigating the case until receiving outside pressure from the
victim's family, their congressman and the media.
   He also was concerned about initial reports released by Navy
spokesman who incorrectly said the death was from natural causes.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880902-0230 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-02-88 2246EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Peru-Economy 1stLd-Writethru a0733 09-02 0349</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Peru-Economy, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0733,0358</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Peruvian President Picks New Ministers as Economy Falters</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 10 grafs to UPDATE with five new ministers
appointed, pick up graf 5 pvs: Manufacturing has...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LIMA, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Alan Garcia appointed a new economy
minister and also changed four other Cabinet posts, the government
said Friday, in the struggle to combat inflation.
   The National Statistics Institute said Friday that consumer
prices increased 243 percent from January through August, the
biggest such rise in Peruvian history.
   The Cabinet shakeup was the fourth in the three-year-old Garcia
government.
   Energy Minister Abel Salinas was appointed late Thursday to
replace Economy Minister Cesar Robles, who resigned, according to
the official gazette El Peruano.
   Jorge Carrasco, a congressional deputy and president of the
Chamber of Deputies' Energy Commission, was named to head the
Energy Ministry, according to the report.
   Late Friday, Garcia named Justice Minister Camilo Carrillo to
head the Transportation Ministry, replacing Francisco Maury, who
resigned, and Sen. Cesar Delgado was named justice minister.
   Ivan Garcia, president of the state steel company Sider Peru,
was appointed to replace industry minister Guillermo Arteaga who
left the Cabinet.
   Garcia, head of the center-left Aprista Party, said other posts
in the 15-member Cabinet would not be changed.
   The five ministers were sworn in to their posts late Friday,
according to the government.
   Robles was the third economy minister in Garcia's government and
served only three months.
   Manufacturing has continued to decline and shortages of basic
consumer goods are widespread. The 39.9 percent cost of living
increase in July was the highest one-month total in Peruvian
history.
   The National Statistics Institute said in a statement published
in Friday's gazette that prices increased 21.7 percent in August
over July and the total for the year so far was 243 percent.
   Government officials have said inflation may reach 400 percent
for all of 1988 but independent analysts predict at least 500
percent. The previous high was 158.3 percent in 1985 and the
inflation rate for 1987 was 114.5 percent.
   Analysts said Salinas is expected to introduce new austerity
measures.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
