<FILEID>AP-NR-09-02-88 1124EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a e PM-APArts:Edinburgh Adv06   09-02 0518</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-AP Arts: Edinburgh, Adv 06,0533</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv 06</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Tues PMs, Sept 6 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Come Festival Time, The Name's The Thing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT WOLF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>EDINBURGH, Scotland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   What's in a name, you ask? At the
Edinburgh Festival, a lot.
   With 913 shows on the unofficial Festival Fringe competing for
theatergoers' time and money, participants found it's the name of
the event, not necessarily the work itself, that often is the thing.
   ``If it's an unknown play, the name can make people look
twice,'' playwright Eleanor Zeal said of her show ``The Tainted
Honey of Homicidal Bees,'' just one of numerous Fringe offerings
whose title immediately catches the eye.
   Indeed, visitors to the 42nd Festival Fringe, which ended on
Sept. 3, and which played alongside the Scottish capital's
higher-profile mainstream cultural binge, are besieged by any
number of suggestive, pun-filled or just plain odd titles chosen to
make one event stand out from the next.
   This year's entries ranged from take-offs on popular movies:
There's both a ``Futile Attraction'' and a ``Fatal Distraction,''
based on the box-office hit ``Fatal Attraction,'' as well as a
``Jean de Toilette,'' based on the critically acclaimed ``Jean de
Florette.''
   There also are Shakespearean send-ups such as ``Not Much of
Ado'' and ``Jesus Christ! It's Julius Caesar.'' Any title is
permissible on the Fringe as long as it's not libelous.
   Trisha Emblem, the Fringe assistant administrator, defined a
good title as one that's ``memorable, even if it's nothing witty.''
She cited ``The Life and Times of Hieronymus Bosch'' as a title
that was effective because of its distinctiveness.
   Sometimes, people don't realize how distinctive their title is.
   ``We didn't actually choose it to cause a stir,'' said Carolyn
Davies, co-director of ``Straight Laced, Jo Orton't, Jo Shouldn't,
Jo Wouldn't, Jo Couldn't, Jo Didn't,'' a satirical comedy that had
this year's longest name.
   ``We all sat around and thought, `OK, what are we going to call
it?' And suddenly, it arrived,'' Davies recalled, aware that length
has its disadvantages.
   ``We couldn't fit the name on the tickets,'' she said, ``but
it's on all the posters and leaflets.''
   One playwright was worried his title was too distinctive.
   ``I have a feeling a lot of people are going to say it's
strident,'' Simon Harries said of the title to his show ``Hold Your
Horses, Mussolini,'' a comedy with music and dancing about one King
Zog of Albania.
   But Harries, a 36 year-old marketing director who last wrote a
Fringe play 10 years ago, stood by his choice: ``It's honest; it
really does say what you need to know about the play. It's
immediately arresting and surprising.''
   And what if the title's good but the play itself isn't? All
agreed that there's the rub.
   ``There has to be something behind a title, an interesting
concept in the play itself,'' said Trisha Emblem.
   Speaking by telephone from his office in London, Simon Harries
said, ``I shall be there (in Edinburgh) every day ... talking to
people to find out why they came to see my show.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PM Tues Sept. 6</NOTE>
</DOC>
