<FILEID>AP-NR-09-02-88 1126EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a e PM-APArts:Costa-Gavras Adv09   09-02 0878</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-AP Arts: Costa-Gavras, Adv 09,0901</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv 09</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Fri PMs, Sept 9 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>A Filmmaker of Controversy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB THOMAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTA MONICA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Having made films about political
violence on three continents, Greek-born filmmaker Costa-Gavras now
turns his attention to racial terrorism in the United States.
   The movie is ``Betrayed,'' in which Debra Winger portrays an
undercover FBI agent who becomes the lover of Tom Berenger, a
Midwest farmer who leads a paramilitary white supremacy sect. The
story begins with the murder of a controversial radio talk-show
host and includes the robbing of banks to finance the movement.
   Once again a Costa-Gavras film has paralleled news events. His
most famous films portrayed U.S. involvement in the overthrow of
Chile's military regime (``Missing''), and military despotism in
Greece (``Z''). He has also dealt with torture in Latin America in
``State of Siege,'' Eastern Europe Stalinism in ``The Confession''
and the Palestinian issue in Israel with ``Hanna K.''
   Costa-Gavras, who has lived in France for many years, is no
stranger to controversy. He recently talked with accustomed
frankness about his work and politics during a visit to California
for the Hollywood opening of ``Betrayed.''
   Q. Is there something unique about racism in the United States?
   A. Here it's different. The expression of racism is probably
much more violent. The ideology of racism is the same everywhere,
unfortunately.
   Q. Did you do a lot of research for ``Betrayed''?
   A. Yes. The moment I started to do the movie, which means three
years ago, I started doing research in the different fields. You
find everything in television or in books or in newspaper
interviews. It's extraordinary; everything is there. I saw hours of
tapes.
   A lot of things happened during and after my research. Howard
Beach happened while I was researching. Then the Bernhard Goetz
story. All those things are extraordinary. I think the last 10-15
years is a kind of wave of racism.
   (Costa-Gavras was referring to a Dec. 20, 1986, incident in the
Howard Beach section of Queens, N.Y., in which a group of young
whites beat and chased some blacks, resulting in the death of one
black. Goetz, who is white, was convicted in June 1987 of a weapons
violation in the New York subway shooting of four black youths he
said he thought were going to rob him.)
   Q. Do you think racism has become more prevalent than before?
   A. Yes, I think so. I do not know the reasons. I try to
understand why. I think it always was there, somehow. But people
feel authorized to express themselves much more openly.
   Q. The most shocking scene in ``Betrayed'' is when the farmers,
armed with automatic guns, stage a kind of nighttime foxhunt of a
young black. Do you think that could happen in this country?
   A. No, I don't have any direct evidence that it happened. What
I'm trying to do there is make the scene as strong as possible,
just to show how unbearable, how frightening can be racist murder.
... I don't see much difference between killing a man on the street
because he is black or has a different religion, or hunting him. I
tried to dramatize how unacceptable that can be.
   Q. Why did you choose Debra Winger?
   A. Debra has the quality of being a strong person as a character
and an excellent actress. She also has a very personal involvement
in what is going on in the world. Those three elements are
essential for someone to play that kind of role.
   Q. And Tom Berenger?
   A. I like Tom's cowboy style _ handsome and clean, he has that
kind of face. And then it's like the moon: He has a dark side. All
of us have our dark side. The important thing is how far we go with
our dark side.
   Q. As an outsider, do you think you have a better view of
America?
   A. Maybe not better. Different, surely, because I have so much
curiosity about your society. Everything that happens here has a
direct effect on where we are coming from, the smaller countries of
Europe, socially and artistically.
   We have a curiosity and also a tenderness about your country,
because you have given us some many things: movies, theater,
literature, music. These things we grew up on.
   Q. Your films always seem to have political overtones. Is this
because of your particular psyche?
   A. I prefer to say ``ethical,'' a more hopeful view. But if we
say ``political,'' I think all movies contain political meaning. .
.. Every movie reflects the philosophy or the ethics of its
authors. Mine are no exception.
   Q. Do you deplore that outpouring of mindless violence and silly
comedies that pour forth from the studios, especially in the
summertime?
   A. Oh yes, yes. ... Let's take an example: the last ``Rambo.''
Everybody says, ``Let's be peaceful, let's try to understand each
other, East-West.'' Then you have something that exploits passion
and hate and all those things.
   But on the contrary, there is in the summertime some
extraordinary qualities (in films). I like very much the light
movies. I like to go and have fun; it's very pleasant.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PM Fri Sept. 9</NOTE>
</DOC>
