<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's largest general retailers were unable to break out
of their 18-month slump in August as weather conditions and
continuing problems in apparel lines depressed sales for yet
another month.
   ``We were looking for a pickup that would hopefully continue
through September and October,'' Fred Wintzer, a retail analyst for
Alex. Brown & Sons Inc., said Thursday after the retailers
announced their August sales figures.
   ``Some of the companies did worse in August than they did in
June and July,'' he said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Labor costs rose, productivity fell and
workers, despite higher wages, lost some of their purchasing power
in the second quarter, the government has reported.
   In revised figures for April through June, the Labor Department
said Thursday that the efficiency of non-farm businesses in
churning out goods and services dropped at an annual rate of 1.4
percent, its first quarterly decline since 1986.
   Labor costs shot up at an annual rate of 5.7 percent, the
biggest increase since 1986.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Construction spending in July posted its
sharpest increase in four months, but only partly recovered from a
June slump, the government reports.
   The Commerce Department said Thursday that building activity
rose 1.2 percent to a seasonally-adjusted annual rate of $401.0
billion in July, following a revised 1.5 percent drop in the
previous month. The June figure was originally estimated as a
slight 0.1 percent gain.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 9,000 people killed at work since
1981 might still be alive if the U.S. Occupational Safety and
Health Administration was doing its job, according to a
Chicago-based work safety group.
   However, statisticians and OSHA disputed the findings released
Thursday by the National Safe Workplace Institute. ``Workplaces are
getting safer,'' said OSHA spokesman Terry Mikelson. ``We've had a
very positive trend.''
   In its report, the Chicago institute contended OSHA's failure to
enforce job-safety laws puts American workers in jeopardy every day.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Critics of the Suzuki Samurai have failed to
demonstrate the sport-utility vehicle has an excessive tendency to
roll over, federal regulators have said in denying a recall
petition.
   However, the National Highway Traffic Safety Administration
began proceedings Thursday to establish standards to protect
drivers of all light-duty vehicles ``against unreasonable risk of
rollover.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Regulators extended by a day their talks with
the Robert M. Bass Group of Fort Worth, Texas, on a federal rescue
of American Savings and Loan Association of Stockton, Calif.
   In a statement released Thursday, M. Danny Wall, chairman of the
Federal Home Loan Bank Board, described the negotiations as
``intensive'' and said any announcement would be delayed by 24
hours.
   Industry sources say the proposal involves a contribution of
about $500 million from the Bass Group and up to $2 billion in
promissory notes from the bank board, which would make it the
largest rescue ever of a single S&L.
</TEXT>
