   San Diego Gas & Electric Co. has rejected an
unsolicited $2 billion takeover offer from the parent of Southern
California Edison, saying it preferred to merge with Arizona-based
Tucson Electric Power Co.
   Tom Paige, a senior executive of the San Diego utility, Thursday
said its long-term interests and its customers would be better
served by the Tucson deal, which would match Tucson Electric
Power's excess generating capacity with SDG&E's burgeoning customer
base.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federal Communications Commission is
moving closer to authorizing futuristic television systems with
movie film picture clarity and sound equal to that of compact discs.
   The commission made preliminary findings Thursday that will
allow research to proceed on the system, which is not likely to
begin in the United States until the mid-1990s.
   The FCC also sought public comment on options for using the
airwaves for so-called high definition TV, which is considered the
biggest television advance since color programming.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>FORT WORTH, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American Airlines says it hopes
lawsuits it filed in three cities against individuals and companies
will help end alleged abuses of the airline's frequent flier
program.
   ``We simply cannot tolerate this situation,'' airline spokesman
Lowell Duncan said Thursday.
   American's frequent flier program, called AAdvantage, stipulates
that customers earning free flights and other benefits cannot sell
their tickets to others. Members of the program may give awards to
anyone they choose, but the airline has repeatedly reminded people
that the awards can not be sold, purchased or bartered.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>HERSHEY, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hershey Foods Corp., trying to use its well
known name to capture the No. 2 position in the powdered chocolate
mix market, has announced a new mix that the company is shipping to
stores.
   Anthony Pingitore, general manager of Hershey's Grocery Products
Group, said Thursday that Hershey's Chocolate Milk Mix scored
highly in consumer trials during its 3{ years of development.
   Pingitore said the company set out in 1985 to find a mix that
would taste better and dissolve more easily in milk.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
