<1ST_LINE>r f PM-OilPrices     09-02 0323</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Oil Prices,0334</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Oil Futures Prices Close Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oil futures prices have responded negatively to
a report of more overproduction by OPEC.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, contracts for October
delivery of West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark U.S. crude oil,
fell 10 cents per barrel to close at $15.08 Thursday. Other
contract months also dropped.
   Contracts for refined petroleum products finished mixed.
Wholesale unleaded gasoline for October delivery rose 0.36 cent to
finish at 44.71 a gallon. The September gasoline contract fell 1.49
cents Wednesday, the last trading day before the contract expired.
Contracts for other months mostly were lower.
   Wholesale heating oil for October rose 0.14 cent to 43.46 cents
a gallon while other contract months were mixed.
   Analysts said the strength in gasoline and heating oil prevented
further declines in crude oil. They attributed the recent gains in
refined products to poor refinery economics. Outdated equipment,
for example, has lowered refinery capacity, keeping supply and
demand nearly equal, they said.
   ``Refining capacity has been pared down to the point where
refiners are having problems just keeping up with day to day
demand,'' said Jayne Ball, a commodity oil broker with Dean Witter
Reynolds Inc.
   Analysts said crude oil recovered from midday lows in response
to reports that the United Arab Emirates would exceed its
production quota set by the Organization of Petroleum Exporting
Countries.
   In recent days, oil futures prices weakened after reports that
OPEC's 13 member nations were exceeding their collective quotas by
more than 3 million barrels.
   ``All this overproduction in a market where demand factors
haven't been substantial tends to be a price weakening factor and
the market goes down,'' Ms. Ball said. ``UAE claims it's going to
have production up to 1.9 million barrels per day, more than double
its quota, which is about 990,000 barrels.''
   Ongoing uncertainty about developments between Iran and Iraq
also softened crude prices Thursday, traders said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880902-0245 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-02-88 0044EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-IBMAdvertising Bjt   09-02 0554</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-IBM Advertising, Bjt,0572</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>IBM Dumps Longtime Ad Agency, Picks Two New Agencies</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: No space is cq in Lintas:USA.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   International Business Machines Corp. has fired
its longtime ad agency, which created the memorable ad campaigns
showing a Charlie Chaplin-like character making his chaotic
business run smoothly with IBM products.
   The computer giant ended a three-month review of its advertising
agencies by selecting Lintas:USA, a unit of the Interpublic Group
of Companies, and Wells, Rich Greene Inc. for its U.S. advertising
assignment.
   The decision was the latest blow to its long-time agency, Lord
Geller Federico Einstein Inc., which is losing its biggest client
and has been wracked by internal turmoil for much of the year.
   IBM reportedly spends more than $100 million a year on
advertising. accounting for about half of Lord Geller's estimated
$200 million in billings.
   Lord Geller, which had competed to keep the account and expected
to retain at least some of it, has worked for IBM since 1979,
creating the Chaplinesque ads and, more recently, a series of IBM
ads reuniting the former stars of the television show ``M-A-S-H.''
   Lintas is best known for its Cover Girl, Diet Coke and Chevrolet
ads, while Wells Rich Greene makes ads for Ford Motor Co. and
Benson & Hedges cigarettes.
   ``We received shocking news this afternoon,'' Lord Geller
executives told the agency's employees in a memo. ``IBM has decided
to move its account to two large agencies.''
   William Wardell, Lord Geller president, said he hopes the agency
can win another computer account over the next few months while it
continues to work through during a transitional period for IBM.
   ``There has been no talk whatsoever about closing,'' he said.
   Lord Geller, a unit of WPP Group PLC, has been in turmoil since
six of its top executives, including chairman Richard Lord and
president Arthur Einstein, walked off the job on March 18 to form
their own agency, blaming interference from WPP's management.
   London-based WPP Group acquired Lord Geller along with the much
larger J. Walter Thompson ad agency in mid-1987 when it bought JWT
Group.
   The defectors eventually were joined by a number of Lord Geller
employees, including about 25 people who formerly worked on the IBM
account.
   The breakaway led to a contentious and unresolved court fight
between WPP Group and the new agency and its leaders.
   In early June, IBM said it would review its agency requirements
and advertising direction and invited a limited number of agencies
to compete for the assignment, including both Lord Geller and the
breakaway agency, Lord Einstein O'Neill & Partners.
   IBM spokeswoman Theo Chisholm said the company heard
presentations from six agencies. In addition to Lord Geller, Lord
Einstein and the two winners, they were D'Arcy Masius Benton &
Bowles and Grey Advertising.
   In announcing its decision, IBM declined to say how much it
spends on advertising or how that spending will be split between
the agencies.
   It said Lintas will be responsible for IBM desktop products,
including the Personal System-2 line of personal computers, while
Wells Rich Greene will do corporate advertising as well as
``marketing image advertising and solutions advertising programs.''
   At Lord Einstein, Chairman Richard Lord said he was disappointed
but added, ``We never expected any IBM business when we left
there.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
