<FILEID>AP-NR-09-02-88 0050EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-RetailSales Bjt   09-02 0746</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Retail Sales, Bjt,0768</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Weather, Fashion Problems Blamed For August Slump</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserGraphic</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOYCE M. ROSENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's largest general retailers still are waiting for
business to improve after continuing problems in apparel lines and
unusually hot weather depressed sales again during August.
   ``It is not encouraging as a harbinger of what back-to-school
and fall is going to look like,'' Joseph Ronning, a retail industry
analyst with the investment firm Brown Brothers Harriman Inc., said
after reviewing sales results announced Thursday by storeowners.
   ``Some of the companies did worse in August than they did in
June and July,'' said Fred Wintzer, an analyst with Alex. Brown &
Sons Inc. in Baltimore.
   Several analysts blamed the August slump on the abnormally hot
weather parts of the country suffered through last month.
   Jeffrey Feiner, an analyst with Merrill Lynch & Co., said the
underlying sluggish trend in consumer spending _ which began in
February 1987 _ also remained in place.
   Retail sales have been a soft spot in an otherwise strong
economy. Consumer spending, which also includes outlays for food,
medical care, autos, utilities, transportation and other
necessities, is closely watched because it accounts for two-thirds
of the gross national product.
   Some analysts dismissed the weather as a factor. Monroe
Greenstein, of Bear Stearns & Co., noted sales were disappointing
on the West Coast despite more normal temperatures there.
   Greenstein said women are still disenchanted with retailers'
fashion lines. It was a year ago, in August 1987, that apparel
retailers fell into a slide as women refused to buy shorter skirts
and clothes they perceived as boring.
   ``A lot of retailers are pushing back their expectations for a
good pickup in business until October,'' Greenstein said.
   Jeffrey Edelman, an analyst with Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc.,
said it was too early to get a good reading on how well the new
apparel lines are faring, but he said ``it appears as if some of
the new fashion is better than it was last year.''
   Edelman said some stores have reported a pickup in business this
week. Those sales will be reflected in retailers' September sales
figures.
   Several companies recorded sales increases under 3 percent,
meaning the stores were losing ground to inflation, which has run
at an annual rate of 4.5 percent so far this year.
   The nation's largest retailer, Sears, Roebuck and Co., said its
overall sales rose 6.3 percent from August 1987 levels, and its
sales for the first 30 weeks of the fiscal year increased 5.5
percent from the same period a year earlier. Sales from Sears
stores open at least a year _ known in the trade as same-store
sales _ were up 1.3 percent last month and 2 percent for the year
to date.
   Retailers and industry analysts believe same-store sales are a
more accurate yardstick of a company's performance than figures
which include sales from new stores. However, not all retailers
report both their overall and same-store results.
   K mart said its sales rose 6.4 percent in August, and 5.4
percent for the year so far. The retailer's same-store sales rose
2.2 percent for the month and 1.9 percent year-to-date.
   Wal-Mart Stores Inc. said its sales rose 24 percent overall last
month, and have risen 30 percent so far this year. Its same-store
sales were up 8 percent in August, and have risen 12 percent during
the first seven months.
   J.C. Penney Co. Inc. suffered a 2.6 percent drop in overall
sales last month, while sales for the year so far were up 1.8
percent. Same-store sales were down 3.4 percent last month while
rising 0.7 percent for the year so far.
   Dayton Hudson Corp. said its overall sales rose 15 percent last
month and 17.3 percent year-to-date. Same-store sales rose 1.7
percent in August and 1.5 percent for the first 30 weeks.
   May Department Stores Co. had a 19.6 percent jump in overall
sales in August while year-to-date sales improved 13 percent. May's
same-store sales were up 1.5 percent last month, and 1.3 percent
for the year so far.
   F.W. Woolworth Co. reported a 12 percent increase in August
sales, and an 11.9 percent rise for the first 30 weeks.
   Montgomery Ward & Co. said its August sales were up 4.7 percent,
while year-to-date sales rose 3 percent.
   The results were from general merchandise and apparel retailers.
Unlike monthly retail sales figures released by the federal
government, they do not include sales at auto dealers, supermarkets
or restaurants.
</TEXT>
