<1ST_LINE>r f PM-DetroitNewspapers     09-02 0523</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Detroit Newspapers,0540</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Detroit JOA `Blueprint' for Gannett Expansion, Arkansas Newspaper
Alleges</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM BOVEE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A partial merger between the Detroit News and
Detroit Free Press would mean trouble for the 25 other U.S. cities
that still have competing newspapers, according to an Arkansas
newspaper.
   The Arkansas Democrat of Little Rock filed a legal brief
Thursday supporting efforts to block a proposed joint operating
agreement between the News, owned by Gannett Co. Inc., and the Free
Press, owned by Knight-Ridder Inc.
   The Democrat's main competitor is the Arkansas Gazette, which is
owned by Gannett, the nation's largest newspaper chain. Gannett
bought the Gazette in 1986, the same year it acquired the News.
   Attorney General Edwin Meese III approved the Detroit JOA on
Aug. 8, shortly before leaving office. Court challenges followed,
and the partial merger was delayed at least until next week, when
it is to be reviewed by a federal judge in Washington.
   ``A decision approving the JOA in this case would be a decision
providing a blueprint for the elimination of competition in the
remaining 25 cities with two newspapers,'' the Democrat's attorneys
said.
   Meese's decision, in designating the Free Press a failing
newspaper, ignored evidence that the newspaper's losses resulted
from strategic decisions rather than market economics, the brief
said.
   The Democrat asked the court ``to rule that a newspaper is not
failing when its losses are the result of predation.''
   The Democrat's brief said Gannett operated both the News and the
Arkansas Gazette at substantial losses in order to force smaller
competitors to incur more painful losses.
   ``Gannett's strategy in acquiring the newspapers in Detroit and
Little Rock was not to operate either profitably in a competitive
market, but was instead to eliminate competition either by
destroying its rival or by forcing its rival into a joint operating
arrangement,'' the brief said.
   Six days after Meese approved the Detroit agreement, the Gazette
lowered subscription prices to 85 cents per week from $1.98 per
week, the brief said.
   Gannett spokeswoman Sheila Owens said the company would not
comment immediately on the Democrat's allegations.
   Bill Malone, publisher of the Arkansas Gazette, said the Detroit
agreement ``has nothing to do with us at all here at the Gazette.''
   ``Number one, this price reduction was on the drawing board long
before we knew anything about the outcome of the JOA situation in
Detroit,'' he said. ``Number two, we're not trying to put them out
of business.
   ``If you will look at the things we have done, it's just to
match them _ free classifieds, we matched them with free
classifieds. As far as circulation pricing, all we've been doing is
matching what they've already been doing.''
   The Detroit agreement would merge News and Free Press production
and business operations while keeping separate the newspapers' news
and editorial departments. Profits and losses would be shared
equally by the newspapers after the first five years of the
100-year agreement.
   The newspapers sought exemption from federal antitrust laws
under the Newspaper Preservation Act, which allows such partial
mergers when one of the newspapers is declared in danger of failing.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
