<FILEID>AP-NR-09-02-88 0958EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Japan-Surplus     09-02 0277</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Japan-Surplus,0287</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Japan's Current Account Surplus In July Declines</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japan posted a current account surplus of $6.48
billion in July, down 11 percent from $7.28 billion a year earlier
but up slightly from $6.43 billion in June, the Finance Ministry
said Friday.
   The current account is the broadest measure of trade and
includes goods, services and investment income plus various
monetary transfers and aid payments.
   The surplus in the trade of goods alone widened from the
year-earlier level for the first time in 13 months, going up to
$8.76 billion from $8.58 billion. It also was up from a $7.38
billion surplus registered in June.
   The ministry said it is too early to conclude that Japan's
downtrend in the trade surplus has come to a halt. The July rise in
the merchandise trade surplus had been reported in early August
using a slightly different measure that made it the first such
increase in 15 months.
   The trade surplus, the main target of criticism from the United
States, European countries and other major trade partners of Japan,
had been declining consistently due to the yen's sharp appreciation
since 1985. A higher yen would restrain exports by making Japanese
goods less competitive abroad.
   Exports in July rose 16.8 percent over a year earlier to $22.8
billion, while imports surged 28.2 percent to a record $14.0
billion.
   Ministry officials said exports of ships, office automation
equipment, semiconductors, television sets and cameras were strong.
Exports also included parts and components that Japanese companies
shipped to their subsidiaries in other Asian countries for
assembly, they said.
   No breakdown of the trade surplus by countries or regions was
given.
</TEXT>
