<2ND_LINE>PM-ZZZZ Best,0224</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hearing Ordered On Witness Tampering Allegations</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge has ordered a hearing to
consider allegations that potential witnesses were intimidated by
defense investigators in the fraud trial of Barry Minkow, founder
of the now-defunct ZZZZ Best Co.
   U.S. District Judge Dickran Tevrizian ordered the hearing
Thursday after prosecutors claimed two potential witnesses said
they felt threatened by investigators working for defense attorney
David Kenner.
   ``We're going to talk to all the witnesses to see if there was
any tampering with witnesses or any intimidation,'' Tevrizian said.
``If that's the indication, I'll order the U.S. Attorney's Office
to file charges.''
   Minkow, who founded the carpet-cleaning firm in his parents'
garage when he was 15, has been charged in a 57-count indictment
accusing him of defrauding investors and banks out of more than $24
million. The trial began last month.
   ``This is an obvious attempt to intimidate the defense in
interviewing and preparing our case,'' said Kenner, who contends
that Minkow, now 22, was forced into the elaborate fraud by
mobsters.
   Investigator Paul Palladino, whose San Francisco firm worked for
the defense in the John DeLorean cocaine trial, denied threatening
or intimidating anyone.
   ``I haven't been doing this for 15 years to make that kind of
mistake,'' the investigator said.

</TEXT>
