<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Northrop-Lawsuit     09-02 0345</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Northrop-Lawsuit,0358</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Stockholders File Lawsuit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two Northrop Corp. shareholders have filed
lawsuits against 38 current and former Northrop officials and
directors accusing them of illegal activities in connection with
the aerospace company's major defense programs, including the
failed F-20 Tigershark jet fighter.
   The suits, filed Thursday on behalf of Northrop, charge the
defendants with breach of fiduciary duties and violations of
various California statutes.
   The lawsuits, which also name Northrop as a defendant, seek the
return of all salaries and other compensation paid the directors,
officers and outside consultants as well as unspecified damages to
be paid to Northrop.
   The company has denied any impropriety.
   The suits, filed in state Superior Court by stockholders
Gabrielle Mayran and Rodney Shields, accuse the defendants of
wrongdoing in connection with most of Northrop's major defense
programs.
   Highlighted in the lawsuits was the failed attempt to sell South
Korea the F-20 Tigershark fighter plane, which the company couldn't
sell after spending $1.2 billion to build it.
   Mayran and Shields claim Northrop officials paid bribes in 1983
and 1984 to South Korean government officials to entice them to buy
the Tigershark.
   ``Many millions of Northrop's corporate funds have been wasted
in illegal bribes and expenditures in an unsuccessful effort to
sell the F-20 Tigershark fighter plane while over $1 billion of its
corporate funds were wasted prior thereto in an inept attempt to
develop and sell the F-20 Tigershark,'' the suit said.
   A congressional committee and a federal grand jury in Los
Angeles already are looking into payments the company made to
Korean companies and individuals in connection with attempts to
sell the ill-fated fighter.
   The suits also accuse the defendants of wrongdoing in connection
with the MX missile and the B-2 stealth bomber, saying problems in
both systems were ``due to the incompetence and mismanagement'' of
Northrop executives.
   The defendants include Thomas V. Jones, Northrop's chairman and
chief executive officer; Ken Kressa, president and chief operating
officer; 12 other company directors; 21 current and former Northrop
executives and employees; and three outside consultants.
</TEXT>
