<1ST_LINE>u f PM-ContinentalLawsuits     09-02 0268</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Continental Lawsuits,0276</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Continental Allowed to Use State Law in Crash Lawsuit Cases</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Continental Airlines won a major federal court
victory when a judge ruled lawsuits from the 1987 crash of a
Continental jetliner at Denver will be tried under Colorado law.
   The decision, reached Thursday, would allow a maximum award of
$45,000 in physical damages to relatives of crash victims who have
no dependants.
   The decision could save the carrier millions of dollars because
Colorado law is considered the most restrictive in the nation in
assessing damages. Lawyers for crash victims had sought trial under
a more liberal Texas law.
   U.S. District Court Judge Sherman G. Finesilver has not yet
decided what law will govern the award of punitive damages _ those
damages awarded if the airline or others are found negligent. A
hearing on that issue is set for Oct. 18.
   The National Transportation Safety Board is scheduled to release
its ruling on the cause of the crash at a hearing in Washington
D.C. on Sept. 27.
   Continental Flight 1713 crashed on takeoff Nov. 15, 1987,
killing 28 passengers and crew. Dozens of suits have been filed
against the airline and its parent, Texas Air Corp.
   Finesilver also on Thursday set a Dec. 5 trial date for crash
lawsuits. He ruled that only one of the suits will be tried then as
a way to save time and money. The outcome of that suit, which will
be selected as the most representative of the lot, will determine
how much liability will be placed on the airline and other parties
in the case.
</TEXT>
