<2ND_LINE>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0312</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Crop Futures Open Slightly Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Futures prices for grain and soybeans opened
slightly lower today on the Chicago Board of Trade on profit-taking
ahead of the long Labor Day weekend.
   ``We had some pretty good gains here during the week and now
people are cashing in,'' said Victor Lespinasse, a trader with Dean
Witter Reynolds Inc. in Chicago.
   He said additional early selling pressure stemmed from an
increase in farmers' sales of corn and soybeans overnight and from
the Agriculture Department's rejection this morning of China's
second bid for 300,000 metric tons of subsidized U.S. wheat.
   Some analysts said traders were disappointed by the USDA's
announcement late Thursday that the Soviet Union had purchased only
100,000 metric tons of U.S. corn. Rumors earlier in the day had put
the Soviet corn purchase at 1 million metric tons.
   In early trading, wheat was { cent to 2\ cents lower with the
contract for delivery in September at $3.97{ a bushel; corn was
unchanged to 2 cents lower with September at $2.89 a bushel; oats
were } cent to 1{ cents lower with September at $2.59{ a bushel;
soybeans were 2{ cents to 4 cents lower with September at $8.65 a
bushel.
   Cattle futures were mostly higher while pork futures were mixed
in early trading on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .05 cent to .15 cent higher with October at
71.25 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .15 cent lower to .13 cent
higher with September at 81.05 cents a pound; hogs were .10 cent
lower to .15 cent higher with October at 38.90 cents a pound;
frozen pork bellies were .02 cent lower to .33 cent higher with
February at 49.20 cents a pound.
   Livestock and meat futures closed mixed on Thursday.
