<FILEID>AP-NR-09-02-88 1158EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-UtilityInvestigation     09-02 0469</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Utility Investigation,0481</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>IRS Extends Arthur Andersen Probe To Electric Cooperatives Around
Country</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. Agriculture Department and Internal
Revenue Service are studying the books of 11 electric cooperatives
and utilities with ties to the Chicago accounting firm of Arthur
Andersen & Co.
   The inquiry is focusing on possible tax violations and illegal
accounting practices by Oglethorpe Power Corp., an Atlanta-based
electric cooperative.
   Richard Allen, USDA's Southeast regional inspector general, said
the government also is examining the role of Arthur Andersen, the
nation's largest accounting firm and the auditor for all 11
cooperatives.
   Allen said that records from the companies were subpoenaed in
June, but that the cooperatives were not necessarily targets of the
federal probe at that time.
   All of the cooperatives are recipients of loans from the Rural
Electrification Administration, which is part of the Agriculture
Department, he said.
   Oglethorpe, which is owned by and provides electricity to 39 of
Georgia's 42 electric membership corporations, has been the target
of both a civil and criminal investigation by the IRS over its tax
returns from 1980 through 1983. It also reported this year it was
under investigation by the Agriculture Department.
   The IRS, in a related probe, is investigating Atlanta-based
Southern Co., the utility holding company, and its subsidiaries,
including the Georgia Power Co., in connection with allegations
that Southern defrauded the government of millions of dollars by
improperly accounting for spare parts.
   During the past week, investigators from the inspector general's
office spent three days examining records at the Raleigh offices of
the North Carolina Electric Membership Corp., said spokesman Owen
Bishop.
   Carl Whillock, president of the Arkansas Electric Cooperative
Corp. in Little Rock, Ark., said his company provided a ``limited
number'' of accounting documents in response to a June subpoena but
had heard nothing from investigators since then.
   ``They told us the subpoena they've issued to us does not mean
we are the target of an investigation,'' Whillock said.
   Sunflower Electric Membership Corp. in Hays, Kan., also received
a subpoena for records relating to its dealings with Arthur
Andersen, The Atlanta Constitution quoted an unidentified spokesman
as saying.
   An unidentified spokeswoman for the Rural Electrification
Administration identified the cooperatives in the inquiry, besides
Oglethorpe, as the Sacramento Municipal Utility District of
Sacramento, Calif.; United Power Association of Elk River, Minn.;
Dairyland Power Cooperative of LaCrosse, Wis.; Corn Belt Power
Cooperative of Humboldt, Iowa; Sunflower Electric Cooperative of
Hays, Kan.; North Carolina Electric Membership Corp. of Raleigh;
Arkansas Electric Cooperative of Little Rock; Square Butte Electric
Cooperative of Grand Forks, N.D.; Eastern Iowa Light and Power
Cooperative of Wilton, Iowa; Thumb Electric Cooperative of Ubly,
Mich., and Owen County Rural Electric Cooperative Corp. of Owenton,
Ky.
   David Kaplan, general counsel for the Sacramento Municipal
Utility District, said the utility had not been subpoenaed.
</TEXT>
