<1ST_LINE>r f BC-OPEC-Oil     09-02 0490</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-OPEC-Oil,0507</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Subroto Calls For Revamped OPEC Production Policy</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subroto as one word is correct</NOTE>
<DATELINE>KUWAIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   OPEC Secretary-General Subroto arrived in Kuwait
Friday after visits to Baghdad and Tehran, where he apparently
failed to settle the problem of setting oil output levels for Iraq
and Iran.
   In arrival statements, Subroto indicated that he saw a solution
only through a revamped production policy for the entire 13-member
Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries.
   Subroto's talks in Iran and Iraq this week reportedly focused on
the question of whether Iraq should be allowed to increase its oil
production quota to parity with Iran.
   The Kuwait News Agency quoted him as saying it was ``necessary
that OPEC member states look into this problem (Iraq and Iran
output) within the framework of the basic issue from which OPEC
suffers ... overproduction by OPEC member states beyond the 15.06
million barrels daily ceiling.''
   Iraq has refused to adhere to its quota of 1.54 million barrels
a day, demanding parity with Iran's 2.369 million. Iraq's
unrestrained current output is estimated at 2.8 million barrels a
day.
   KUNA said Subroto indicated the Iraq-Iran production controversy
``cannot be solved separately from the rest of the pending issues
related to OPEC production.''
   Among the issues Subroto is discussing during his current tour
of Persian Gulf nations is the production level of the United Arab
Emirates, which he visited on an earlier tour and which currently
is estimated to be producing at least twice its allotted quota. The
U.A.E. announced its quota should be 1.5 million barrels a day
instead of its alloted 948,000.
   Since late 1986, the cartel has slashed its aggregate output by
more than 3 million barrels per day to try to stabilize nosediving
prices around an $18-a-barrel benchmark.
   But quota violations by member states has made the target price
elusive. OPEC's current output is about 20 million barrels although
the official overall ceiling set by the cartel is 15.06 million,
excluding Iraq.
   In Kuwait last week on his way to Tehran and Baghdad, Subroto
said he believed it was reasonable that Iraq and Iran should have
equal quotas of 2.3 million barrels a day.
   His statements to KUNA here confirmed he had made no headway so
far. But he was quoted as saying ``we have not yet despaired and we
still have a number of proposals in this connection.''
   Subroto said he discussed with Iraqi and Iranian officials ``the
future level of output for each of Iraq and Iran,'' KUNA reported.
He could not predict when a settlement was possible and said a
single visit to each capital ``is difficult for reaching a
solution.''
   In Baghdad earlier in the day, Subroto declined to comment to
reporters on the result of his talks there. Iraqi officials
described the talks as ``satisfactory.''
   The official Iraqi News Agency said only that Iraq's oil
minister, Issam Abdul-Rahim al-Chalabi, and Subroto discussed
recent developments in the oil market.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
