<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Boisjoly-Thiokol 1stLd-Writethru f0024 09-02 0671</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Boisjoly-Thiokol, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0024,0692</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Dismisses Engineer's Suits Against Morton Thiokol</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with formal ruling filed; ADDS detail and
EDITS throughout to conform; ADDS byline; No pickup; Also moved on
general newswires</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT MIMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge today dismissed two
lawsuits seeking $3 billion from space shuttle rocket-maker Morton
Thiokol Inc. by a former company engineer who warned against the
ill-fated 1986 Challenger launch.
   U.S. District Judge David K. Winder granted Morton Thiokol's
request for dismissal of the suits filed by Roger Boisjoly, who
left the company in July 1986, citing physical ailments and alleged
mental torment.
   Telephone calls to Boisjoly's Willard home were not immediately
returned.
   In his decision, Winder dismissed most counts in Boisjoly's
suits with prejudice, meaning they cannot be refiled.
   But the judge said he would dismiss two counts of one suit,
which deal with allegations of defamation and conspiracy, without
prejudice.
   In one suit, Boisjoly sought $1 billion for the deaths of the
seven astronauts killed when Challenger exploded on Jan. 28, 1986,
and $1 million in compensatory damages for Boisjoly's health and
career.
   Boisjoly claimed Morton Thiokol impugned his professional
reputation after he and other engineers testified before a
presidential commission investigating the disaster that they had
warned against the launch.
   His other lawsuit, filed under the False Claims Act on behalf of
U.S. taxpayers, sought $2.075 billion and alleged that Morton
Thiokol knowingly provided NASA with defective solid rocket motors.
   Winder ruled that ``the `conspiracy' alleged in the complaint is
not of a nature to support an action for damages on the part of
Boisjoly. ... Neither the conspiracy itself nor the overt acts
allegedly done in furtherance of it were directed toward Boisjoly.''
   The judge wrote that ``to suggest that the recommendation or the
launch were acts directed toward and for the purpose of injuring
Boisjoly is ridiculous.''
   ``Furthermore, for a reasonable person to know that Boisjoly
might suffer emotional injury as a result of the launch would
include the requirement that the person know that the launch would
end in disaster,'' Winder added.
   ``The dismissal of these two suits completely vindicates Morton
Thiokol,'' said Morton Thiokol spokesman Ed Snow. ``We are very
happy to have this situation behind us.''
   Company attorneys had argued that Boisjoly's contention that he
was defamed was based on office chatter. ``It is just
workplace-related talk that goes on all the time,'' attorney Robert
Jordan told the judge at a hearing in February.
   However, Boisjoly's attorney, Robert Levin, accused company
officials of launching a campaign to defame the engineer through
pamphlets and interviews.
   ``This is not a disgruntled person,'' Levin argued. ``This is an
engineer who stood up and risked his career and hurt his health
because he had this alternate view.''
   In a May interview, Boisjoly said it was only after two years of
therapy and ``the positive catharsis'' of lecturing on the disaster
that he was able to stop blaming himself for the destruction of the
shuttle and deaths of its astronauts.
   ``For a long time, I bore the burden of guilt because I hadn't
done more to stop it,'' he said. ``But I've resolved it now. I did
everything I could.''
   Boisjoly and several other Morton Thiokol engineers argued the
night before the launch that temperatures of 53 degrees or less
could cause a rocket joint seal to fail.
   But after a second caucus with NASA officials, Boisjoly said,
company managers ``perceived pressure from NASA. ... There was no
other justification for the launch. I felt the pressure, others
felt the pressure.''
   The Rogers Commission, which investigated the disaster, blamed
the tragedy on a leaking joint seal that allowed superhot gases to
escape and ignite the shuttle's external fuel tank. Investigators
said the cold had weakened the seal.
   Boisjoly took disability leave in July 1986, and left the
company for good two months later.
   This year, he won the Scientific Freedom and Responsibility
Award from the American Association for Advancement of Science.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
