<HEAD>Dollar, Gold Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar fell against major currencies in
European trading Friday after the announcement of slightly
higher-than-expected U.S. August unemployment data.
   Gold prices also fell.
   Foreign exchange dealers said the dollar dropped sharply against
the West German mark after the U.S. Labor Department's announcement
that the unemployment rate had risen to 5.6 percent from 5.4
percent in July.
   Most traders had expected the unemployment rate to have remained
at about the same levels as July, they said.
   One trader at a German bank in Frankfurt said the unemployment
data accelerated an already noticeable downward trend in the U.S.
currency because the data suggested the American economy is slowing
down, dampening expectations that the United States would increase
interest rates in the near future.
   However, trading generally was quiet Friday, with many market
participants confused about the market outlook and unwilling to
take positions before the upcoming three-day Labor Day weekend in
the United States.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day
begins, the dollar rose 0.05 yen to a closing 136.75 yen. Later, in
London, it was quoted at 137.65 yen.
   Other late dollar rates, compared with late Thursday: 1.8665
West German marks, down from 1.8795 1.5725 Swiss francs, down from
1.5835; 6.3365 French francs, down from 6.3780; 2.1050 Dutch
guilders, down from 2.1205; 1,388.50 Italian lire, down from
1,398.50; 1.2362 Canadian dollars, down from 1.2370.
   In London, the British pound fetched $1.6755, compared with
$1.6730 Thursday.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $429.40 a troy ounce and
at midmorning the city's five major bullion dealers fixed a
recommended price of $428.95. Late Friday, gold fell to $427.50.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $428, down from $430.50 late
Thursday.
   Earlier in Hong Kong, gold fell $1.26 to close at $431.35.
   Silver was quoted in London on Friday at a bid price of $6.52 a
troy ounce, down from $6.58 Thursday.
</TEXT>
