<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices closed at their best levels Friday on
the London Stock Exchange, buoyed by a strong opening on Wall
Street.
   Dealers said London shares also were boosted by higher U.S.
unemployment figures for August announced in Washington, which
eased fears of inflationary pressures.
   At the end of trading, the Financial Times-Stock Exchange
100-share index was up 16.4 points, or 0.94 percent, at 1,746.9,
its best level for the day. The index hit its low point of 2.9
points higher shortly after the opening.
   Dealers said Wall Street's early 26.49-point surge in the Dow
Jones industrial average, to 2,028.81, was sparked by July's
revision to the non-farm payroll component within the latest U.S.
employment data. In addition, the rise in the jobless rate in
August to 5.6 percent from 5.4 percent in July calmed inflationary
worries.
   The Labor Department in Washington said U.S. non-farm payroll
jobs created in August totaled 219,000. The revised unemployment
rate for July remained unchanged at 5.4 percent, but the non-farm
payroll gain was revised downward to 200,000 jobs from 283,000 jobs.
   Market expectations had been for an unchanged jobless rate in
August and non-farm payrolls at around 224,000.
