<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Belgium-Donnay     09-02 0157</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Belgium-Donnay,0164</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tapie Reaches Tentaive Donnay Takeover Deal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A tentative deal was reached Friday for
French businessman Bernard Tapie to take a majority share in Donnay
SA, the Belgian sporting goods maker that went bankrupt last month,
officials said.
   Under the accord Tapie will get 51 percent of Donnay which until
its bankruptcy was majority-owned by the Donnay family.
   The government of Wallonia, Belgium's French-speaking southern
half, will get a 29 percent stake and Albert Frere, head of Group
Bruxelles Lambert, the holding that owns Belgium's second largest
bank, will control 20 percent.
   Donnay, the world's top maker of tennis rackets a decade ago,
was declared bankrupt Aug. 12 after it failed to agree with
creditors on new funds and a restructuring of its debt which totals
$35 million.
   Donnay reached its peak when Bjorn Borg advertised its products,
but began to suffer losses after the Swedish tennis ace retired in
1981.
</TEXT>
