<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Peru-Economy     09-02 0248</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Peru-Economy,0259</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Economy Minister Resigns as Inflation Soars</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LIMA, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Peru's economy minister resigned Friday, three
months after taking office, following a government report that
showed inflation soared a record 243 percent during the first eight
months of the year.
   President Alan Garcia immediately appointed a new economy
minister, Abel Salinas, to fill the post vacated by Cesar Robles,
the official gazette El Peruano said.
   Analysts said Robles' resignation was expected after
disagreements arose in the Cabinet of Ministers over how to
reactivate the nation's recession-ridden economy.
   Salinas, current energy minister and former interior minister,
was expected to move quickly to combat inflation with another round
of austerity measures, analysts said.
   Jorge Carrasco, a congressional deputy and president of the
Chamber of Deputies' Energy Commission, is to head the energy
ministry, the gazette said.
   Robles, the third economy minister in Garcia's center-left
government, assumed his post just three months ago as a recession
deepened and inflation skyrocketed.
   According to the government report, manufacturing has continued
to decline, shortages of basic consumer products are widespread and
the cost of living rose 30.9 percent in July, the highest single
month total in Peruvian history.
   The National Statistics Institute said in a gazette communique
Friday that August consumer prices increased 21.7 percent over the
July level, and 243 percent from January through August.
   Independent analysts project inflation will pass 500 percent
this year. The previous high mark was 158.3 percent in 1985.
Inflation last year was 114.5 percent.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
