<DOCNO> AP880902-0270 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-02-88 1533EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Japan-IndexFutures Bjt   09-02 0661</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Japan-Index Futures, Bjt,0678</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Stock Index Futures, an American Invention, Debuts in Japan</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Saturday in lead graf is correct.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Trading of stock-index futures began Saturday in
Japan, theoretically giving investors a new opportunity to protect
themselves if and when the big rally in the world's largest
securities market ends.
   Although stock-index futures have been blamed by some critics
for playing a significant role in the October stock market crash in
the United States, there seems to be little concern the same thing
could happen here, partly because of what strategists called
Japan's penchant for caution.
   ``The Japanese are a very wise people,'' said Alan Johnson, an
Asian-Pacific futures specialist at Citicorp Scrimgeour Vickers
International Ltd. ``They like to acclimatize themselves properly
before doing anything. Going off the board isn't their way of life.
Their way of life is to do all their homework very carefully and
make sure it works.''
   A distinctly American financial invention that the Japanese have
been eying for years, stock index futures are obligations to buy or
sell the equivalent cash value of a group of stocks at a set price
on a set date.
   Purchased for only a small fraction of their total worth, index
futures theoretically enable investors to bet on the overall
direction of the stock market. Index futures can serve as hedging
mechanisms against a market drop or an inexpensive way to speculate
on a market advance.
   Their eagerly awaited premiere in Japan comes at a particularly
opportune time, because Japanese stock prices have been trading
near their record highs. There has been increasing concern over how
long the rally will last, and investors have been looking for ways
to protect themselves in a decline.
   The debut of index futures in Japan also coincides with
simmering controversy in the United States on the impact of such
financial strategies. U.S. critics say index futures encourage
reckless speculation and conflict with the kind of long-term
investing in individual stocks that is essential for healthy
markets.
   Moreover, the critics contend, the development of high-speed
computerized trading of index futures and the stocks that comprise
them in order to profit from price differences, a technique called
index arbitrage, has injected frightening volatility into the
markets and discouraged would-be investors.
   Some studies have blamed index arbitrage for aggravating the
Oct. 19 collapse of stock prices in the United States.
   In U.S. trading, the most popular index futures are based on the
Standard & Poor's 500-stock index, and the Major Market Index, a
measurement of 20 stocks that closely tracks the more widely known
Dow Jones Industrial Average.
   The Japanese concocted their index futures based on the Nikkei
Index of 225 Selected Issues, which began trading Saturday on the
Osaka Securities Exchange, and the Tokyo Stock Price Index, called
Topix, which began trading on the Tokyo Stock Exchange.
   Japanese market professionals said trading began slowly,
reflecting an underlying cautious approach. They said it would
probably take a few years for the Japanese to develop profitable
index arbitrage computerized strategies, and in the meantime the
impact on stock prices likely would be small.
   Part of the problem in developing such strategies, they said, is
that some stocks represented in the Nikkei or Topix indexes cannot
be traded via computer, which makes complicated arbitrage
strategies difficult.
   In addition, Japanese stock markets are protected from wild
swings by the daily limits placed on individual shares, another
potential obstacle to profitable arbitrage between stocks and index
futures.
   Both the Nikkei and Topix contracts will have a limit of 3
percent for a single day of trade, although if the market is
orderly then exchange officials have the power to allow continued
trading.
   ``Of course when volume builds up over time, the futures will
become another factor affecting stocks,'' said a futures trader at
Salomon Brothers Inc.'s Tokyo office, who asked not to be
identified by name. ``But I don't think there will be all that much
speculative interest.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
