<FILEID>AP-NR-09-02-88 1609EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Eternity Bjt   09-02 0657</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Eternity, Bjt,0680</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Minnetonka Corp. Invests Fortune In Sequel To Obsession Perfume</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TONY KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BLOOMINGTON, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For Minnetonka Corp., there may be
only one ``Obsession.'' But now the company hopes to extend its
success in the personal fragrance business into ``Eternity.''
   Minnetonka is spending about $18 million to launch Eternity,
another Calvin Klein fragrance that the company says will appeal to
a growing set of Americans interested in true romance and lasting
love.
   Robert Taylor, founder and chairman of Bloomington-based
Minnetonka, said he expects the new, floral scent to be as popular
as its steamier predecessor, Obsession.
   ``Obsession stands for the '60s and '70s of the sexual
revolution. It's warm and sensual,'' Taylor said. ``I think
Eternity stands for love, romance and commitment.''
   Regardless of the values they espouse, both perfumes have the
smell of money.
   Obsession is the sales leader at Calvin Klein Cosmetics Corp.,
the subsidiary that accounted for an estimated $105 million of
Minnetonka's 1987 sales of $152.4 million, said Marsha Raley, a
stock analyst for Dain Bosworth Inc., Minneapolis.
   ``We think Eternity will be as big as Obsession,'' Taylor said.
   Largely on the continued strength of Obsession sales, Minnetonka
is expected to record net income in 1988 of about $15.5 million, or
95 cents a share, Raley said. That compares with net income of
$10.1 million, or 57 cents a share, in 1987, not counting the
after-tax gain of $65 million on the sale of Softsoap to
Colgate-Palmolive Co.
   ``They're very creative,'' Raley said. ``They're good at
identifying mass psychology trends.
   ``If you read the public right and you simplify what the public
wants and you color it the way you think they want it colored then
you end up striking a successful chord,'' Raley said.
   Taylor and Kim Delsing, executive vice president of Calvin Klein
Cosmetics, credit the fashion designer for attaching significance
to Eternity. Klein is settling down after undergoing treatment for
an addiction to vodka and valium and his life mirrors the message
of Eternity, Delsing said. In fact, the fragrance got its name from
an inscription on a ring purchased by Klein about a year ago for
his wife. He bought the ring from a Duke of Windsor collection.
   ``Everything about Eternity so epitomizes his new lifestyle,''
Delsing said.
   But Eternity wasn't designed in ``random creative'' fashion,
Taylor said. Instead, Minnetonka identified a niche in the perfume
market opposite Obsession and screened the samples that Klein chose
from.
   ``It's more of a directed creative approach,'' Taylor said. ``We
didn't want to cannibalize Obsession.''
   Minnetonka has hopes that both fragrances will prove to be
classics. Channel No. 5, for instance, has survived for 65 years.
   Taylor, whose company acquired Calvin Klein Cosmetics in 1981,
said he'll keep Obsession and Eternity alive by restricting
distribution to about 700 stores. At $185 an ounce _ $10 more than
Obsession _ Eternity is decidedly upscale and gets prime display
space, he said.
   ``We don't do anything unless it's prime,'' Taylor said.
   Eternity made its debut from June through August at two Saks
Fifth Avenue stores in New York. Its national launch officially
began this week, but Dayton Hudson department stores have been
selling it since the first weekend in August, said John Brennan, a
senior buyer of fine fragrances for Minneapolis-based Dayton Hudson
   ``It's been tremendously successful,'' Brennan said. ``We had
customers literally grabbing four or five bottles off the first
cart as it was being unpacked.''
   Taylor said Eternity has been his company's chief focus for the
past year. Next year an Eternity for men will be developed and
Calvin Klein Cosmetics will introduce a line of dressing
accessories such as belts, purses and cosmetic bags.
   Meanwhile, Calvin Klein continues to hold about 12 percent of
Minnetonka Corp. stock, which has been selling in the range of $16
a share. Taylor said Klein has no intention of seeking a
controlling interest in the company.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
