<1ST_LINE>r f AM-3MFine     09-02 0152</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-3M Fine,0157</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>EPA to Fine 3M $1.4 Million</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Environmental Protection Agency said
Friday it plans to levy a $1.4 million civil fine against Minnesota
Mining and Manufacturing Corp. for illegally importing and using
two unspecified chemicals.
   The agency said it had cut the proposed penalty in half because
the St. Paul, Minn.-based company voluntarily disclosed the
violations immediately after they occurred.
   The agency said it was not disclosing the chemicals in question
and the dates of the violations because 3M was entitled to keep
that information confidential.
   Federal law forbids manufacturing, importing and commercial use
of chemicals not on EPA's approved list unless the agency is given
90 days notice to review the new chemical.
   3M has 20 days to answer EPA's charges. In St. Paul, company
spokesman Mark Fenner said he was unable to comment because he had
not been made aware of the accusations.
</TEXT>
