<FILEID>AP-NR-09-02-88 2141EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Coca-Cola-NFLAds     09-02 0446</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Coca-Cola-NFL Ads,0462</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Coca-Cola Plans NFL Lineup in Diet Coke Commercials</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The soft drink makers are recruiting some tough
characters for commercials designed to convince men that it's okay
to drink diet colas.
   This summer it was boxer Mike Tyson in commercials for Diet
Pepsi. This fall, it will be a few dozen pro football players for
Diet Coke.
   It's a new approach for sugarless sodas, a majority of which
have traditionally been consumed by women.
   A decade ago, the soft drink makers say, women consumed about 75
percent of the diet soft drinks purchased. Atlanta-based Coca-Cola
USA said that percentage has since fallen to about 65 percent.
   Nonetheless, Michael Beindorff, vice president of advertising
for Coca-Cola, said a big block of men remains ``averse to diet
soft drinks.''
   He hopes to change that attitude with a campaign that begins
Monday, and will eventually feature players from every National
Football League team in local print and broadcast ads for diet Coke.
   The first commercial airs during the season's first Monday Night
Football telecast on ABC matching the Washington Redskins and the
New York Giants.
   In the ad, Redskins linemen Charles Mann and Dave Butz toss a
quarterback rather than a coin to decide who gets the last Diet
Coke during practice.
   Additional ads will appear locally during the season. In some
cases, players will appear in versions of an ad adapted for local
use.
   For instance, Beindorff said one local ad will show three
players from a team with a tiger, a bear or some other team symbol.
   As the camera pans over them, the announcer will say ``three out
of four (Bengals or Bears or whatever) prefer'' Diet Coke.
   Jesse Meyers, publisher of Beverage Digest, a trade publication
based in Greenwich, Conn., said soft drink sales rose about 4
percent last year to $40 billion, but that the diet segment has
been growing four to five times faster.
   His 1987 beverage rankings listed Diet Coke as the third best
selling soft drink behind Coca-Cola Classic and Pepsi with 7.7
percent of the market, and Diet Pepsi fourth with 4.8 percent.
   Meyers gives Pepsi ``high marks for clearly identifying the male
image'' with its ads that featured Tyson, who defended his
heavyweight title and said Diet Pepsi did too in taste tests
against Diet Coke.
   Beindorff said the new diet Coke ads were in development long
before the Tyson ads ran. While he would not disclose how much they
cost, he said the fees for all the football players will come to
only a fraction of the $1.25 million he said Pepsi reportedly paid
Tyson.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880902-0280 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-02-88 1714EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-WallStreet 1stLd-Writethru   09-02 0484</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Wall Street, 1st Ld-Writethru,0504</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates with closing prices throughout.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CHET CURRIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market rolled up its sharpest gain in
more than three months Friday, inspired by new statistics on
employment that suggested a slowing of economic growth.
   Falling interest rates in an enthusiastic bond market helped to
keep the rally going.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials jumped 52.28 to 2,054.59
for its biggest one-day advance since it rose 74.68 points on May
31. The average finished the week with a net gain of 37.16 points.
   Advancing issues outnumbered declines by about 4 to 1 in
nationwide trading of New York Stock Exchange-listed stocks, with
1,197 up, 296 down and 439 unchanged.
   Volume on the floor of the Big Board came to 159.84 million
shares, up from 144.09 million in the previous session. Nationwide,
consolidated volume in NYSE-listed issues, including trades in
those stocks on regional exchanges and in the over-the-counter
market, totaled 183.57 million shares.
   Before the opening, the Labor Department reported that the
unemployment rate rose to 5.6 percent in August from 5.4 percent
the month before.
   In accompanying data that are watched especially closely on Wall
Street, the department reported smaller-than-expected increases in
payroll employment.
   The news was widely seen as evidence that economic growth was
slowing, reducing prospects for heightened inflationary pressures
and giving the Federal Reserve more leeway in its credit policy.
   The figures got a rousing welcome in the bond market. Prices of
long-term government bonds, which move in the opposite direction
from interest rates, climbed more than $20 for each $1,000 in face
value.
   Analysts said it was also a healthy sign that stock trading
volume stepped up to its highest level in more than two weeks, even
with many traders presumably getting an early start on the long
Labor Day weekend.
   All 30 of the stocks that make up the Dow Jones industrial
average posted gains.
   Among actively traded blue chips, American Express gained 1\ to
29[; International Business Machines 3} to 114; Exxon 1 to 46~;
General Electric 1 to 40~, and American Telephone & Telegraph | to
25.
   Redman Industries jumped 1} to 10. The company said it agreed to
be acquired by an investor group for $10 a share.
   Nantucket Industries, traded on the American Stock Exchange,
rose 2 to 8]. Integrated Resources made an $8.50-a-share offer for
the company.
   As measured by Wilshire Associates' index of more than 5,000
actively traded stocks, the market increased $47.60 billion, or
1.84 percent, in value.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks
gained 2.98 to 149.66.
   Standard & Poor's industrial index rose 7.00 to 303.35, and
S&P's 500-stock composite index was up 6.13 at 264.48.
   The NASDAQ composite index for the over-the-counter market added
3.55 to 376.51. At the Amex, the market value index closed at
295.62, up 2.44.
</TEXT>
