<2ND_LINE>AM-Markets, 1st Ld-Writethru,0633</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Stocks, Bonds Rally After Report Of Higher Jobless Rate</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Unemployment, Bjt</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 6th graf, The Treasury's ..., with 2 grafs to say
overall bond market had biggest rally of 1988; picks up 7th graf
pvs, Late in ....</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A report that more Americans were out of work
triggered a powerful rally on Wall Street Friday as investors
figured a slowdown meant less inflation and lower interest rates.
   The government's report of a rise in the civilian jobless rate
to 5.6 percent in August helped calm a market that has been worried
for months that the economy was growing too quickly and might go
into an inflationary spiral.
   ``It's bad news, I guess, for job searchers, but it's not
necessarily bad news for consumers in general,'' said George
Iwanicki, an associate economist for Kidder, Peabody & Co.
   Stock prices leaped and the Dow Jones average of 30 industrial
stocks rose 52.28 points to 2,054.59, its biggest rise since a
74.68-point gain on May 31.
   The rise of more than 50 points triggered a restriction on
member firms' use of computers for a form of program trading. The
collar is designed to avoid chaotic swings in stock prices.
   Friday's rally began in the bond market, which staged its
biggest rally since Oct. 22, the aftermath of the stock market
crash, according to an index of all outstanding Treasury issues
maintained by Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc.
   The Treasury's closely watched 30-year bond staged its
second-biggest rally of the year. The price of the Treasury's
30-year bond briefly rose almost $30 for every $1,000 in face value.
   Late in the day, the long bond's price was up about $25.90,
driving its yield down to 9.04 from 9.30 percent late Thursday. The
only bigger rally of 1988 was a $26.25 price increase on Jan. 15,
after the government reported a big drop in the trade deficit.
   The bond market is highly sensitive to inflation and takes
weaker growth as good news. When bond prices rose, investors moved
to the stock market in search of bargains.
   For stock investors, the higher jobless rate was good news
because it seemed to lessen the likelihood that the economy was in
the late stages of an inflationary boom that would end up with a
bust, said David Bennett, a market analyst at Prudential-Bache
Securities Inc.
   In the long run, a slight increase in joblessness could mean
more stable, prolonged growth, Bennett said.
   In spite of the uptick in the jobless rate, from 5.4 percent in
July and a 14-year low of 5.3 percent in May, the economy continues
to be expanding and the nation is not far from full employment,
Iwanicki said.
   ``Fundamentally, the economy is quite strong,'' said Helen
Hotchkiss, a senior economist at Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc.
   Analysts said the slight increase in the jobless rate eases
pressure on the Federal Reserve to raise interest rates to cool
down the economy. In particular, it reduces the probability that
the central bank will move before the election to raise its
discount rate, which it charges on loans to banks.
   The number of jobless Americans grew by 226,000 in August and a
four-month hiring boom in the nation's factories ended abruptly,
the government said.
   A separate survey of business payrolls showed employers adding
219,000 new jobs in August, compared with average monthly gains of
more than 325,000 the previous three months.
   Despite the increase in the unemployment rate, the Labor
Department said a record 62.3 percent of the working-age population
16 and over held jobs in August.
   Average hourly wages for non-supervisory workers held steady at
$9.24.
</TEXT>
