<1ST_LINE>r f AM-AutoRecalls     09-02 0170</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Auto Recalls,0175</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ford Recalls 18,000 Cars Flunking California Smog Tests</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ford Motor Co. will recall 18,000 1984 Tempo and
Topaz cars and spend up to $8.1 million on anti-smog repairs to
meet California emissions standards, the California Air Resources
Board said Friday.
   In a news release, the regulatory board said Ford will be
sending notices through October to owners of 1984 Tempo and Topaz
models sold in California with 2.3 liter engines, offering free
repairs.
   Dealerships will adjust air injection systems and install larger
catalytic converters, at a cost to the manufacturer of about $450 a
vehicle.
   The Air Resources Board said that in tests of vehicles driven by
California motorists, the cars exceeded allowable limits of
smog-forming hydrocarbons and oxides of nitrogen and emitted more
than twice the allowable amount of carbon dioxide.
   California and federal regulations require cars to meet
emissions standards for five years or 50,000 miles, and California
law requires manufacturers to repair emissions control system
defects free during that period.
</TEXT>
