<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Bonds     09-02 0709</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bonds,0734</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Repeating For All Needing</HEAD>
<HEAD>Bond Market Posts Biggest Gain Of Year</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Buisiness Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Treasury bond market posted its biggest gain
of the year and interest rates tumbled Friday as a new report on
employment in August indicated the pace of economic growth may be
slowing.
   The report defused concerns, at least for the time being, that
the economy may be growing so fast that it could ignite inflation,
which eats away at the value of fixed-income investments such as
Treasury notes and bonds.
   Slower growth is a plus for bond prices because credit demands
and price pressures are usually lower in such periods and interest
rates can fall.
   The Shearson Lehman Daily Treasury Bond Index, which measures
price movements on all outstanding Treasury issues with maturities
of a year or longer, climbed 12.24 points to 1,142.50.
   That was the biggest rise since a 15.00-point advance on Oct.
22, 1987 when the Federal Reserve was standing ready to provide
liquidity to the financial system in the wake of the stock market
crash. The biggest rise in the composite index this year had
previously been a 12.05-point increase on Jan. 15.
   The Treasury's 30-year bond climbed nearly 2| points, or about
$26 for every $1,000 in face amount. That was slightly below the
$26.25 rise on Jan. 15, when the market was cheered by a narrowing
of the nation's trade deficit.
   Its yield, which moves in the opposite direction from its price,
skidded to 9.04 percent from 9.30 percent late Thursday. That was
its lowest since it finished at 9.03 percent on Aug. 4.
   The bond rally was sparked by the government's report that the
nation's unemployment rate rose to 5.6 percent in August from 5.4
percent in July.
   A companion report on business payrolls said there were 219,000
new jobs in August, and revised downward the payroll growth
previously reported for July. In addition, the report indicated a
decline in hours worked and only a slight increase in average
hourly earnings index for August.
   William V. Sullivan Jr., director of money market research for
Dean Witter Reynolds Inc., said the report ``allays the market's
fears that the economy was moving into an overheated phase.''
   He said the pace of trading was moderate, a pickup from the slow
pace that has preceded release of the report.
   Elliott Platt, director of fixed-income research at Donaldson
Lufkin & Jenrette Securities Corp., said, ``It was one of the most
broadly-based, good reports we have seen in a long time.''
   Sung Won Sohn, chief economist for Norwest Corp. in Minneapolis,
said the report means ``there is virtually no chance that the Fed
will tighten in the near future'' since the economy appears weaker
than some presumed it was.
   Platt said the report may mark a turning point for trends in
longterm rates, but Sohn said he expects rates will head higher
later this year.
   In the secondary market for Treasury bonds, prices of short-term
government issues rose by between { point and } point, intermediate
maturities were up by between a full point and 1{ points and
20-year issues were up 2{ points, according to Telerate Inc., a
financial information service.
   The movement of a point is equivalent to a change of $10 in the
price of a bond with a $1,000 face value.
   In corporate trading, prices rose. Moody's Investment Grade
Corporate Bond Index, which measures price movements on 80
corporate bonds with maturities of five years or longer, rose 3.34
to 287.76.
   Yields on three-month Treasury bills, meanwhile, fell to 7.42
percent as the discount fell 8 basis points to 7.20 percent. Yields
on six-month bills fell to 7.78 percent as the discount fell 8
basis points to 7.40 percent. Yields on one-year bills fell to 8.04
percent as the discount fell 16 basis points to 7.50 percent.
   A basis point is one-hundredth of a percentage point. The yield
is the annualized return on an investment in a Treasury bill. The
discount is the percentage that bills are selling below the face
value, which is paid at maturity.
   The federal funds rate, the interest on overnight loans between
banks, was quoted at 8 3-16 percent, down from 8\ percent late
Thursday.
</TEXT>
