<1ST_LINE>r f AM-NYSE-Specialists     09-02 0495</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-NYSE-Specialists,0509</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Big Board Reallocates Four Stocks in Disciplinary Move</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICK GLADSTONE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The New York Stock Exchange said Friday that it
has removed the rights of two specialist firms to make markets in
four stocks following inquiries into their conduct during the
October crash and its aftermath.
   The disciplinary move by the nation's biggest stock market
against the firms, Stern & Kennedy and Spear, Leeds & Kellogg,
brought to 11 the number of stocks that have been reallocated from
NYSE specialists because of probes into how well they handled the
panicky buying and selling during the crash.
   In the NYSE system for stock trading, 54 specialist firms
control the rights to market certain stocks and are required to
keep order by setting opening prices and covering trades using
their own money when there are too few buyers or sellers.
   Specialist monopoly rights on stocks are considered extremely
valuable because the firms get the great majority of business in
those stocks. Removal of those rights by the NYSE is considered a
significant punitive measure.
   The NYSE said after the crash that it would investigate several
cases in which the specialists failed to maintain orderly trading
in stocks they controlled. NYSE spokeswoman Sharon Gamsin said the
announcement Friday marked the conclusion of those investigations.
   As is NYSE policy, she declined to elaborate on what the
specialists did or failed to do. But she reiterated the Big Board's
position that ``we think the specialists did an excellent, though
obviously not perfect job.''
   Carl Hewitt, a staff attorney at Spear, Leeds & Kellogg, said
the firm would have no comment on the NYSE's action. A receptionist
who answered the telephone at Stern & Kennedy's office said nobody
was available to comment.
   A brief NYSE press statement said the exchange would reallocate
Stern & Kennedy's rights in Loctite Corp.'s stock following a
review of the specialist firm's actions on Black Monday, Oct. 19.
   The statement said Spear, Leeds & Kellog's specialist rights
were removed from Alleghany Corp. and Greyhound Corp. because of
the firm's performance on Oct. 20; and its specialist rights were
moved from Kysor Industrial Corp. because of the firm's Oct. 22
performance.
   ``After discussions with the NYSE, Stern & Kennedy and Spear,
Leeds & Kellogg agreed voluntarily to withdraw as the specialist in
each of the stocks,'' the statement said.
   An NYSE committee that assigns stocks to specialists was
accepting applications from other firms that want to make markets
in the four stocks and will likely announce its decision next week,
Ms. Gamsin said.
   For Spear, Leeds & Kellogg, one of the biggest NYSE specialist
firms, it was the second reallocation resulting from post-crash
inquiries. Previously, the firm surrendered its franchise in J.P.
Morgan & Co.'s stock.
   In addition, the specialist firms Wagner, Stott & Co., M.J.
Meehan & Co. Lawrence, O'Donnell & Co., and LaBranche & Co. have
relinquished market-making rights in some stocks since the crash.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
