<FILEID>AP-NR-09-02-88 1844EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-GroceryMerger Bjt   09-02 0485</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Grocery Merger, Bjt,0499</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>California Says Market Merger Would Cost Consumers Millions</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Stands for AM-Lucky-American listed on the digest</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SUE MANNING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The purchase of Lucky markets by American
Stores Co. should be stopped because it would cost California
consumers millions of dollars a year in higher food prices, the
state attorney general said Friday.
   Attorney General John Van de Kamp filed suit in U.S. District
Court here late Thursday, seeking to block the $2.5 billion
purchase of Lucky Stores Inc. by American Stores, which runs the
supermarket Alpha Beta.
   Van de Kamp said a merger of the two companies would violate
state antitrust laws.
   The deal, and the unrelated purchase of 172 Safeway stores in
southern California by the Vons Cos., had been approved by the
Federal Trade Commission, which analyzes the effect of business
combinations on competition and prices.
   But Van de Kamp, standing in an alley beside one of American's
Alpha Beta markets in the predominantly Hispanic Westlake district,
accused the FTC of failing to protect the interests of California
consumers.
   ``This injustice will strike most cruelly at those least able to
afford it _ the poor, the elderly, the least mobile of our
citizens, those who cannot afford high prices and who cannot flee
their neighborhood market for distant lower prices,'' Van de Kamp
said.
   American has said the deal would result in lower prices because
of the efficiency of a larger operation.
   Van de Kamp sought a temporary court order blocking the
American-Lucky combination until a trial, but U.S. District Judge
David V. Kenyon delayed a decision until Tuesday so he could study
the case.
   Meanwhile, Van de Kamp's staff continued to negotiate with Vons
on a settlement of similar allegations about the El Monte-based
grocery chain's $408 million purchase of 172 Safeway stores in
Southern California. Vons already has started converting the stores.
   Van de Kamp said the talks appeared to be making progress, but
warned he would take Vons to court immediately if the negotiations
broke down.
   American, which recently moved its corporate headquarters from
Salt Lake City to Irvine, Calif., is one of the nation's largest
supermarket companies. Its holdings include Acme markets on the
East Coast, Skaggs Alpha Beta, Alpha Beta and Buttery in the West
and the 27-state Osco drug chain.
   The transactions would give the combined Alpha Beta-Lucky chain
550 stores and Vons 350 stores, with the two chains together owning
half the supermarkets in the state.
   In opposing the California mergers, Van de Kamp cited a study
commissioned by his office that found the combination of American's
Alpha Beta with Lucky and the Safeway-Vons deal would increase food
prices by $400 million a year in the state.
   As a condition of its approval, the FTC required American to
sell 37 markets to competing chains to maintain competition. Vons
was required to sell 12 stores.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
